<HEAD>Bush and Bhutto Seek Political Solution To Afghanistan Stalemate</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS grafs 18-20: ``In an,'' with Mrs. Bhuotto's nuclear
remarks in interview report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday told visiting Pakistani Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is willing `` to explore any serious avenue'' to achieve a political solution in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> in turn said after private talks with the president that `` we are in complete accord'' on the situation in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, stalemated since the pullout of the last Soviet troops in February. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the withdrawal of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> proved the effectiveness of <LOCATION> U.S-Pakistani </LOCATION> support for the Afghan resistance fighting the Marxist regime in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> shares a common border with <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` We agreed, however, that the job is not done,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> continues and their struggle for self-determination goes on.'' `` Prime Minister <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and I discussed ways to encourage a political solution in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> that will lead to a non-aligned, representative government willing to live in peace with its neighbors, to replace the illegitimate regime in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will continue to explore any serious avenue towards this end.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials had anticipated a rapid demise for the government of <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON> after the Soviet pullout, but it has not happened. Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> said she and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` have reviewed the situation in the light of the prevailing circumstances and we are in complete accord'' on what needs to be done. `` <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> remains committed to a political solution of the Afghan problem, whereby the brave people of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> will have the right to freely choose their own government without interference from outside,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, the daughter of former Prime Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, said that while the Soviet pullout `` has brought a welcome change in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the continued fighting and prolonged presence of over 3.5 million Afghan refugees pose serious threats to the peace and stability of the region.'' After a full-dress military ceremony on the White House lawn, including a 19-gun salute, and an Oval Office meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> went to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for a meeting with Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and a lunch in her honor. At a state dinner Tuesday evening, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> joked during the exchange of toasts that Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> had `` refused my latest offer. She's not going double or nothing on this year's Harvard-Yale game.'' Keeping up the Ivy League banter, Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> responded: `` Ladies and gentlemen, I studied at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and believe me, I did n't know until tonight that <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> ever produced charming men. I'm glad I met the only one.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> is a 1973 <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> graduate; <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is a 1948 graduate of arch-rival <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has a standing request to buy 60 more F-16 fighter jets from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> brushed aside reporters' attempts to ask about reports that approval of the jet sale is imminent. An administration official, briefing reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> discussed the F-16 sale, but `` I would n't anticipate any specific announcement from outside'' during her visit. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, indicated there were no stumbling blocks to the sale, but normal steps such as congressional notification would take more time. On another topic, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> `` assured me that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s nuclear program is committed to peaceful purposes.'' He said he underlined his commitment `` to discourage proliferation of nuclear and chemical weapons, ballistic missiles, in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> region and around the world.'' In an interview with editors of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> said she had `` very frank talk'' with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, and assured them <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> does not intend to build nuclear weapons. She said she wanted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to help <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> reach a nuclear test-ban treay with `` other countries in the region,'' an apparent reference to long-ti8me rival <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, according to a report on the interview in Wednesday editions. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> exploded what it called a nuclear `` device'' in 1974. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> last month said <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> `` clearly'' was developing nuclear capability and Indian appeared interested in developing thermonculear weapons. The two leaders also discussed efforts to combat drug production and trafficking. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he `` applauded her tough stance on eradicating the opium cultivation'' and thanked her for extraditing an alleged drug trafficker. The two countries were expected to sign agreements on housing, narcotics and education this week during <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s stay. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the third largest recipient of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid, is slated for $ 380 million in economic assistance and $ 240 million in military aid next year. Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s father was deposed by Gen. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> in 1977 and hanged two years later for a political murder. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> remained in power until perishing in a mysterious plane crash last year that also claimed the life of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphel </PERSON> and an American general. Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who had picked up her father's fallen standard and been jailed for a time under <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>, led her <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to victory as head of a coalition government last November. Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> was scheduled to address a joint session of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. She also had stops here at the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. She will receive an honorary degree at her alma mater, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, on Thursday and visit the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. She departs for home Saturday evening.
