<HEAD>Seven People Named for Knight-Bagehot Fellowships</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A longer version on financial wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION> announced the seven people selected as 1989-90 Knight-Bagehot Fellows in Economics and Business Journalism. The fellowships are designed to provide formal business and economics training for journalists at mid-career. Fellows spend an academic year attending classes at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s schools of business, law and international affairs. The 1989-90 fellows are: <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bureau chief for <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Copetas </PERSON>, national correspondent for <PERSON> Regardie </PERSON>'s magazine in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Corman </PERSON>, international trade reporter for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietrich </PERSON>, a producer for <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Also named Tuesday were <PERSON> Micheline </PERSON> <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> bureau chief for <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Hannah </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, a correspondent for the <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Talib </PERSON>, news editor of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Straits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. The fellowships are funded by an endowment from the <ORGANIZATION> Knight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and by grants from a number of foundations and corporations including the <ORGANIZATION> Olin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Fund </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The fellowships are named after <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>, a Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist and businessman, and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagehot </PERSON>, a 19th-century economist and editor of the Economist magazine.
