<SECOND>PM-Khomeini's Son, Bjt,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Son Emerges From Shadows, But Power May Elude Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has emerged from the long shadow of his father and appears to be making a bid for power himself, a move some analysts believe is doomed to fail. He was making his moves even before <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> died Saturday. But the death of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s revolutionary and spiritual patriarch, before the leadership issue could be settled, has added urgency to the son's campaign. `` A lot of emotions are rampant in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> now,'' <PERSON> Shahram </PERSON> <PERSON> Chubin </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> specialist with the <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview. `` Some people will be trying to take advantage of that and <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> is one of them.'' The Assembly of Experts, the body formed in 1979 to ensure a smooth transition after <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death, on Sunday named President <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> as a caretaker leader until the succession is resolved. In the meantime, rivals in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> are jockeying for power. Although <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> is only a middle-ranking cleric, or hojatoleslam, and holds no official title, he was one of his father's closest advisers. As <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s private secretary, he controlled access to the reclusive patriarch and wielded considerable influence behind the scenes. The younger <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, 43, took an increasingly high public profile as his father's health declined. He has allied himself with radical figures in the hierarchy in the power struggle that has intensified since the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Speculation rose that he sought to establish himself as his father's political heir by engineering the March 28 dismissal of his father's designated successor, <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein-Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> was his father's eyes and ears since their days in exile and through the Islamic revolution that toppled the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>. Last month, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> newspapers published lengthy excerpts of a 110-page memorandum <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> wrote to <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON>, lashing him for seeking to undermine <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s regime and consorting with opposition groups. The document appeared to be aimed at publicly projecting <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> as a candidate to inherit his father's mantle. <PERSON> Masoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajavi </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION>, or People's Holy Warriors, the main Iranian opposition movement, says <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> was grooming <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> as his successor. <PERSON> Rajavi </PERSON> said in a statement that <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s dismissal of <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON> for criticizing the regime `` prepared the ground for this appointment.'' He argued that <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s appointment of a special committee to amend the constitution, including downgrading the religious qualifications of his successor from `` divinely inspired authority'' was aimed at making room for <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>. But analysts believe the black-bearded <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> could eventually become a political casualty now that his father is dead. They believe that bereft of the ayatollah's authority, and with no secure power base of his own, <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>'s influence could evaporate. `` As <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s health deteriorated, he was able to control his father's statements and this gave him some authority,'' <PERSON> Chubin </PERSON> said. `` But it would be rather difficult for him to be the keeper of the flame now that <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has gone. <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> has neither the religious credentials nor the administrative experience to rule and it's not clear whether claiming dynastic credentials will be enough. `` He could become a pawn in the power struggle, a front man for more powerful people following his father's death.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> specialist <PERSON> Shireen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview: `` I do n't think he'll emerge as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s strongman. `` His power is really quite vicarious, stemming primarily from his position as his father's gatekeeper. I do n't believe he can fill his father's shoes.'' With 40 days of mourning declared for <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has been engulfed by a wave of emotion for its dead leader, a development <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> could exploit to advance his political ambitions. But Ms. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> cautioned: `` Using <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s name could be a double-edged sword. There was already a backlash against <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> and that in the end could work against <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>. The revolution is against dynasties. `` He could well become a major player ... but he's not a person of great convictions and he'll have to associate himself with one group or another to stay in play.'' From the outside, the political maneuverings in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> are often opaque. But last August, <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> was seen as a member of an unofficial troika with <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, both so-called `` pragmatists,'' who had effectively taken over day-to-day control as <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s health failed. Now he's aligned with the radicals led by Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>, Prosecutor-General <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> <PERSON> Khoeiniha </PERSON>, Intelligence Minister <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Rey-Shahri </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Tavasoli </PERSON>, a powerful behind-the-scenes figure in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. Some analysts believe <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> could swing back to <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> again if he sees him gaining ground. But for now he's lined up against <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who was earlier outflanked by the radicals in the fundamentalist resurgence decreed by his father in February. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s shrewdest politicians, appears to be maneuvering his way back and could well come out on top again, as he has done many times before. There is speculation <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> will run in presidential elections scheduled for Aug. 18. So far the only announced candidate is the formidable <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who won the highest ballot in last year's parliamentary elections with more than 1.3 million votes.
