<FIRST>r i PM-AIDS Bjt   06-07 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Predict More Widespread AIDS Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health official says the time is coming when doctors will report the names of people testing positive for the AIDS virus and try to trace victims' sexual contacts. But activists criticized the proposal. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Assistant Secretary for Health, said he did n't know when such a system would be in place, but when it happens `` we will have normalized HIV and will handle it like syphilis.'' HIV, or human immunodeficiency virus, causes AIDS. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s remarks Tuesday at the Fifth International Conference on AIDS drew immediate criticism. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON>, executive director of the Gay Men's Health Crisis in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, opposed the proposal because he feared names would not be kept confidential and that people known to be infected would suffer from the stigma associated with acquired immune deficiency syndrome. `` People lose their jobs, their housing and their schooling opportunities,'' he said. `` That's not like other diseases.'' Furthermore, he said, tracing patients' sexual contacts will not work for AIDS as it does with syphilis because HIV patients may have been infected for years when they are diagnosed. Tracing partners so far back is unlikely, he said. The consequences of reporting would discourage many people from submitting to testing, <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON> said. `` The only way people are going to come forward is if there's something effective'' to help them, he said. The Gay Men's Health Crisis received numerous calls Tuesday from people who were already concerned that their names might be recorded if they seek testing. Dr. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> health commissioner, floated a similar proposal at the AIDS meeting Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has directed the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to prepare a report on discrimination against people with AIDS and HIV infection, <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said, in anticipation of moves toward reporting the names of those tested. He said early identification of infected people through contact tracing could allow them to be treated promptly with new drugs now being tested. The cost of such treatment would run into the billions of dollars, <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said. He did not know where that money might come from. In other conference reports: _ Researchers said initial studies on a new AIDS drug called CD4 showed that the medicine is safe and may reduce levels of HIV in the body. The drug is a decoy intended to confuse the virus and draw it away from the blood cells it ordinarily infects. In expeimental use on 18 people, Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Yarchoan </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> found that the drug appeared to lower virus levels in the body by about 50 percent. However, he cautioned that this could have been a natural fluctuation instead of a result of the drug. Another team found no clear evidence of virus reduction, but researchers said they were still encouraged by the drug's potential and said higher doses could have a greater effect. _ In a report scheduled for presentation today, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reserachers said a recently discovered herpes virus may accelerate the development of AIDS in people infected with HIV Dr. <PERSON> Paulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusso </PERSON> said the virus, called HHV-6, enhanced the growth of HIV in test tube, causing more cells to die more quickly. More than half of Americans, Canadians and Europeans have been exposed to HHV-6 without any ill effects and may be capable of passing it on, studies have shown. _ Researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> said it was now possible to predict two years in advance which patients infected with HIV will develop AIDS Studies suggest that a majority of people infected with the virus get AIDS or related illnesses. A similar study by researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, found that a combination of five laboratory tests can predict which patients will develop AIDS during a four-year period.
