<HEAD>Political Blood Lust Still in Evidence on Republican Right</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the House Republican leader warned his <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> colleagues against a French Revolution mentality in which `` evil Democrats'' are hauled to the guillotine, some began humming the French national anthem. The incident at a party meeting Tuesday illustrates the political blood lust that persists in a chamber fractured by months of ethics charges and countercharges, and the uphill fight new House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> will have in trying to restore order. `` The task I see for myself is to create the environment where ... debate can take place without recriminations, without the kind of angry, hostile feelings between members'' that have dominated the House of late, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> told reporters. `` This tension which has built up over a period of many months is going to require a little time to turn around,'' he said. `` It's not going to be done in a day. ... But I believe it will happen.'' Some Democrats, stung by the sacrifice of former speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> in the ethics storm, have turned their sights on Rep. <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, R-Ga., who filed the original ethics charges against <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> An ethics investigation of <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>'s book-promotion deal could begin as early as Thursday. Of the ethics committee and <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, Rep. <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Slaughter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said: `` I want them to treat him fairly, but I certainly want them to treat him.'' The political knives remained out in the Republican camp, as well. <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> political operatives were searching financial disclosure reports for possible ethical shortcomings of Democrats, and <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> spoke of new ethics cases yet to be filed against members of the majority party. Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mich