<HEAD>Questions Raised About Company's Subsidies, Ties to Fugitive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing a grain company's possible links to a fugitive commodities trader in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and its receipt of at least $ 65 million in government export subsidies. At issue are the company's ties to <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>, who fled to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> in 1983 before his indictment for criminal tax evasion, racketeering, mail and wire fraud. A department official confirmed Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> was examining <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a Swiss-based company with an office in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and payments it received through the Export Enhancement Program, known as EEP. The review was started at the request of the chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., who raised questions about the company at a hearing earlier this year and on Tuesday asked the agency for a full investigation <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, in a letter to the agency, said `` an unmistakable line of ownership, control and profit runs from'' <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> through a series of subsidiary arrangements. `` While I am disturbed that a company whose main operations lie outside of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can establish but a nominal onshore presence and qualify to receive <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> bonuses, as appears to be the case with <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION>, I am truly shocked that a fugitive from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> justice can benefit from a program funded by taxpayer dollars,'' <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> said in his letter to Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. Under the Export Enhancement Program, private exporters can sell <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities at lower prices to meet foreign competition and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON>, under secretary for international affairs and commodity programs, said <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> had started `` checking through what the connections are'' between <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>. He declined to provide any details on the findings so far. An official of <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Church </PERSON>, declined to comment about the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> review and would not provide any information about the company. <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> asked that <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s Office of Inspector General determine whether <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> qualified for the export subsidy program and whether department eligibility guidelines need to be changed to close any possible loopholes used by <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> has the same telephone number as <ORGANIZATION> Clarendon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Marc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. A.G. of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> <PERSON> Clarendon </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> company settled a federal tax evasion case in 1984 by pleading guilty and agreeing to pay more than $ 200 million in back taxes, fines and other penalties. Criminal charges against <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> were unaffected by the settlement. The government alleged that <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> and his commodity-trading empire cheated the government out of millions of dollars in taxes through a series of illegal oil transactions among Rich-controlled companies. <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> has received at least $ 65 million worth of subsidies through <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, ranking it ninth among grain exporters in the program, according to information supplied to a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>. Most recently, <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> picked up estimated subsidies of $ 250,000 for a wheat sale to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Last month, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> approved use of the subsidy program for the sale of 1.5 million tons of wheat to the Soviets. <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> handled at least 30,000 tons of the initial part of the wheat deal. Subsidies averaged $ 8.46 per ton for <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> and four other companies, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, who met Tuesday with <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> might need to pass legislation disqualifying <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> from the export program unless <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> administratively barred it from receiving more subsidies. `` The export enhancement program has undergone some criticism anyway. It would be a shame to jeopardize its future because we're providing bonus commodities to a tax fugitive,'' said <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> `` This is a guy of renowned international bad dealings.''
