<HEAD>NRA Tries to Counter Police Endorsements of Gun Bans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While several police organizations are urging <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to approve strict controls on semiautomatic assault-style weapons, some 225 officers gathered on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> to say those groups do n't speak for them. `` The average policeman in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> right now is extremely upset with the misrepresentations,'' said Patrolman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aveni </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who asked that his department be identified only as being in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The notion that policemen favor `` gun bans as a solution to violent crime'' is wrong, said <PERSON> Aveni </PERSON>, who recently organized a group called Law Enforcement for the Preservation of the Second Amendment, which guarantees the right to keep and bear arms. `` The majority of us have taken an oath to uphold the Constitution,'' he said in an interview. `` The Second Amendment's the cornerstone of the Constitution If the Second Amendment goes, there's no guarantee that the rest of the Constitution will remain intact. ... Without arms, people are powerless to dissent against any kind of tyranny or repression of government.'' <PERSON> Aveni </PERSON> was one of the 225 officers flown to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to participate in a news conference Tuesday and lobby their respective congressmen and senators. The only state not represented by an officer was <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. They were here to combat the impact of gun-control endorsements by law enforcement officials such as <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Daryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Behan </PERSON>, who are pushing for controls on assault-style weapons including semiautomatic versions of the AK-47 and Uzi. Law enforcement groups that have taken similar stands include the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraternal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Order </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION> and the Police Executive Research Forum. `` For thousands of us out there that the chiefs, the appointed officials, do not speak for the law enforcement officers that are in the field, in the trenches, doing the job,'' said <PERSON> Patrolman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Maples </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Memphis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, counsel to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraternal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Order </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, countered that his organization speaks for 200,000 of those officers, not for their bosses. `` The Fraternal Order of Police does speak for the cop on the street,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` There are no chiefs, there are no sheriffs. They do n't speak for anyone except for the cops on the beat.'' The contention by some law enforcement leaders that their officers are being `` outgunned'' by criminals wielding assault-style weapons `` offends me,'' Officer <PERSON> Leroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said at the news conference. <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, Officer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Steiner </PERSON> said criminals have better firearms because they're making more money these days. `` Unfortunately, police departments have for many years been forced to look at the bottom line in terms of low bid, and that applies to our safety equipment in particular,'' <PERSON> Steiner </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> Police Lt. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said many of the officers attending were `` under direct orders from their police chiefs to disassociate themselves from their respective police departments'' in their comments. `` The remarks that are made here should not be construed as the official policy of our respective police departments,'' he said.
