<HEAD>The Folks in `The People's House' Go Ceremonial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> loves to call itself `` The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'' and its members like to act like folks On high state occasions, like Tuesday's, when the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> installed a new speaker, it has to go ceremonial but it could n't quite shed its old-shoe habits. When <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> had been duly elected, the doorkeeper bellowed out, just as he does on State of the Union night, `` Mister Speaker!,'' introducing new Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> to departing Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. And <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> marched the route of presidents: down the central aisle, accompanied by an escorting committee, shaking hands all round. But still, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is the House. So some members brought their children to work, to be there for the history of it all, and plunked them on the plush brown leather seats. Six of the kids sat in one row. One tried to figure out how his white sailor hat could be made to fit his knee. Another tried out his sunglasses against the bright lights. When the adults stood and applauded, so did the kids. To old timers in the galleries, the moment brought to mind another occasion when a popular product of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> stood before the chamber at the climax of a tense national drama. That was 1974, when <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leader, arrived as president, having succeeded <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, a chief executive who resigned in disgrace, largely due to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s own impeachment process `` Mister Speaker!'' the doorkeeper bellowed then, too, but <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> showed the members that he was still a man of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with a corny line; he was, he said, the same old guy: `` I am a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, not a Lincoln.'' The ethical troubles which compelled <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to resign as speaker were no Watergate, but within the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, an insular body, the trauma was almost comparable. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> had no catchy line like <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s but he called up some numbers to deal with something <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and others had been saying about the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ that it has become a self-perpetuating body. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, just before leaving office, noted that 98 percent of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members who ran for re-election won and concluded it was easier to be re-elected to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> than to the Supreme Soviet. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s answer: `` Only 7 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s current members were in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> when I was first elected in 1964. Eight-one percent of the current members have been elected since 1974. More than half of the current members _ 55 percent _ have been elected since 1980. The constant change in membership is a source of great strength for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but fundamentally, and more importantly, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> reflects the will of the electorate.'' <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> had another comparison. He contrasted the transfer of power here with the awkward reaching toward democratic formulas in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and the bloody events in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. He said congressmen can be proud that the values which have sustained the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> `` now sweep around the world.'' `` We are,'' he said, using that phrase again, `` proud to call this the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the fundamental institution of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> democracy.''
