<HEAD>Panel Told of Failures to Protect Elderly From Financial Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is not doing enough to keep the elderly from being ripped off by people appointed to handle their Social Security checks, senators said after being told of abuses. An <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> woman and a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> woman misused <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> payments that they had been entrusted to manage on behalf of elderly beneficiaries, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging was told Tuesday at a hearing. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, testified that she was told by the government that she needed a representative to handle her disability benefits because she was incapable of managing the money herself. But she said the woman who was appointed kept some of the benefits for herself, and had a history of writing bad checks. She did not identify the appointee. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of <PERSON> Marvell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, told the panel that her representative collected her disability benefits, but then refused to use the money to buy a telephone, clothes or other necessities that <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> requested. `` She often would not tell me how much money she would have of mine, or what was going on,'' she said. The system is so ripe for abuse that `` in some communities in our nation, private profiteers are virtually lining up at Social Security offices in the hope they can get their hands on a beneficiary's money by being appointed a payee,'' said <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Child </PERSON>, attorney for a legal services firm in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>. He called the government's oversight of the payee program `` lax.'' About 4.6 million Social Security beneficiaries have mental or physical impairments deemed serious enough that they need someone to manage their benefits. The <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> accepts applications from anyone who wants to be a payee, but gives preference to relatives or to public or private groups with good records in handling elderly affairs. But Sens. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., said the government has not been vigilant enough in overseeing the `` There is some evidence that <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> has not been keeping a close watch on those who apply to be representative payees,'' <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> said. `` Presently, the <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> does not do background checks, nor does the <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> monitor the program to ensure that the beneficiaries actually receive their money.'' <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Enoff </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> deputy commissioner, said the administration recognized there was a problem, and was evaluating steps to remedy it. He said the victims represent a small percentage of the beneficiarfies and are often poor or handicapped people without relatives to care for them. <PERSON> Enoff </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> verifies the identities of payee applicants, and asks them whether they have felony convictions. He said he was concerned about a bill introduced by <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> on Tuesday that would require <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> to conduct criminal background checks on applicants, while barring most creditors from becoming payees. A ban on creditors would be too stringent and would keep, for example, helpful landlords from becoming payees, <PERSON> Enoff </PERSON> said.
