<HEAD>U.N. Optimistic Sudanese Relief Supplies to Arrive in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials in charge of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s famine relief operation say an agreement between rebels and the government to allow safe transit of emergency supplies could help save up to 100,000 Sudanese lives. The delivery of food and other supplies _ before the rainy season cuts off access by dirt roads and airstrips _ is behind schedule but recent accords between guerrillas and the government improve the survival prospects for thousands, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, head of Operation Lifeline <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, said Tuesday. `` It's going to be a very difficult summer and fall, but I think at this stage, barring a collapse of the present sort of pattern of cooperation, I think we can say that the great majority of those 100,000 deaths that looked so likely in February and early March can be averted,'' the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said. More than 60,000 tons of food has already been delivered, and the relief operation is attempting to deliver another 20,000 to 40,000 tons before the heaviest rains hit in July and August, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. `` For the first time in history, there is, in the middle of a civil war, a plan of action agreed to by both parties with ` corridors of tranquility' for the passage of supplies,'' said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, who returned from observing the operation last week. The rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is fighting for more autonomy in the southern provinces, where the government generally controls only garrison towns. A railway route from central to southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> is now open, said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. One rail trip was completed in late May; another is set to begin Saturday, and two more runs are planned later this month. The first train, with over 100 cars, moved south through rebel and government-held areas, reaching war-weary <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> on May 28. `` At one government garrison where the train stopped overnight, the train was so long that the <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> was guarding the tail end of the train while the government was guarding the front of the train,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. The government and rebels have both agreed to respect the `` corridors of tranquility'' as long as necessary, said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. In addition, both parties have agreed to meet in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, on Saturday to open talks aimed at reaching a comprehensive truce. The <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> has also announced it is extending its monthlong unilateral cease-fire for another two weeks, said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. Although the rainy season has already begun, <ORGANIZATION> Operation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lifeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> has not yet lost the use of all dirt roads and airstrips, he said. Bulldozers have been able to keep open dirt roads linking <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> with southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> so truck convoys can pass, and the relief operation has been able to use lighter planes to land on rain-sodden dirt airstrips. However, a barge convoy planned for the <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nile </ORGANIZATION> between <LOCATION> Kosti </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malakal </LOCATION> has not yet been able to start, said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. Negotiations with the government, unions and barge crews are still under way. Despite that setback and other delays, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said he was `` more optimistic for the prospects for success than at any time in the past.'' The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> estimates 250,000 Sudanese died last year from starvation due to flood or drought, or war-induced famine.
