<SECOND>PM-Veal Dispute,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing Pits Animal Rights Groups, Veal Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chef of an exclusive <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> restaurant says veal producers who confine calves in small stalls and feed them no-iron formula to get pure white meat have a mistaken idea of what the best cooks want. `` As a chef, the quality of the veal used in my kitchen is very important, and yet of equal concern to me is the quality of life of these calves,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palladin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jean-Louis </LOCATION> restaurant at the Watergate Hotel, in support of legislation that would change the way veal is raised. <PERSON> Palladin </PERSON> was one of 34 witnesses Tuesday at a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee hearing in a debate over whether calves destined to become cuts of milk-fed veal ought to spend their short lives in a freer state consuming more than just liquid. The legislation pits animal rights advocates against government agriculture officials and most of the relatively small <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> veal industry. <PERSON> Palladin </PERSON> and others supporting the bill sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., said the rationale behind current practice is that the public wants pure white meat `` For me, the foremost concern is the taste, not the color of the meat,'' said <PERSON> Palladin </PERSON>. He said he thinks the confinement of calves in small crates can lead to weakness, illness and use of antibiotics in milk formulas, all of which affect the quality of the meat. But <PERSON> Wanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, who has been raising calves in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> since 1976, said `` disease problems were nothing short of horrifying'' when she and her husband tried letting the animals roam. `` We had no control over the amount of milk calves could drink at will. Weak calves were pushed aside. Navel sucking, ear sucking and urine drinking were common,'' she said. Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McGlone </PERSON>, associate professor of animal science at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said there is no scientific evidence that solid food is better for calves than a milk formula with nutrients. In answer to concerns about the lack of iron in calves' diets, <PERSON> McGlone </PERSON> said, `` Borderline anemia of veal calves does not cause serious health problems.'' He said many of those attacking the industry actually have a broader goal of ending all human consumption of meat. `` The veal industry is a small segment of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> agriculture,'' <PERSON> McGlone </PERSON> said. `` Because of its small size, it is a relatively easy target for advocate roups that seek to reduce or eliminate use of animals by humans.'' The <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> bill would require that calves be given solid food and iron, have physical contact with one another and be kept in larger enclosures. `` The crate system most commonly used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is so confining that the calves can not turn around or lie down comfortably,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` These normally playful animals are kept practically immobile, are prone to be unhealthy and lead a miserable existence,'' said <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Loew </PERSON>, dean of <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> school veterinary medicine, said veal stalls commonly are 22 to 24 inches wide and 60 inches long. He said calves average 239 pounds when they are slaughtered. Dr. <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plowman </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s agricultural research service, said about 1 million of the nearly 40 million cattle slaughtered each year are special-fed calves at the center of this controversy `` There is a general perception that calves are purposely made iron deficient or anemic to produce the desired coloration of the meat.'' said <PERSON> Plowman </PERSON>. `` This is not true.'' He said research shows that raising calves in elevated, individual stalls reduces disease and increases survival rates. When calves nuzzle each other, they pass along infections, he said.
