<HEAD>Third World Falling Behind on $70 Billion Owed US Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal auditing agency says Third World countries are falling behind on $ 70 billion in debt repayments to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks and that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> regulators should make banks put up more reserves to protect depositors against loan losses. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the auditing arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, did not name the debtor countries. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, the third largest debtor behind <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, has paid no interest on its foreign debt for more than one year and owes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks more than $ 8.5 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said regulators should demand that banks put up about 12 times more reserves against loan losses than is currently required. `` Because banks generally respond to reserve requirements by writing down assets by the required amounts, a decline in the book value of their assets results,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said in a note on figures it sent to Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFalce </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Though the auditors' report did not say so, writing down a bank's assets reduces the amount of business it can do and makes the management look bad to depositors and stockholders A bank is now only required to put up reserves when the regulators declare foreign loans it has made to be either a total loss or `` value-impaired.'' That means the debtors have not paid interest for six months or have shown in other ways that they are in deep trouble. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> regulators next week are expected to discuss behind closed doors whether to put loans to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> in the `` value-impaired'' pigeonhole. The list already contains <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>. But their total debt is small compared with the major debtors. In a letter Tuesday to <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> LaFalce </PERSON> joined in urging that the banks put up more reserves. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> takes the lead in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulation process. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks maintain lower reserve levels than almost all other industrialized countries,'' <PERSON> LaFalce </PERSON> wrote.
