<HEAD>Sub Designer Cites Risk of Construction Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A key contractor helping to design the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Seawolf nuclear attack submarine says development snags could delay completion of the first vessel The warning, issued last December by the <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> News </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Drydock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, complained of a lack of progress by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and another contractor, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, in developing the combat system of sensors and computers needed to operate the new sub's weaponry. <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> said the delays could mean the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> may not get the first completed sub in May 1995 as planned. `` Continuing delays in completion of the -LRB- combat system -RRB- design or the emergence of significant changes in the design could seriously impact the lead ship design schedule,'' the company said. The Seawolf, or SSN-21, is described by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> as the key to rebuilding the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> edge in underwater warfare _ an advantage that has eroded over the past decade because of espionage scandals and Soviet efforts to build quieter submarines of their own. The report from <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> was disclosed Tuesday by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Mich., in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> voicing `` strong concern about a high-risk acquisition strategy being pursued by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in the procurement of the $ 50 billion-plus SSN-21 Seawolf submarine program. <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> holds the contract for designing the Seawolf's hull and interior layout. The company concluded in its December report that it could not keep the project on schedule unless `` the combat system design development -LRB- is -RRB- brought in line with the ship design development.'' `` In essence, the ship design and the combat system design -LRB- have become -RRB- out of phase by over a year,'' <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> to review the program and give his view of whether all operational tests should be completed on the first sub before a full-scale production go-ahead is given. Each Seawolf is now expected to cost more than $ 1.5 billion. `` My concern about this matter has been reinforced by a copy of a letter which has recently come to my attention indicating strong concern about the design of the AN-BSY-2 fire control system ...,'' <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> wrote. The congressman said would like the <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary to tell him `` when and how will you know whether the problems raised in the <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION> letter will affect the planned delivery date of the first SSN-21?'' The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday declined to discuss the substance of the <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> report, saying `` it would not be appropriate to comment on what will become the substance of a reply'' to <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> did say, however, it was confident the combat system would be delivered on time for the lead Seawolf sub. The SSN-21, like the current 688 - or Los Angeles-class attack sub, will be designed primarily to hunt and kill Soviet submarines It is supposed to feature greater speed, better sensors and longer-range weapons than the 688 class. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> maintains the Seawolf `` is going to represent a major advance in speed, depth, quieting, weapons capability and supportability.''
