<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Air turbulence bounced a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet at 37,000 feet Tuesday, injuring about 30 passengers bound for <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, officials said. United Flight 90, a non-stop flight from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> carrying 232 passengers and 11 crew members, landed at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> around 7 p.m. without further incident, said airline spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>. `` We've been told the plane was over <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, when it encountered clear-air turbulence ... which means the pilot could n't see it,'' <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said `` The flight attendants said it lasted less than a minute, but apparently the turbulence was pretty severe,'' he added. ` Fortunately, the seat-belt light was on at the time.'' `` It was like being in one of those roller coasters,'' said passenger <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasquesi </PERSON>. United Flight 90 originated in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> picked up a handful of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> tourists fleeing the unrest in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> before continuing to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said airline spokesman <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON>. It was not known if any of those travelers were among the injured. Figures on the number injured varied. Officials at hospitals said 20 victims were brought in, but the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> put the number at 35. Ten people were removed from the DC-10 on stretchers, said <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ