<HEAD>Research: Risk From Pill Low for Relatives of Breast Cancer Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Birth control pills pose no increased breast cancer risk even for women with a family member who developed the disease. That's the finding of a new study of oral contraceptive use among women who have a family history of breast cancer, one of the major concerns in the medical community about long-term use of th pill. `` These data suggest you do n't need to be nearly as concerned as some people thought previously if you have a very strong family history -LRB- of breast cancer -RRB-,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON>, co-author of the study and a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> Uniformed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, Md. <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON> said that women whose mothers, sisters, daughters, aunts, or grandmothers had breast cancer are known to be at higher risk of developing the disease. As a result, doctors for years have recommended that women with such a family history not take birth control pills. The perception, he said, was that oral contraceptives would aggravate an existing risk. But the new study relieves this concern, said <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON>, and shows `` oral contraceptive use does not appreciably alter risk of breast cancer as far as we have been able to study.'' The research, published in the journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obstetricians </ORGANIZATION> and Gynecologists, involved an analysis of data collected from eight areas of the country by two federal agencies for what is called the Cancer and Steroid Hormone Study, or CASH. The CASH research examined the medical histories of 4,730 women with cancer and 4,646 who did not have cancer. From these groups, the new study analyzed the relative risk of breast cancer among oral contraceptives users who had a family history of breast cancer in comparison with those pill takers who had no family history of breast cancer. The length of time that oral contraceptives were used also was analyzed. `` We looked to see if there was a different effect for women with a strong family history compared to women with no family history,'' said <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON>. `` We found no adverse effect -LRB- from the pill -RRB-. Our data suggests that oral contraceptive use does not increase the risk of breast cancer in women with a family history.'' Though the research seemed to give definite results, <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON> said there is a need for confirming studies. `` This is the largest study of this issue, but it is one study,'' he said `` In this sort of research, we always like to see the building over time of a consensus based on more and more data. But this is certainly a strong piece in that direction.'' <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverberg </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a medical school professor who has researched any connection between birth control pills and cancer, said the findings confirm a continuing sense of confidence in the safety of oral contraceptives. `` This is not unexpected,'' he said. `` I would have expected oral contraceptives to not be associated with increased risks, even for women with a family history of breast cancer. The birth control pills now being prescribed should n't pose a high risk of breast cancer at all.'' Other co-authors of the study were <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesselman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Uniformed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
