<HEAD>Rules Panel Says Only a Few Bailout Bill Amendments to be Considered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> are telling colleagues the panel is unlikely to permit the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to consider more than a few of the 100-plus proposed amendments to savings and loan bailout legislation. However, it is clear from panel members' comments that the committee will clear at least one or perhaps a combination of several of the 10 proposed amendments that would blunt the tougher capital requirements that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration says is the cornerstone of its plan to reform the industry. `` There seems to be great sympathy throughout the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to do something with this'' capital rule, said Rep. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N </LOCATION>. The committee, which decides the rules for debate of legislation in the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, heard in a 4 -LCB- - hour session Tuesday from 12 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members seeking to reshape parts of the S & amp; L bill written in the Banking, Ways and Means and Judiciary committees Forty-seven members remain on the witness list and the Rules panel scheduled another session this afternoon and may have to hold a third on Thursday. Panel members conceded that the flood of amendments means there's little hope of meeting <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s request to move the bill to the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> this week They predicted House action next week. That would set the stage for a conference to reconcile the House bill with a version passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in April and send finished legislation to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s desk in July. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials are insisting that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> require all S & amp; L owners to risk more of their own capital _ $ 3 for every $ 100 in lending _ as a buffer against losses to the government deposit insurance fund. However, Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., and others are arguing that 732 of the nation's 2,949 <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls should keep an accounting break known as `` supervisory goodwill,'' which in some cases allows S & amp; L owners to operate without risking any of their own money According to <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, 241 of the 732 will fail to meet the new capital requirements unless they keep the goodwill, which regulators permitted in the early 1980s as an inducement for merging with failing S & amp; Ls. <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> wants S & amp; Ls to have the right to appeal to regulators to keep their supervisory goodwill, but critics say that could delay the imposition of tougher standards for as long as 18 months. Reps. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on financial institutions; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFalce </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, a member of the banking panel, and two members of the Rules committee, Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Tenn </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, are proposing other accommodations on goodwill, arguing that it's unfair for the government to renege on previous `` I think it's really a bad day in the history of this country when we as legislators agree to do away with written agreements the government has made,'' <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON> said. However, Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, pleaded with the <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to permit consideration of at least one amendment to strengthen capital requirements even further from the 3 percent standard favored by the administration. <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> wants S & amp; L owners to hold 4 percent tangible capital within two years and five percent after five years. In addition to the capital standards, the Rules panel was expected to approve floor consideration of an amendment by the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to add $ 50 billion in government borrowing for the bailout to the federal budget deficit. The administration favors a mechanism for keeping it out of the budget deficit.
