<HEAD>Senate Tidying Up Bill With Money for Veterans, Pet Projects</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Debate resumes at noon EDT; top planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is trying to finish crafting a bill funneling $ 3.3 billion to veterans, college students and other groups, with some lawmakers hoping to use the measure to block a surtax on the elderly. Legislators planned their fourth day of debate on the legislation today, hoping to complete work on a bill that has garnered a slew of provisions on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> since President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> first sought the measure in March. Discussion was continuing today on an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., postponing implementation of much of the new catastrophic care program for the elderly under <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, including a cap on doctors' bills <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>'s proposal also would delay for a year the surtax on people 65 or older that is designed to pay for the program. That levy can reach a maximum of $ 800 this year for the wealthiest senior citizens, and some of them have complained that the tax is excessive. `` We're laying an incredible cost on them for coverage they do not want or need at that cost,'' <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> said. But opposition to <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> came even from his own political party. `` I think I know where the crux of the problem comes from ...,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` They all live in <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and they all have incomes of $ 30,000 to $ 40,000 a year.'' <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is a retirement community in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. Democrats said the size of the surtax should be reconsidered instead in future legislation. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejected 69-29 a proposal by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, allowing the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to withhold aid from communities refusing to let transit projects to companies doing business with the pro-apartheid government of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Lawmakers also adopted by voice vote an amendment by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, urging <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to revamp a tax law that business considers burdensome. That followed a 50-49 defeat for Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>, R-Wis., who instead wanted the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to repeal the tax law, which forces companies to prove their health benefits are as generous to low-paid workers as they are to executives For technical reasons, <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> would have needed 60 votes to prevail. The overall spending bill is designed to provide federal agencies with enough money to see them through the Sept. 30 end of fiscal 1989. It would pump $ 1.2 billion to veterans programs, $ 892 million for Guaranteed Student Loans for college students, and $ 225 million for food stamps. It would finance other costs including those for Soviet refugees moving to this country, last year's forest fires, foster care, and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping efforts. The measure also is studded with provisions directing federal resources at projects important to individual lawmakers. Thus, it would prevent a school district in <LOCATION> Sumter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, from losing about $ 700,000 in federal education aid this year it would otherwise forfeit. The provision was sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Other clauses would order the Army to spend $ 50 million this year on cold weather clothes manufactured in 10 states; provide <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rican </LOCATION> political parties with $ 1.5 million to conduct a referendum on the island's future political status; and distribute $ 6.6 million in subsidies to airlines that serve small communities in 39 states. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed a $ 3.7 billion version of the bill on May 24, two months after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sought legislation totaling $ 2.2 billion. The two chambers will have to agree to a compromise before sending a bill to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s signature.
