<HEAD>Cities Nationwide Look To Fremont Child-Care Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE vote.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NJ Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A landmark measure to create a direct tax on households and businesses to support child care was failing in early returns Tuesday as cities and child-care advocates nationwide watched. With 27 of 84 precincts reporting, the vote was 3,218 against the measure to 858 for. The measure, which faced an uphill battle to win passage by a two-thirds majority, would raise $ 1.8 million a year from residents, businesses, developers and the city's own coffers to open care centers at 30 elementary schools. The program in this city of 165,000 on the east side of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> also would help sick kids and subsidize poor parents for baby-sitting costs. `` Cities around the country are looking to the Fremont example to see whether taxpayers are willing to pay for child care,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON>, director of the Children and Families and Cities Project of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` People in 80 percent of all cities are saying child care is the most pressing need for children from birth to 9 years old,'' he said. `` Cities are looking for ways to handle that need, and resources are the biggest barrier to providing good services.'' About 100 cities offer some kind of support for child care, <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON> said. Some simply coordinate programs or offer training; others spend money through general funds, federal community block grants or developer fees. `` Fremont's measure is the only example I know about of a dedicated tax for any services having to do with children,'' <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON> said. `` This is on the forefront of things to come in the future.'' The measure would impose a $ 12 annual tax on every homeowner, with renters exempt, and a 20 percent business tax surcharge. It would expire in 15 years. The vote in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION> will indicate `` how deep public support is for child care,'' said <PERSON> Abby </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, managing attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` We all have magnifying glasses and we're watching it very carefully,'' said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, coordinator of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>'s office on child care. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION>, which has 1,400 member cities and 49 state and municipal members representing an additional 14,000 cities, said many cities are watching closely. `` Advocacy groups see Fremont as an example of what can be done to deal with a need that is felt in all cities,'' <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON> said. `` It's not just something for the rich or poor Lots of people need it. This measure will make city governments think about this problem.''
</TEXT>
