<FIRST>r w PM-GreenhouseUncertainty     06-07 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenhouse Uncertainty,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Urge More Study Before Launching Anti-Greenhouse Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More proof of the danger is needed before governments launch programs seeking to correct the `` greenhouse'' warming of the planet, a pair of scientists is cautioning. There does seem to have been a warming over the last 100 years, but too much uncertainty remains about the causes of that change to justify immediate government action, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON>, former head of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Goddard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>. The effect of clouds is not well understood, and the small warming recorded so far could easily be a result of normal climate variability or changes in the brightness of the sun, explained the former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> scientist. `` Current forecasts of the man-made greenhouse effect do not appear to be sufficiently accurate to be used as a basis for sound national policy decisions,'' said <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON> made his comments in releasing the study `` Scientific Perspectives on the Greenhouse Problem.'' The report was presented by <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON>, a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and of <ORGANIZATION> Rockefeller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. A third co-author, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nierenberg </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanography </ORGANIZATION>, could not attend the news conference on Tuesday. The study was published by the <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The institute, funded by foundation grants, conducts research on public policy issues, said <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON>. In recent years the threat of greenhouse warming has attracted considerable attention, with some scientists warning that it could raise the Earth's temperature, changing the climate, turning major farm areas into dust bowls and melting the polar ice caps, causing a rise in sea levels. The warming would result from increases in gases such as carbon dioxide and methane in the atmosphere. These gases allow warmth from the sun to pass through to the earth but block outgoing radiation, raising the planet's temperature in somewhat the same way a greenhouse warms its interior. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON>'s successor at <LOCATION> Goddard </LOCATION>, has been a leader in this research, warning that the effect may already be observable in studies indicating the planet is about 1 degree Fahrenheit warmer now than it was a century ago. That conclusion has been widely debated, with various climate experts differing on the effect of clouds, urban growth and other factors in changing average temperatures. `` We do n't believe he has overstated the risks,'' of this warming, commented <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON> of <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>'s work. But, <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON> added, `` the one place we part company is the ability to forecast the next century from what we know now.'' <PERSON> Jastrow </PERSON> recommended increased research spending to determine the extent of the danger, if any. Research facilities costing $ 100 million or so could help provide these answers in three to five years, he said, still plenty of time to act if it is found that a gloabl warming is, indeed, underway.
</TEXT>
