<HEAD>Marcos Rushed Into Emergency Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Philippine President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> underwent emergency surgery Tuesday, but hospital officials declined to give any immediate details. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, who has been listed in very critical condition since May 18, underwent 3 -LCB- hours of surgery at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> beginning at 3:30 p.m., said <LOCATION> Gemmo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION>, a family spokesman. `` He's very much alive,'' <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> said, `` They did n't tell us yet what the surgery was for.'' Hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Kop </PERSON> said a statement on the operation would be released soon. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, 71, has been suffering from a variety of serious ailments, including kidney and heart failure, pneumonia and bacterial infections. He has been unable to breathe on his own and has been undergoing constant kidney dialysis. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, who has lived here since his ouster in a popular revolt in February 1986, has been hospitalized since Jan. 15. On May 23, his doctors said it was a miracle he was still alive. `` I think if you asked any one of us, we'd all say he has a low probability of long-term surivival,'' transplant surgeon Dr. <PERSON> Livingston </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON> said then. Although the prognosis for <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> remained poor at the time, doctors would not rule out the possibility of recovery. The former leader's illness has prevented him from traveling to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to face racketeering charges alleging he plundered his homeland of more than $ 100 million and used the money to buy real estate and art in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. His wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, who also is charged, last month appealed to <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to allow her husband to die in his homeland. The request was denied.
