<TEXT>
 Compromise federal housing legislation that <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> authors hope will promote participation of developers, community groups and local officials in the creation of new affordable homes has won the backing of two Northeast governors. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said Tuesday the $ 4.1 billion bipartisan measure `` has all the pieces we need to address the housing needs of our country.'' `` It reaches out to the states and local communities. It recognizes that there is a strong and eager network of people in the housing community ready and anxious to work with you and the new administration,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> governor told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on housing and urban affairs. <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON>, a Republican representing the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, also endorsed the measure by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., and <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, to create affordable housing The Cranston-D'Amato legislation, the product of two years of negotiations, would require state and local governments to match the federal funds with 25 percent contributions.
