<HEAD>Station Not Required to Tell Viewers Toy Maker Providing Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> television station was not required to tell viewers that a toy maker was providing a children's program in exchange for advertising space. The commission, in a ruling upholding the common industry practice of `` barter'' sales, on Tuesday denied a complaint that <ORGANIZATION> KCOP-TV </ORGANIZATION> should have identified <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and TV syndicator Group W Productions as sponsors of the cartoon show, `` He-Man and the Masters of the Universe.'' The Los-Angeles based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> had characterized the children's fantasy show as a non-stop depiction of the `` He-Man'' logo and `` He-Man'' toy products made by <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 denied the complaint, which had been joined by Action for Children's Television. <ORGANIZATION> NABB </ORGANIZATION> appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which in September 1987 remanded the case to the commission which denied the complaint again Tuesday.
