<HEAD>Carnage In China Stuns Filipinos, Whose Uprising Ended Bloodlessly</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For Filipinos, the bloody attacks on pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have served as a shocking vision of what could have happened to their own `` People Power'' revolution three years ago. Commentators and officials have also taken advantage of the massacre of hundreds and possibly thousands of Chinese to discredit Filipino Communists, who have have patterned their 20-year insurgency on the Chinese `` people's war'' that brought the late <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> to power 40 years ago. Newspaper and broadcast commentators have drawn parallels between the turmoil in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and the events of February 1986, when hundreds of thousands of Filipinos poured into the streets to protect military officers who had mutineed against President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> ordered his troops to suppress the mutiny. But <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' troops refused to fire on civilians who included nuns, priests and students On Feb. 25, 1986, <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> fled <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> for exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The only casualties were three pro-Marcos soldiers slain defending the government television station against mutineers. `` There, but for the grace of God, we might have gone in February 1986, when that glorious buzzword ` <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>' was invented,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Soliven </PERSON> in The Philippine Star of the carnage in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` In that crucial moment, that crossroads of history, the -LRB- Philippine -RRB- Armed Forces chose to side with the people rather than with our tyrant.'' In the years since <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> fled, President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> and other Filipino leaders have attributed the success of their `` revolution'' to factors ranging from the `` power of the people'' to intercession by the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>. `` In -LRB- 1986 -RRB-, we were all praying because we are all Christians,'' said Cardinal <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sin </PERSON>, who called civilians into the streets three years ago. `` To us, a man is indeed very valuable. Even soldiers loyal to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> felt that their obligation is toward their country.'' Some Filipino commentators also believe the key was American diplomatic pressure. After supporting <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> for years, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats warned him not to use force and finally offered him safe haven in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. No foreign government has such leverage with the Chinese. Meanwhile, the military has already begun using the events in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> as a propaganda weapon against the underground Communist Party of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> said Tuesday that the events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> prove that Communism is a discredited philosophy. In a statement Monday, <PERSON> Cardinal </PERSON> <PERSON> Sin </PERSON> said the savagery in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> should serve as a warning to Filipinos who support the rebels. `` Please open your eyes to the reality that Communism can only make our lives more miserable,'' he said.
</TEXT>
