<HEAD>Report: Foreigners Among Leading Political Contributors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an unprecedented report submitted to parliament, the government has revealed that many of the major contributors to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s political parties in last year's national elections were foreigners. The report only gave the first initial, last name and sum contributed for the 20 largest givers, but the list included figures from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, State Comptroller <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> said. She would not elaborate on the contributors' identities. The report, submitted Tuesday by Mrs. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON>, publicly revealed for the first time the names of political contributors. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s two major political parties, the left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, have long opposed any efforts to disclose the names of large contributors, saying it would inhibit contributions. The report named <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as the largest single contributor. He gave $ 1.3 million to Labor. The second largest donor, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, gave $ 415,000, also to the Labor party. Although corporate contributions are outlawed, there is no ceiling on private donations. Speaking before the report was formally issued, former Labor party Secretary-General <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Baram </PERSON> said: `` To my knowledge there is no other example in the world where most of the donations that are made to political parties do n't come from the same nation where the elections are held.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> said she released the report to prevent large contributors from trying to influence <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> politics. `` If we know about these contributors and, <PERSON> God </PERSON> forbid, one of them sees it as an investment, and wants it to be realized, the public can come and help me so it does n't happen,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> said. The report listed the names of all contributors who donated more than $ 31,000 to political parties after August 20. Ms. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> first notified parties that the names of contributors would be published on that date. The election was held Nov. 1. The report lists 14 contributors who together gave $ 2.8 million to Labor and five who together gave $ 405,000 to the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>. One contributor, from <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, gave $ 100,000 to the left-wing <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>. The report did not include the names of three donators. One gave $ 250,000 to the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, and two gave a total of $ 470,000 to Labor. Ms. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Porat </PERSON> agreed to withhold publication of their names when leaders from Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> said they were in sensitive positions in foreign countries and publication of their names could endanger their lives. The report said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 17 political parties raised a total of $ 41.8 million, with <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> and Labor both gathering almost $ 15 million.
</TEXT>
