<HEAD>Amnesty Signed for Return of 41,000 Namibian Guerrillas, Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has agreed to a general amnesty that is to allow 41,000 Namibian black nationalist guerrillas and refugees to return home to the territory from camps in neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. The move is part of an independence plan for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled for 74 years in defiance of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and a 23-year fight for black majority rule. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> signed the amnesty Tuesday, paving the way for the repatriation to begin Monday. Some Namibians will be coming home for the first time in 20 years. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials said they would be airlifting the Namibian refugees at a rate of 1,000 to 1,400 a day through July. In conjunction with the amnesty, <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s South African-installed administrator repealed security laws, including those allowing detention without trial and empowering <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to halt court proceedings against security force members. The repeal is a prelude to pre-independence elections in November. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s administrator, and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> envoy <PERSON> Martti </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON> had been negotiating the moves for weeks. `` The discriminatory and restrictive laws that are to be repealed represent only a small fraction of those that have existed in this territory for many years,'' <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON> said. He said all 41,000 Namibians returning from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> will be covered by the amnesty. On Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees plans to bring the first 1,374 refugees to the northern towns of <LOCATION> Ondangwa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Grootfontein </LOCATION> and the capital, <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>, officials said. They will include members of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s only guerrilla-backed movement <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is favored to win the November elections, though it is unclear if the organization will capture the two-thirds majority needed to control a new government. Campaigning is to begin July 1, but senior guerrilla leaders have not said when they plan to come home. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and South African officials still must resolve issues including voter registration procedures and the release of political prisoners. Namibian authorities say they are holding 29 political prisoners. The guerrilla movement says 201 dissidents were freed recently. More than 4,000 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military personnel are in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to monitor the transition to independence, and <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON> said he would deploy 500 more police monitors. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> independence plan in a three-nation regional accord involving the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops helping <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s government fight right-wing rebels armed by <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. At <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> announced Tuesday that two black African diplomats have been appointed as senior staff to strengthen the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Namibian independence operation. African front-line states had lobbied intensely for appointment of an African assistant to give them a stronger voice in the <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> operation. <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador, <PERSON> Legwaila </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Legwaila </PERSON>, was named an assistant secretary-general to serve as deputy special representative for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. B.A. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Nigerian </LOCATION> ambassador, was the U.N. Transition Assistance Group's special representative in <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION> to improve liaison with Angolan authorities.
