<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats Probe,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Launches Criminal Investigation Of Rocky Flats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB KERR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scores of federal agents seized records at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant as the government announced a criminal investigation of possible environmental violations at the facility. Investigators were checking allegations that employees treated, stored and disposed of hazardous wastes without permits, falsely certified federal environmental reports and concealed environmental contamination, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said 75 agents from the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s office of criminal investigations began searching the plant Tuesday morning. The probe is expected to last six months to a year. Federal officials declined to say what prompted the search at the plant, identified last year by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> as the most environmentally hazardous site in the nuclear weapons industry because of contamination of an underground reservoir. Officials stressed that no new dangers existed at the plant, which processes plutonium for nuclear weapons. `` It is absolutely essential that the public understand that this investigation does not signal any major new environmental safety or health concern,'' Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said in a statement issued in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON>, D-Colo., whose district encompasses Rocky Flats, said the implications of the swarm of investigators at the plant `` is the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> had some reason to believe they would be risking destruction of evidence if they did n't act in that fashion. He told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> he has heard `` there were several informants that became the basis for the FBI-Department of <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> investigation and that's been going on for the better part of a year.'' The plant 16 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> is operated for the <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Investigators are examining actions by both government and <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> employees, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> said the company had advised employees to cooperate with investigators but declined to comment further. Rocky Flats has been dogged by environmental problems. DOE inspectors closed the plant's main plutonium reprocessing building last October for four months because of safety violations. The DOE also issued a report last December that revealed 32 new safety problems. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said he authorized disclosure of the investigation because the search was a matter of public record. <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON>, a staunch critic of Rocky Flats' operations, said there was apparent `` reason to believe a number of individuals at the plant were involved in concert in the effort to falsify and mislead with regard to environmental compliance issues.'' Energy Secretary Admiral <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, in a statement, said his department will perform an independent analysis of Rocky Flats operations `` and ensure that continued operations, regardless of past practices, are conducted in a safe and environmentally sound manner.'' He also said part of the plant would be shut down as a result of the investigation, but he offered no specifics in the statement. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said he was suspending `` those operations for which safety could be adversely affected by the presence and functioning of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> investigating team.'' Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON>, a Democrat who has prodded federal officials to deal with <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION>' radioactive waste disposal problems, was informed of the investigation only an hour before it was announced. <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said he was assured he would be notified immediately of any new dangers. `` I'm outraged by the possibility that some criminal action may have occurred at Rocky Flats,'' <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> told a news conference shortly after the federal announcement. `` I have been trying to say to people this is an operation that we're monitoring closely and it's not endangering your health. Today I have to say to people, ` Wait a minute. I do n't know yet,''' <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said. The investigation involves alleged violations of the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act, the Clean Water Act and the federal false statement law, <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said.
