<HEAD>Thumbnail Sketches of Chinese Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are sketches of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s top leaders:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> DENG </PERSON> <PERSON> XIAOPING </PERSON>, 84, who ordered troops to march on the capital to suppress pro-democracy unrest, is the most powerful leader in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> even though the highest ranking position he holds is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The commission, not the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, has the final say on military matters. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> was purged twice by radicals during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution and then staged a comeback that transformed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> from a country dominated by ideological battles into one with pragmatic, market-oriented economic policies. Living standards have improved for millions of Chinese but the modernization drive has led to serious problems of inflation and corruption. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> has been out of sight since May 16. Chinese sources say he has been hospitalized for treatment of prostate cancer. The government denied a report Tuesday that <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> had died, calling it a `` fabrication designed to make people uneasy and create chaos.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> ZHAO </PERSON> <PERSON> ZIYANG </PERSON>, 69, reportedly purged for sympathizing with the students, was general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> since 1987 and had been the nation's leading advocate of rapid economic reforms. As governor of <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> province in the late 1970's, he led the country in successful experiments in restoring family farming. In 1980, <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> brought him to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and he was quickly named premier. He became party chief in 1987 following the ouster of fellow reformist <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>, who was blamed for student unrest. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was last seen on May 19 when he went to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> to meet student hunger strikers. He is said to be under house arrest.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> LI </PERSON> <PERSON> PENG </PERSON>, 60, who declared martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on May 20, has been premier since April 1988. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> studied in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the 1950's and represents the technocrats now filling many government offices. He opposed <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s moves in market-oriented reforms, saying he supports the plan but prefers a more cautious pace. One <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> newspaper reported that <PERSON> Li </PERSON> was shot Sunday by a police officer in the Great Hall of the People and wounded in the thigh. It said <PERSON> Li </PERSON> was not seriously injured and the officer was immediately shot to death. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> has not been seen in public since he met three new ambassadors May 25 and said the government was `` stable.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> YANG </PERSON> <PERSON> SHANGKUN </PERSON>, 82, who supported <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s declaration of martial law and led the hardliners demanding a tough stand against the students, became <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s president, or head of state, in April 1988. The post of president is largely ceremonial but <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> has close ties to <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> and holds a seat on the 17-member party Politburo. A career military man who was active in <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> campaigns in the 1930's and 1940's, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> was appointed permanent vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in 1982. <PERSON> Yang </PERSON>'s power in that post reportedly has grown and some say he has been running the commission. More important, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> is widely believed to have family connections within the hierarchy of the armed forces, particularly the 27th Army that marched on the city last weekend.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> QIN </PERSON> <PERSON> JIWEI </PERSON>, the defense minister may have been ousted from office for opposing martial law. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> is the former head of <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>, which was said to be unenthusiastic about martial law. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> has links with the 38th Army from the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> region that may have refused orders to move against the students.
</TEXT>
