<HEAD>Stocks Soar, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices rose sharply in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today, while the dollar edged up against the Japanese yen amid uncertainties over turmoil in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, dealers said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION>, which slipped 5.07 points Tuesday, rose 174.88 points, or 0.52 percent, closing at 33,626.89. The index had fallen four straight days since Thursday. The dollar ended trading at 142.80 yen, up 0.17 yen from Tuesday's 142.63-yen finish. After opening at 142.45 yen, the currency ranged between 142.40 and 143.00 yen. <PERSON> Toru </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanai </PERSON>, foreign exchange analyst with <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the unstable Chinese situation encouraged dollar buying, but speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> might cut interest rates also gave participants a reason to sell the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. `` We had a lot of dollar buying because many investors believe the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> money is a safe investment in time of emergencies,'' he said. `` But they did n't want to hold too many dollars either because of expectations the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> might cut its interest rates soon.'' Investors speculate the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> may ease its monetary policy following the cut in the prime lending rate on Monday by major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks. <PERSON> Kanai </PERSON> said there were unconfirmed rumors that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> intervened in the market to support the yen when the dollar hit the 143-yen mark. `` It had no impact on the market,'' he said. The central bank usually does not comment officially on its market interventions. On the stock market, dealers said the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index began to rise as investors picked up cheap issues following the four days of losses. But trading was basically directionless because of uncertainties over political unrest in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which made many institutional investors remain on the sidelines, said a trader with a major securities firm. Speculative buying pushed up the index, he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. Trading was moderate, with volume on the market's first section estimated at 600 million shares, up from Tuesday's 550 million shares. Among the winners were steel and construction issues.
