ng the legwork for the pedal-powered craft. Swimmers on the other side of the pool easily lapped the submarine during its first efforts. But as navigator Cangahuala and <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> hit their stride, the Icarus began picked up speed. The three-day race, beginning June 23 off <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, is sponsored by the H.A. <ORGANIZATION> Perry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit scientific foundation created to inspire development of undersea technology through education, research and experimentation. The MIT entry will be up against 18 other submarines from 16 colleges or engineering firms. <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> crew will use `` ringers,'' or athletes, to pedal the submarine. The subs are `` wet,'' or water-filled, meaning the pilot and first mate will have to wear SCUBA equipment. If Greek mythology has anything to do with it, the MIT entry could be the favorite to win the competition. According to legend, <PERSON> Icarus </PERSON> and his father, <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION>, attempted human-powered flight. While <PERSON> Daedalus </PERSON> stayed aloft, Icarus plunged into the sea.
