<HEAD>City Bans Ducks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. AUGUSTINE BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ducks have been dumped and their supporters are crying foul. The few Muscovy ducks that have survived a 17-month-old feud over their presence in this north <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> coastal community were exiled by commissioners at a late-night session Monday unattended by most pro-duck forces. On a 3-2 vote, the city commission banished the half dozen remaining <PERSON> Muscovies </PERSON> and disbanded a committee that had been formed to resolve the dispute. No destination or departure date has been decided for the ducks, which once numbered near 150 but dwindled after some residents complained the large fowls defecated profusely and harassed other animals. The duck debate became a cause celebre in January 1988, when the commission voted to reduce the <LOCATION> Muscovy </LOCATION> population from 150 to 20. The ducks were caught and taken to farms or residences outside the city and eggs were destroyed. In late August, a Muscovy swooped down and attacked a city commissioner and his family. In December, pro-duckers accused anti-duckers of running over the birds with their cars. One duck was found with its legs chopped off. Commissioner <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> did n't present his resolution to oust the Muscovies until shortly before midnight Monday because the commission had a two-hour public hearing on a new veterinary clinic. `` The ducks have to go,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. `` Loud mouths and money have talked against the ducks, and we ca n't match that,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanairsdale </PERSON>, the only pro-duck committee member to witness the vote. `` I'm really taken aback.'' `` Some people are mad as hell about it,'' said Commissioner <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodson </PERSON>, who also backed the birds.
