<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposal to get heavy trucks off the street during rush hour has gotten the green light from major construction unions and businesses, Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. Following long negotiations, city officials exempted trucks and other equipment required to pour concrete, lay hot asphalt and erect structural steel from the traffic - and smog-control plan, the mayor announced Tuesday In return, the construction industry agreed to shift its work hours _ without premium pay _ to 6 a.m. to 3 p.m. instead of the current 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. to reduce truck and automobile traffic, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. `` Compromises such as these will ensure cleaner air and provide free-flowing streets and highways for all in the city of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> area,'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. The plan is expected to go before the City Council next month. However, Councilman <PERSON> Zev </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaroslavsky </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> later in the day approved spending $ 250,000 to help develop the plan, said much work remains. `` There are a lot of flaws to any program which deals with city streets and does n't deal with freeways,'' he said. `` And I do n't think you can deal with one city and not deal with surrounding cities. The plan's one-hour shift would remove about 125,000 construction workers from city streets during the morning and afternoon rush-hour, the mayor said. The altered work schedule involves 83 union locals, including boiler makers, brick layers, carpenters, operating engineers, Teamsters, general contractors, pipe trade workers and painters. The proposal, developed by the city with a regional air quality control agency, would require truck operators to pay a surcharge to use city streets during rush hour.
