<HEAD>Mourners Chant Support for Khomeini Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of mourners today chanted support for <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s interim successor, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, at a memorial service for the revolutionary patriarch at <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Iranian new reports said almost 11,000 had been injured during the demonstrations of national grief since <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> died on Saturday night. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio quoted an unidentified health official as saying `` many died,'' but no number was given. Eight deaths were reported on Monday. News reports said 438 people had been taken to hospitals. Carrying black flags and portraits of the imam, or spiritual leader, today's crowds at <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> chanted `` The imam is in heaven today'' and `` Better we were dead and you were here with us.'' The 86-year-old <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, who turned <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> into a fundamentalist Islamic state after the overthrow of a 2,500-year-old monarchy in 1979, died of a heart attack on Saturday. He had undergone intestinal surgery 11 days earlier. Today's memorial service was held at the site of a weekly prayer service. Attending were <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON>, Chief Justice <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardebili </PERSON>, <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s son <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s president, was named caretaker leader on Sunday, winning 60 of 74 votes cast by the Assembly of Experts. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> had formed the group to handle his succession. `` Obedience to <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> is obedience to the imam of Ummah -LRB- The Islamic nation -RRB-,'' the crowd chanted. After the ceremony, many people beat themselves rhythmically on the head in a traditional gesture of grief by Shiite Moslems. Many fainted in the heat. They were lifted above the crowd and passed overhead to stretchers that took them to first-aid stations. However, life was gradually returning to normal a day after the city was convulsed with grief during the funeral of <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. Shops reopened today with long lines for bread and other supplies. Heavy traffic also reappeared on the streets; private cars carried black flags and portraits of <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> on their windshields. Also today, the official <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> news agency reported that <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Montazeri </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> removed as his designated successor in March, visited his grave in <LOCATION> Beheshte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zehra </LOCATION> cemetery. The news agency said the cemetery was still mobbed with people paying their respects at the grave. On Tuesday, mourners blocked a van carrying the body in an open coffin from the square where it laid in state for 24 hours in an air-conditioned glass cubicle. Scrambling for mementos, they grabbed the white burial shroud and tore it to shreds. The body, which fell to the ground, was taken away in an ambulance and lifted by helicopter to the gravesite.
