<HEAD>Citywide Child Care Measure Defeated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A first-in-the-nation measure that would have taxed residents and businesses to pay for day care citywide was trounced at the polls. `` It's a resounding victory for those family values that have gotten us this far,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pro-Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION>, which opposed the measure. He said before the election Tuesday that parents who had already raised children without help would defeat the measure. With all ballots counted, 3,671 or 22 percent voted in favor of the measure, and 12,697 or 78 percent voted against it. The tax needed a two-thirds majority to become law in this city of 165,000 on the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. Under Measure B, households would have paid an additional $ 12 annually and businesses a 20 percent tax surcharge to raise $ 1 million annually. An additional $ 800,000 would have come from general funds and developer fees. The money was slated to buy 30 portable day-care classrooms, provide child-care vouchers for poor families and train child-care providers. While other cities subsidize child care for the poor, <ORGANIZATION> Fremont </ORGANIZATION> attempted to tax citizens directly to pay for child care for the entire community. The proposal drew support from working parents, feminists and business leaders. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of the pro-Measure B Citizens for Quality Child Care said he may return with another version. `` Children do n't go away,'' he said. `` People are going to have to recognize and deal with it one way or another.'' Supporters of the measure maintained that `` children are the responsibility of the entire community and that's precisely the point of disagreement,'' <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> said. `` We're frightened by that point. Children are the responsibility of their parents except where financial assistance is a necessity.'' Despite the lopsided defeat, just getting the measure on the ballot is an accomplishment and a signal the public recognizes child care is `` a pervasive problem for all classes,'' said state Assemblyman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, co-chairman of a task force on the changing family.
