</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 June 2 Post-Bulletin, <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, on Bush-Soviets: President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has responded effectively to recent policy initiatives by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The president acted decisively in his visit to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, particularly with his statement on arms reduction and his call for the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION> to tear down the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall and to `` bury'' the Cold War. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s more assertive approach not only scored points in the public relations war with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. It also was well-received in this country, where public opinion has tended to believe that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms and less bellicose attitude are genuine and hopeful signs. There is no assurance that reforms now under way in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION> countries or in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will succeed. Repression may return. But whatever happens, the people in communist-dominated countries never again will be as docile or submissive as they have been for the past 70 years in the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> and the past 40 years in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is right in encouraging these reforms. He is right in challenging Soviet leaders to reduce armaments to a level that makes sense for defense, but drastically reduces offensive capability.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 June 2 Herald-Dispatch, <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, on the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall: President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was the first to issue the call That was in 1963. President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> repeated the message in 1978 and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1987. Now President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, as he should, has added his voice. Speaking in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to tear down the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall: `` The wall stands as a monument to the failure of communism. It must come down. Make all <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> a center of commerce between East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> _ a place of cooperation, not confrontation.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> thus has managed to put a bit of political pressure on Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who visits <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in mid-June. Europeans in general and the West Germans in particualr have welcomed the apparent conciliation and cooperation that have been <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s hallmark since he took power in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. But the blunt reality is that `` glasnost'' will be little more than a pretty word as long as the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall stands. The Soviets should back up their words with deeds _ and start by dismantling the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall.
</TEXT>
