<HEAD>Customers Withdrew $5.4 billion from S&amp;Ls in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said today that savings and loan customers withdrew $ 5.4 billion from their accounts in April, a high number but an improvement compared with the record outflows earlier in the year. It was the 12th consecutive month of withdrawals and the sixth in a row when outflows exceeded $ 5 billion, according to a report by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates the nation's 2,934 S & amp; Ls. In the first four months of the year, customers withdrew $ 33.7 billion more than they deposited, compared with a $ 16.2 billion gain in deposits during the same period of last year. Withdrawals set a one-month record of $ 10.8 billion in January, slipping to $ 9.2 billion in February and $ 8.3 billion in March. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Barth </PERSON>, chief economist of the bank board, said the April figure is better than it at first appears. `` About half of the outflow is accounted for by 10 thrifts, four of which are insolvent,'' he said in a statement. `` The deposit outflow figures are even smaller when you account for seasonal factors, since one of the poorest deposit flow months of the year is April when people are paying income taxes. `` On a seasonally adjusted basis, the outflow was $ 1.6 billion, down sharply from $ 6.7 billion in March, and the smallest outflow since ... last September.'' <PERSON> Barth </PERSON> attributed the continuing withdrawals to the failure of <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls to keep pace with rising interest rates offered by competitors such as mutual funds and to orders from regulators requiring overextended thrift institutions to shrink. Private analysts say lack of public confidence in S & amp; Ls is also a factor. To remedy that, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to move more swiftly on its bailout plan, now not expected to reach the president's desk until next month.
