<HEAD>Chinatown Shaken by Beijing Massacre</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS 3rd graf pvs, `Like in ...' to fix grammar.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRIS CHANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The butcher raised his cleaver and slammed it into the neck of a duck at a <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> grocery store. `` Killers,'' he spat out as he chopped the duck and listened with two other men to a Chinese-language radio broadcast on the weekend massacre in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Anguish pervades this Chinese enclave south of downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, as it does in other Chinatowns around the country. Groups of people _ mostly men _ squat on street corners or sit in restaurants. Newspapers in hand, they talk about the military suppression of the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s student-led, pro-democracy movement. `` The tanks,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON>, pointing at a newspaper picture of the scene in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square. `` Students were in a tent. The tanks, they crush them, over and over! Until all bodies be a mess! A mess!'' Yuan's face twisted in pain and he took off his glasses to wipe the corners of his eyes. A pastor at the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> was handing out fliers advertising a prayer service. `` The only thing we can do is pray,'' he said. About 16,000 people live in the 15-square-block <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>. The district's commercial strip is a tourist attraction with its welcoming green and red gate and blocks of restaurants and gift stores. After the massacre, residents of Chinatowns in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and elsewhere held demonstrations against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s hard-line leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> residents grab for the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and other Chinese-language newspapers every morning, said <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Ti-yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON>, a reporter for the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> bureau. Some wait for an hour by news stands for delivery trucks that arrive at 10 a.m. Advertisements in the World Journal announced a meeting planned for Sunday to raise money to buy facsimile machines to get news out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and medical supplies and airline tickets for students who want to go to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to demonstrate. `` It's going to be very dangerous,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> said, nodding. `` There are rumors that doctors who treat the wounded in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> are executed.'' Rumors seemed to be as prevalent as hard news along the commercial strip. `` I heard that <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> is dead,'' a bartender said in the Three Happiness restaurant. The Chinese government on Tuesday denied the rumor. At <PERSON> Mabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Moy </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Four </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seasons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Moy </PERSON> has been counseling people not to return to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` I tell them they better think it over before they go,'' Ms. <PERSON> Moy </PERSON> said. `` Everyone in <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> knows each other and I'm not going to put anyone's life in danger just to sell a ticket.'' Many people in <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>, like the butcher, would not talk with a reporter, and some who did would not give their names. `` I do n't even feel like eating,'' said a Chinese student who declined to give her name. She works part time in a gift shop packed with paper fans and miniature Buddhas. Her family, including her husband, are still in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. She talked with them by telephone on Monday. `` My brother and my husband spent the whole night at Tiananmen Square the time they started shooting,'' she said. `` I'm lonely here,'' she said, adding she had planned to return to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> next year. `` Now I do n't know when I can see my family.''
</TEXT>
