> Bhutto </PERSON> had `` discussed ways to encourage a political solution in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'' that would replace the `` illegitimate regime in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'' with a peaceful and non-aligned representative government. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will continue to explore any serious avenue towards this end,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> replied: `` We are in complete accord'' on the course of policy in regards to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. She added that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> `` remains committed to a political solution of the Afghan problem.'' The late President <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ul-Haq </PERSON>, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutoo </PERSON>'s predecessor, had rejected the idea of a political settlement in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s father was by deposed <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> in 1977 and hanged two years later. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> remained in power until perishing in a mysterious plane crash last year that also claimed the life of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphel </PERSON> and an American general. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> brushed aside reporters' attempts to ask about earlier reports of the F-16 deal. An administration official, briefing reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> discussed the F-16 sale, but added that he did not anticipate any specific announcement during her visit. The official, speaking under condition of anonymity, indicated there were no stumbling blocks to the sale. The two leaders also discussed efforts to combat drug production and trafficking. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he applauded Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s `` tough stance on eradicating the opium cultivation'' and thanked her for extraditing an alleged drug trafficker. After a luncheon in her honor at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> witnessed the signing of agreeements providing for $ 465 million to help <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> finance housing, narcotics and education programs. The agreements are part of a $ 2.28 billion, six-year aid package designed to support <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s economic development, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is the third largest recipient of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid.
