<HEAD>Two Cuban-Born Republicans Enter Race for Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with second Republican entering
the race; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Ros-Lehtinen pledged ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Cuban-born Republicans today entered the race for the congressional seat left vacant by the death of <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, the liberal Democrat whose district came to be dominated by conservative Hispanics. State Sen. <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> and conservative businessman <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> announced bids to become the first Cuban-American in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> reported today that Democratic state Sen. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> also will run. The special election will be held Aug. 29. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> pledged to continue the district's tradition of `` a leadership which has been based on a caring conscience and conservative convictions. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>'s passing has left a void that is nearly impossible to fill.'' She said her priorities are bridging the ethnic and social differences in the district, protecting <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, waging war on drugs, taking a tough stand on <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and strongly supporting <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> called the special election on Tuesday, a day after the 88-year-old congressman was buried in <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> after a week of mourning. `` <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> will be difficult, if not impossible, to replace in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. But it's vitally important that we move as quickly as possible so that the people of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s 18th congressional district can be represented,'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. Primaries were set for Aug. 1, with runoffs, if needed, on Aug. 15. Pepper was elected to the seat after its creation in 1962 and won re-election by large margins every two years He drew no opposition last year. In his absence, Republicans are hoping to control the district, whose registration is 54 percent Democrat, down from 72 percent a decade ago. Hispanics are estimated to comprise nearly half the district. `` I think the chances are pretty good for a Cuban-American to be elected,'' said <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendixen </PERSON>, a Democratic strategist. `` Without a doubt, that person would be the most powerful Cuban-American in the country.'' The <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> area is home for many of the 1 million Cubans who have come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s revolution 30 years ago. <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, an independent elected in 1985 as the city's first Cuban-born mayor, has indicated he will support <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, a 36-year-old educator, is married to popular <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON>, who has said he is happy in his current high-profile position. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, a millionaire banana importer, is a staunch supporter of former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. Republican State Rep. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutman </PERSON>, whose Cuban-Jewish heritage fits two large ethnic groups in the district, also was mulling over a candidacy. On the Democratic side, state Sen. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said he would decide by Friday whether to run. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, 67, shares much of Pepper's constituency and liberalism, but may have problems with Hispanic voters because of his opposition to Nicaraguan Contra aid <LOCATION> Hialeah </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, also Cuban-born, was a possible Democratic contender as were Commissioner <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gersten </PERSON>, State Attorney <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> and former school board chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cejas </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
