<HEAD>U.N. Agency Reports Wave of Locusts in West Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swarms of desert locusts have been spotted in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> nations of <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. In a report from its <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> headquarters, the agency said the swarms were rapidly moving east and may reach <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> or even as far as western <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The report said there might be extensive breeding later in the year. The agency said most swarms were small, but one was reported to cover an area of 60 square miles. Swarms of locusts emerged in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> at the end of last year but have not been reported in past months. The report said the locusts' flight activity was limited until about three weeks ago. It was not immediately known what caused the change. The agency said it was monitoring the swarms and conducting aerial insecticide spraying where possible.
</TEXT>
