<HEAD>Energy Company To Pay Families $2.75 Million In Toxic Waste Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gas producer has agreed to pay $ 2 million to eight families forced from their homes by toxic waste, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> reported today. <ORGANIZATION> Colonial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged dumping coal-gasification byproducts decades ago where the homes were later built, the newspaper reported. Under the settlement, to be announced today, Colonial will buy the homes, pay damages and finance the continuing cleanup of the site near the <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified sources as saying the company, in addition to paying each family $ 250,000, agreed to pay $ 750,000 to the Department of Environmental Quality Engineering for testing, fencing the site and cleaning it. Residents had claimed their homes were rendered worthless and the land was so contaminated that sections turned blue from cyanide and other pollutants. They were moved to condominiums last year, with the state paying their rent. `` We're greatly relieved and very happy,'' said <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeley </PERSON>, who moved with his wife and three children last year. `` It's like being a bird in a cage and suddenly having the door sprung open.'' The families' attorney, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlitchmann </PERSON>, told the Globe the settlement is believed to be the first environmental case between a company and homeowners to be resolved through mediation rather than a lawsuit. Mediation took six months, <PERSON> Schlitchmann </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
