<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Local Officials Urged to Review Census Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> launched an effort Wednesday to get local government officials involved in making sure everyone is counted in 1990. The agency said it is sending technical guides to 39,000 local governments, encouraging them to review census maps to make sure all housing units are included. More than 100 million census forms will be sent to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> households at the end of March 1990 to be used in completing the national head count April 1. The bureau said it will hold 470 training sessions for local officials across the nation. Then, later this summer, census maps will be sent to the local governments for comparison with local tax records, occupancy and demolition permits, utility hookups and other records to make sure no home has been overlooked. Once that is completed the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> will compile block-by-block housing counts and send them back to local officials in November for yet another check prior to the actual census. Census counts are vital to city, state and other local governments because those numbers are used to determine representation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and in the distribution of billions of dollars in state and federal funds to communities.
