<HEAD>Far-Right Party's Policies to Come Under Close Scrutiny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities are examining the policies of the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to determine whether they violate constitutional bans against extremist groups, officials said Wednesday. The party might be banned if its policies are found to be contrary to the country's charter, said Bavarian Interior Minister <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoiber </PERSON> He said the party's election rallies have been marked by `` incredible intolerance and brutality.'' The Republicans, led by former <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> SS soldier <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoenhuber </PERSON>, are campaigning for the ouster of foreign workers from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and for limits on the number of people granted asylum in the country. <PERSON> Stoiber </PERSON> made the announcement 10 days before a vote for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. The Republicans' headquarters are in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, the Bavarian capital. Although it is running for seats in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, the party rejects most European Economic Community policies. The parliament, based in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, consists of elected members from each <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> nation. The party's views have been described by critics as similar to those of neo-Nazis. And <PERSON> Stoiber </PERSON> said four of the Republicans' 20 candidates for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> have an `` extremist rightist background.'' As an example of the party's growing extremism, <PERSON> Stoiber </PERSON> quoted a recent statement by its leader, <PERSON> Schoenhuber </PERSON>, who reportedly said: `` If <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> was more aware of history, he would not have let himself be dragged into war only six years after gaining power.'' A regional Republican leader in <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION> recently caused an uproar by suggesting that the party's leftist opponents be sent to labor camps. The Republicans scored major gains in recent state and municipal elections, winning 11 seats in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and seats in several local legislatures in <LOCATION> Hesse </LOCATION> state. Recent polls have predicted the party might get more than 5 percent in the national elections in December 1990, permitting it to enter <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s federal parliament for the first time. Official <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> documents until now have described the Republicans as a `` radical'' rather than an `` extremist'' party. As such, the Republicans did not fall under automatic observation by the country's top internal security agency, the Verfassungsschutz. Groups judged `` extremist,'' whether rightist or leftist, are routinely watched by the agency. <PERSON> Stoiber </PERSON> said authorities will determine whether the Republicans might be qualified as `` extremist.'' If so, and their policies are contrary to the constitution, they might be banned, <PERSON> Stoiber </PERSON> said.
