<HEAD>Recalls, Warnings Issued for Children's Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A toy boat and three types of baby strollers are being recalled because of the danger of choking children, according to a government agency which also issued a warning about a type of crib toy. No reports of injuries have been received involving any of the products, the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. Toys `` R'' Us of <LOCATION> Paramus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, is recalling the `` Toot Toot Tug'' toy boat because a metal rod could become detached from the toy and possibly pose a choking hazard, the commission reported. About 5,200 of the toys were sold nationwide for about $ 4.99, and they can be returned for a refund, the commission said. The boats can be identified by the name `` Primex-Shyf 4768.'' The second recall involves baby strollers sold by <ORGANIZATION> McCrory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has its headquarters in <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. Plastic plugs sealing the tube ends on the strollers could come loose and pose a choking hazard, officials said. The strollers were sold nationally in McCrory stores as well as by <PERSON> Britt </PERSON>'s, <PERSON> Elmore </PERSON>, H.L. Green, <PERSON> Kittinger </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kress </PERSON>, <PERSON> McClellan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Newberry </PERSON>, Silver, <ORGANIZATION> TG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Y and some independent stores, according to the commission. Imported from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, the strollers involved are Model AT410 Item 129088 umbrella stroller; Model PHT438 item 128942 umbrella with canopy stroller, and Model PHT417, item 129007 canopy stroller. Owners of the strollers should discontinue using them and contact <PERSON> McCrory </PERSON> for details of a free modification kit. Write, including the stroller's item number and style, to <ORGANIZATION> McCrory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, Dept. 06-Mail Stop 0512, 2955 E. Market St., <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, 17402. In addition to the recalls, the commission issued a warning about a crib toy called Crib Kickers made by <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Calliope </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. These toys consist of a series of polyester-filled figures such as animals and flowers, attached to a ribbon for tying them across the top of a crib or playpen. Such toys can pose a danger of strangling to children once the infant is old enough to push itself up and possibly get caught in the ribbon. A warning is supposed to accompany such toys urging parents to remove them when children reach that stage of development. The commission said a warning was included in the box of the crib kicker, but was not attached to the toy, so it issued a public reminder of the danger.
