<HEAD>Paramount Launches $10.7 Billion Bid for Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with stock prices and judge
denying request. PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `The Paramount ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> shares rocketed in early trading today in a runup sparked by a $ 10.7 billion takeover offer from <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The offer rivals a merger agreement Time has with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Time jumped $ 43.50 to $ 169.50 a share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> After a delayed opening, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> was up $ 1.37 -LCB- to $ 53.12 -LCB- and <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> slipped 87 -LCB- cents to $ 53.12 -LCB-. Paramount, the entertainment and media company formerly known as <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, announced late Tuesday a tender offer of $ 175 a share cash for Time. The company also filed a lawsuit in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where Time is incorporated, to block provisions of the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> agreement that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said were aimed at thwarting competing offers. But a judge declined to immediately grant <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s request. The Paramount offer comes 2 -LCB- weeks before <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders are to vote on whether to approve the merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, a stock swap combination that would create the world's biggest media and entertainment company with $ 10 billion in annual revenue. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, who follows the entertainment industry for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the Paramount bid would provoke `` a much lengthier battle than Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> had anticipated.'' Paramount's bid is 60 percent above where Time stock was trading before the publishing and cable giant announced in March it had reached an agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. It's also 39 percent above Time's closing price Tuesday of $ 126 a share, up $ 2.75 from Monday's close. Paramount is the owner of <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>, whose films include the `` <ORGANIZATION> Crocodile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dundee </ORGANIZATION>,'' `` <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> Cop'' and `` Indiana Jones'' series. Its TV programs include `` Cheers'' and `` Family Ties.'' Paramount also owns publishers <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Schuster and Pocket Books. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive, said a marriage of his company and Time would create `` the foremost American communications company, capable of competing on a global scale against foreign media giants.'' That's also a goal of the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger plan. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> also owns a movie and TV production companies. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> said its board would review the proposal `` as required by law'' and urged its shareholders `` not to do anything until they hear from Time.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the company had no immediate comment. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> would make `` a superb business fit'' with <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest publishing company. `` We will have unequaled strength in quality magazine and book publishing, as well as in motion picture and television production and distribution, cable systems and cable programming'' he said. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said Time had essentially put itself up for sale by agreeing to merge with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> in a deal that would wind up giving <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s shareholders 60 percent of the new company. Nevertheless, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said it would withdraw its offer if Time shareholders approve the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> transaction on June 23. Until Tuesday, the planned <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger had sailed past every potential hurdle, but speculation had persisted that a bidder would emerge for Time, long a target of takeover rumors. Paramount's offer is subject to several conditions, including obtaining financing, the elimination of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s `` poison pill'' takeover defense, required regulatory approvals and ending a proposed lock-up stock swap between Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 384.7 million, or $ 3.21 a share, on revenue of $ 5.1 billion in its fiscal 1988, which ended Oct. 31. The company also owns Madison Square Garden in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Knicks </ORGANIZATION> basketball team and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION> hockey team, the <ORGANIZATION> MSG </ORGANIZATION> cable network. Time earned $ 289 million, or $ 5.01 a share, on revenue of $ 4.5 billion in its fiscal 1988 that ended Dec. 31. Time publishes such titles as Time, People, Sports Illustrated amd Fortune. It owns the book companies <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foresman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Little </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and controls the cable programmer <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Box </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
