<SECOND>AM-Avtex Resident, Bjt,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Resident Left in Subdivision Contaminated by Rayon Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRONT ROYAL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Before toxic chemicals from the Avtex Fibers plant seeped into the wells of homes across the <LOCATION> Shenandoah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Poland </PERSON>'s house was part of a neighborhood. The neighbors are gone. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and his wife are the only residents left in the Rivermont Acres subdivision, living alone on a dirt road that cuts through fields between cement blocks where other houses once stood. At the entrance to the road, a home-made sign reads `` Entering Water Pollution Area.'' The Polands' ranch house was one of a dozen small homes with back yards slanting down to the river, lined with trees that in summertime blocked the view of the 65-acre rayon plant on the opposite bank. <ORGANIZATION> Avtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fibers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> bought up most of the subdivision five years ago, when tests showed that groundwater had been contaminated by viscose and sulfate bases from the plant's holding ponds. But the purchases stopped short of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s house, the furthest upstream from the plant, because it is outside the contaminated zone, the company says. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> said many of the former residents of the subdivision have died of cancer, and he is worried about his and his wife's health. He'd like to sell the house and move, he said, but most real estate agents wo n't touch the property. `` I'm stuck and I know it,'' he said. `` They do n't have to do anything about it. What makes me so mad is they knowingly endangered the lives of everyone down here. They do n't do anything unless they're forced to do it.'' The Avtex holding ponds have n't been used since the contamination was discovered and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> declared the area a cleanup site in 1984 under the industry-financed Superfund law, said <PERSON> Avtex </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>. But pollution of the groundwater and the river has continued, state officials say. At a hearing last week on the plant's violations of state water pollution limits, state and <LOCATION> Avtex </LOCATION> officials alike described the 50-year-old plant as leaking chemicals through its floors and deteriorated sewer systems. <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> T.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markow </PERSON> is considering a state proposal to fine Avtex $ 140,000 for violating its agreement to comply with state water discharge limits. From the other side of the river, few of the aging plant's problems are visible, except an occasional patch of white gleaming on the river bottom and a cloudy brown plume of water spewing into the green river further downstream <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, 49, worked for Avtex for 17 years until quitting in 1981. He says the first sign of a problem in <LOCATION> Rivermont </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Acres </LOCATION> came in 1968, when a neighbor dug a well and found a smelly green substance at the bottom. The discovery led to more than a decade of official inquiries and tests of water in the subdivision. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> started bringing in his own drinking water in 1972, when his water started tasting bad. `` It smelled like sulfur,'' he said. At the same time, he started itching and having skin problems. `` The dog scratched for a week after a bath,'' he added. `` He do n't imagine things.'' In October 1981, the county health department advised residents that `` the well water in this area could be potentially hazardous to your health and you should not drink it.'' Wells in the area had been found to be contaminated with chromium, arsenic, cadmium, carbon disulfide and phenols, the department said. After the area was declared a Superfund site in 1984, <PERSON> Avtex </PERSON> offered to purchase all the plots in the subdivision except <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s. `` Mr. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s property is not within the contamination area,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. `` In July 1984 <PERSON> Avtex </PERSON> did an analysis of his well that proved to be standard for the area.'' After <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> complained to the company of itching after showers, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said <PERSON> Avtex </PERSON> agreed to provide him with water `` as a matter of courtesy.'' <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Avtex </PERSON> built him a 6,000 gallon reservoir at a cost of $ 8,000 and refills it each month. Tests have showed trace amounts of various chemicals in his groundwater, but <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> says officials have told him it's not Avtex-related. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> says he's resigned to staying at Rivermont Acres. And if the Avtex plant closes, as he expects it will, he'll go back to buying his own drinking water. `` I'm just fed up with the area,'' he said. `` It's peaceful in the summertime, but it's lonely as hell down here in the wintertime. You do n't see nobody.''
