<FIRST>u i AM-AIDS-Needles Bjt   06-07 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Needles, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Needles Essential to Stop AIDS in Addicts, Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Giving clean needles and syringes to drug addicts does not promote drug use and is essential for stopping the explosive spread of AIDS among narcotics abusers, a researcher said Wednesday. And, in a strikingly upbeat assessment, a leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health official who pioneered the first anti-AIDS drugs predicted that a cure for AIDS will be found. `` In the early 50s and 60s, there were many people who predicted there would be no progress against childhood leukemia. They were as wrong then as they are about AIDS now,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Broder </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. In an address at the Fifth International Conference on AIDS, <PERSON> Broder </PERSON> noted that AZT, the first approved anti-AIDS drug, has extended the lives of people with AIDS. A study of homosexual men showed that they had a 30 percent chance of surviving for 18 months with AIDS in 1982, but a 60 percent chance by 1987. `` I believe the widespread introduction of AZT is one factor that contributed to this,'' <PERSON> Broder </PERSON> said. He directed the development of AZT, also known as zidovudine. In another report Wednesday, researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said they eliminated any trace of the AIDS virus in a single AIDS patient who was given AZT and a transplant of bone marrow from a sister whose bone marrow type matched his. The experiment showed that bone marrow transplants could work in AIDS patients. Such treatment is unlikely ever to become widely available, however, because matching bone marrow can not always be found and because transplants are too expensive to be done on a large number of patients. Despite being cleansed of the AIDS virus, the patient died of cancer six weeks after the transplant. The study on drug addicts was reported by Dr. <PERSON> Roel </PERSON> <PERSON> Coutinho </PERSON> of the public health service in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> began providing needles to its addicts in 1984. Addicts spread AIDS by sharing needles and syringes, either because that is a customary practice or because needles and syringes are in short supply. Needle exchanges _ in which clean needles and syringes would be swapped for used needles and syringes _ were proposed to help stop sharing. Critics feared that such programs would encourage drug abuse. `` There is no evidence that the needle exchange increased intravenous drug use,'' <PERSON> Coutinho </PERSON> said. Sharing of needles among some addicts dropped from 56 percent of addicts to 16 percent in one study, <PERSON> Coutinho </PERSON> said. `` Apparely intravenous drug users are able to change their behavior,'' he said, if needles are available and if the addicts are given intensive counselling about AIDS and how it can be prevented. `` I think that providing needles and syringes is absolutely necessary,'' he said. <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> has only about 8,000 intravenous drug abusers, <PERSON> Coutinho </PERSON> said, making it much different from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, for example, where there are about 200,000. It is not clear, therefore, whether the lessons learned in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> would apply in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Preliminary results from a study of a recently begun needle exchange program in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> showed that drug abusers were less likely to share their needles and syringes and were more likely to clean them with bleach, which kills the AIDS virus. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Des </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarlais </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Substance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> concluded that the program was substantially reducing the risk of AIDS spread among addicts. A study in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> showed, however, that needle sharing fell when needles were provided, but that some addicts also stopped using condoms to prevent sexual spread of AIDS, and the incidence of AIDS infection among the addicts increased. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, needle sharing declined after an exchange program was started but 30 percent of the study's participants continued to share needles despite the best efforts of the program's organizers
</TEXT>
