<HEAD>One Killed in National Guard Tank Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two National Guard M-1 tanks collided at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harrison </LOCATION> today, killing one driver and seriously injuring the other, officials said. Sheriff <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said one of the 60-ton <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> battle tanks ended up on top of the other, causing severe damage to both. Authorities said the drivers were <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> employees performing technical checks on the recently arrived $ 1.8 million tanks. The accident occurred before 9 a.m. on a flat, open training ground, <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said. The cause was under investigation. The injured man was hospitalized in <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION>, <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> said. The M-1 has been used by the active <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> since 1982. It has a four-person crew and a top speed of 45 mph and fires a 105mm cannon. The <ORGANIZATION> Montana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> received 120 of the tanks during the winter as part of the reorganization of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s 163rd Armored Cavalry Regiment into a brigade, a larger unit with different duties. Guard units in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> also use the M-1.
