<HEAD>First Defendants Sentenced Get Short Halfway-House Terms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Wednesday gave short sentences in halfway houses to the first two defendants convicted in the Pentagon corruption investigation and said their trial had revealed purchasing practices that let consultants `` live a parasitic life off the government.'' `` I ca n't believe our government, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and executive, lets a system like this endure,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said in passing sentence on <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, vice presidents of <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> was given concurrent sentences of one year each on eight counts of conspiracy, wire fraud and false statements. All but six months of the term was suspended. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> drew concurrent sentences of one year each on one count of conspiracy and three counts of wire fraud, with all but three months of the sentence suspended. The judge directed that the two serve their time in halfway houses so that both men can continue to work. They have been on leave from their jobs. <PERSON> Berkeley </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, assistant to the president for public relations at <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent company of the electronics subsidiary, said by telephone from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> that he understood federal law prevented a defense contractor from employing a convicted felon. However, he said, the company `` will want to do the humanistic thing'' and would study the judge's ruling. After completing their time, <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> will be on probation for two years with orders to do 200 hours of unspecified community service. <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> was fined $ 30,000. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> was not fined. His lawyer told the court that <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> had no assets except a small equity in a house he bought last year with a <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> loan. <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> could have been sentenced to 40 years in prison and fined $ 2 million; <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, 20 years and $ 1 million. `` This trial was a window to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> procurement procedures,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` Those procedures are so outrageous that a world of so-called consultants, and as far as I am concerned that is another word for rogue, are permitted to live a parasitic life off the government,'' the judge said. A jury found the two guilty in April of participating in a scheme to hire defense consultant <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON>, who, in turn, bribed a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> official to obtain inside information that would help <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> get a $ 24 million contract for hand-held radar-detection kits. <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> pleaded guilty to bribery charges. Both he and <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> engineer who pleaded guilty to receiving nearly $ 5,000 in bribes from <LOCATION> Parkin </LOCATION>, were sentenced to 26 months in prison last week. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said a halfway house in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> area is expected to have an opening within 30 days and the men will remain free until then. He gave <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> until Aug. 2 to surrender so that he could attend his daughter's wedding July 29. Charges against a third <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> defendant who stood trial, <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnittjer </PERSON>, were dismissed after jurors were unable to reach a verdict in his case. A dozen other individuals and two corporations, including <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, have pleaded guilty in connection with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Operation Ill Wind'' investigation of military purchasing fraud. <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> pleaded guilty to conspiracy and making false statements. The company, based in <LOCATION> Newbury </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, has paid $ 4.3 million in penalties and fines.
