<HEAD>Solidarity, Communists Discuss Power-Sharing Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity plans to support progressive communist candidates in the June 18 runoff elections to build on its already stunning success in parliamentary elections, spokesmen said Wednesday. Communist officials, stung by their widespread rejection in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s freest elections since 1947, have been pushing Solidarity to join some sort of governing coalition with the party. The independent trade union has so far refused, saying it prefers to keep its freedom to criticize government policies. But its electoral dominance has severely undermined the authority of the communists and left questions about their ability to govern. The murky political situation following Sunday's election was expected to be the No. 1 topic Thursday when representatives of the two sides, led by Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, meet in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. Official voting results were expected to be issued either Wednesday night or Thursday, according to the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION>. The party has already conceded a `` decided'' defeat. Solidarity was limited by a political deal it struck with authorities in April to run for only 35 percent, or 161, of the 460 seats in the Sejm, the lower chamber of parliament. Solidarity says it already has won 160 of those seats, and that the remaining seat should be sealed up in the June 18 runoffs for candidates who failed to win 50 percent of the vote, the union said. But in most cases the candidates of the communist party and its allies, who ran for the remaining 299 Sejm seats, did not obtain the requisite 50 percent in the first round of voting and will have to participate in the second round. This gives Solidarity the opportunity to choose among the communist and allied candidates those who most nearly agree with Solidarity's program. `` Our opinion is that it is worthwhile to get engaged in the second round in order to present to our voters candidates who, in out estimation, are better candidates,'' <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> campaign chief <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON> told a news conference in the capital. `` We want to give all the candidates a chance to present their platforms to our voters and we will probably arrange meetings'' to discuss qualifications of the official side's candidates, he said. The meetings would be between the already elected Solidarity deputies and those hopefuls still in the running for the communist party or the allied Peasant and Democratic party seats, he said. <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON> noted that in Sunday's elections some communist-backed candidates already had shown they were more popular with voters than others, and that Solidarity would help make such people more widely known. Endorsement by Solidarity was virtually tantamount to being elected in the first round. If the same holds true June 18, Solidarity could be able to determine nearly the entire makeup of the Sejm. According to its unofficial tally, Solidarity already has won 92 of the possible 100 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats and its candidates who must enter the runoffs generally were the highest vote getters in their districts. After the runoffs, it appeared possible the union would hold all 100 seats. Still undecided is what to do about the 35 seats reserved for prominent communist and government officials who were allowed to run opposed. All the candidates had to do was win 50 percent of the vote, but voters reportedly have overwhelmingly rejected them. <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON> and national Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> shed little light at the news conference on the progress of talks to determine how to fill those seats that are expected to be vacant. According to Solidarity, among the defeated is Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>, Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and six other members on the ruling 17-member Politburo. Solidarity has promised to allow the party to fill the seats even though its candidates were defeated. Under the April accord that made the elections possible and resulted in Solidarity's legalization, Solidarity ceded 65 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> to the communists and their affiliated groups Solidarity and government representatives held informal talks Tuesday on the issue, but nothing was resolved and the union says it still awaits the government's proposed solutions. <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> would discuss it further at Thursday's full meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Arbitration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a panel set up to resolve any conflicts between the government and opposition stemming from their historic accord that liberalized <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s election process `` We will learn there what are the possibilities for solving this problem,'' <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said.
