<HEAD>Governors Urge Long-Term Energy Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's governors urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday to try anew to forge a long-term national energy policy, and said it should include tax and price incentives for the development of domestic resources, even in currently restricted wilderness and offshore areas. Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, presenting recommendations of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> after an 18-month study, declared `` the nation simply may not be able to afford to permanently remove prospectively valuable -LRB- oil and gas -RRB- areas off its shores, in vast areas of the West and in the Arctic.'' `` As a personal note,'' he added, `` it is my belief that we can not afford to foreclose development in the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>,'' even in the wake of the environmental furor over the damage caused by the massive spill of the Exxon Valdez oil tanker. `` Any development in currently restricted areas can and must comply with the strictest environmental safeguards, including standards for tanker safety,'' he said. <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> noted the governors also recommended the export of Alaskan oil on a barrel-for-barrel trade basis with other nations. He said the current prohibition against such exports `` reflects the political situation at the time the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> pipeline legislation was passed, not the real workings of the oil markets or the economic realities of oil trade.'' `` I am convinced that such trades would be economically beneficial, given the high transport cost of moving Alaskan oil to <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> refineries, where much of it goes today,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on economic stabilization. `` The nation would not lose oil supplies as the result of these transactions.'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>, who was joined by representatives of the governors of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, acknowledged that `` energy issues are not a central concern to most people today,'' despite memories of the oil shocks of the 1970s. `` However,'' he said, `` I come before you ... to say that complacency is both unwarranted and dangerous.'' The trends are `` in the wrong direction,'' he said. `` Domestic oil production is down, oil production in other stable and ` friendly' nations is down as a percentage of world oil production, the concentration of oil productive capacity in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> is up, and domestic oil consumption is up. In the transportation sector alone, the nation now uses more oil than it produces.'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> noted the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imported more than 43 percent of the oil it consumed last year, and the bill accounted for more than one-fourth of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. `` What is more,'' he said, `` after nearly 15 years of improvement in our efficiency of energy use, the most recent figures from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> indicate that our energy efficiency has started to decline. We use twice as much energy per unit of GNP as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and nearly twice that of our European trading partners.'' He said the governors want <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to take a hard look at a variety of incentives for domestic oil and gas exploration and for coal, including standard investment tax credits on exploration and the deregulation of natural gas wellhead prices. In 1977, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed a law requiring the president to develop and send to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> comprehensive 5 - and 10-year energy plans, and to update them every two years Despite that law, said Rep. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, head of the subcommittee, `` this country has no national energy policy plan worthy of the name.'' The last plan submitted by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in 1986, totaled a mere two pages, she pointed out. Ms. <PERSON> Oakar </PERSON> said `` the nation has been asleep on energy security for the past eight years, and that is why the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil spill was a wakeup call for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.''
