<HEAD>Massacre Blackens Name of People's Army</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>A version of this report moved for PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six days into a bloody crackdown to suppress a peaceful movement for freedom, the Chinese army has failed to pacify <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. There are numerous reports of clashes between units of the army that may be loyal to different political factions. The massacre Saturday and Sunday of hundreds of people blackened the name of an army onced famed for its bravery and selflessness. Troops once affectionately called `` brother of the people'' and `` Uncle PLA-man'' quickly were termed `` running dogs'' and `` fascists'' by citizens enraged at the killings of relatives and friends by their own army. The events in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> have raised some questions about the discipline and readiness of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest army with an active force of more than 2 million soldiers. Simple barricades of metal fencing stopped tanks and other heavy equipment, breaking the drive trains of the vehicles, copies of 1950's Soviet models. Other trucks broke down in the road. The government announced Tuesday that 364 military vehicles, mostly tanks and armored personnel carriers, were burned by unarmed citizens. Tear gas used against the tens of thousands of people who came out to stop the troops had little effect. One canister that landed near an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter briefly made his eyes sting and head spin. The effects soon wore off. Communications among military units also appeared poor. On Wednesday, troops on one <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> bridge scurried behind trees, concrete fences and trucks as if an attack were imminent. The assault never came. On at least two occasions, armored personnel carriers, driven at high-rates of speed, crushed foot soldiers. Reports of dissension among commanders is adding to the chaos. On Tuesday, armies supporting rival factions clashed in front of the downtown Military Museum. On Wednesday, thousands of troops moved onto an intersection then retreated, as if preparing for urban warfare. Troops show a lack of discipline by firing randomly into crowds of unarmed citizens. Shots in the air have killed people in high-rise apartment buildings. The windows of one compound housing foreigners was riddled by 27 bullet holes Wednesday. An armored personnel carrier crushed at least seven students in a group of thousands that retreated peacefully from <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. The army's violence has shocked <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> residents. Until the weekend, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> held an important position in the hearts of many citizens in this capital. Formed in 1927, the army was famed not only for its fighting prowess but for its rescue work during disasters and the critical help it provided to peasants harvesting crops. `` The army goes with the people like fish swims through water,'' was a popular proverb. The <ORGANIZATION> PLA </ORGANIZATION> played a key role in the revolution. Heeding closely the order of Marshal <PERSON> Zhu </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> `` not to steal a pin from the people,'' the army gained the affection of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s peasantry as it battled the corrupt Nationalists, or Koumintang, and invading Japanese. Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s founder, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>, recognized this role in his famous saying: `` Political power grows out of the barrel of a gun.'' But now the gun has been aimed on the common people. `` I lived through the Japanese occupation and the Kuomintang corruption,'' said a 65-year-old man. `` Never have I seen anything like this. The army comes from the people. How can it kill the people? `` <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Tieguo </PERSON>, a soldier until last year, said he had been proud to be a veteran of the army, but that turned to horror when he saw troops kick a 12-year-old girl in the chest and crush her heart. `` When I saw these hooligans kill that girl I was disgusted with myself,'' he said. `` Can these people be my comrades ever again? `` The army was one of the four pillars of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s modernization program started by <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> more than a decade ago. So important is the military to <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s planning that the only title he has retained is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Under <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s policies, the army has undergone a massive reform designed to turn it into a professional fighting force. It has decommissioned more than 1 million troops and purchased vast quantities of materiel from the West. But problems remain. Clashes among units of the army in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> indicate the army has failed to end the factionalism that has plagued the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military since the warlord period 80 years ago. Its seven regional armies are clearly not all loyal to the same political commanders. The quality of its soldiers also remains suspect. Official media reports quotes random surveys as saying about one-third of the troops are illiterate and say deaf mutes and mental cases have been accepted as conscripts.
