<FIRST>r a AM-InfantLungs     06-07 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infant Lungs,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Synthetic Cortisone Improves Lungs of Premature Babies, Study Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cortisone shots appear to speed the recovery of premature babies with lung disease, helping them get off respirators significantly more quickly than usual, a study concludes. Doctors gave the synthetic form of cortisone called dexamethasone to tiny infants with bronchopulmonary dysplasia, a form of lung disease common in babies born with immature lungs. They said that the babies treated this way suffered no ill effects from the medicine and seemed to avoid some of the complications of months on mechanical breathing machines. The study, directed by Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, was published in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine. However, an accompanying editorial by Dr. <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stahlman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, cautioned that studies done at single hospitals on small numbers of patients often fail to hold up when repeated on larger numbers at groups of hospitals. `` An effective and safe treatment for bronchopulmonary dysplasia is urgently needed,'' she wrote, `` but more definitive data from a multicenter trial will be required before the use of dexamethasone can be widely recommended.'' In the study, doctors gave 42 days of dexamethasone to 13 babies who weighed less than 2.7 pounds. For comparison, they gave 18 days of the drug to 12 babies and placebos to 11 others. Those who got the full course of dexamethasone were weaned off the respirators after a median of 29 days, compared with 73 days for those who got less medicine and 84 days for the babies in the placebo group. The babies getting full dexamethasone also were more likely to have normal neurological development.
</TEXT>
