<SECOND>AM-Holocaust Pennies,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Gestapo Prisoner Raising a Penny for Each of 6 Million Slain
Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Polish immigrant who escaped the World War II Holocaust is directing a one-man effort to collect a penny of remembrance for each of the 6 million Jews killed by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. `` During the war,'' said <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON>, `` a Jewish life was n't worth a penny. In the past two years, he has gathered $ 24,000 toward his goal of $ 60,000 in pennies, which will be donated to the proposed <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Holocaust Memorial Museum in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. While <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON>, 75, and his wife and daughter survived, he said it's important to remember the millions who did not. `` Not only to perpetuate the memory, but to alert the present and future generations who think this can never happen again,'' he said Wednesday. As vice president of the museum's <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> chapter, <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON> also is helping direct a $ 10 million fund-raising effort in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area. But pennies make it easy to donate, even for children, he said. `` From mouth to mouth, we let our friends know about the project,'' <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON> said. `` One woman called me to say she had 50 pounds of pennies. ... When I go down to the store with my wife and they give me change, maybe 50 cents, I say, ` Will you be so kind to give me the change in pennies?''' The donations, still in pennies, are delivered from time to time to the museum committee in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pela </PERSON>, his wife of 53 years, were born and educated in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. His father and in-laws were killed at the <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION> concentration camp, and he said about 150 members of his extended family lost their lives in the Holocaust. For a while, <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON> said, he and his wife escaped capture. `` I looked very Aryan _ blond-haired, blue-eyed,'' he said. But in February 1942, his luck ran out and he spent five months in prison before he escaped. Later, he smuggled his 18-month-old daughter out of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> by drugging her with the help of a physician and placing her in a tiny casket. His wife accompanied the casket to a Jewish cemetery outside <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, while <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON> left the city by another route. The family reunited at a prearranged spot and with forged identity papers were able to live as non-Jewish Poles outside <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. `` It's the only case in the Holocaust when a child was saved as a dead child,'' said <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON>. When they came to this country in 1948, <PERSON> Starkopf </PERSON> said he had $ 3 in his pocket. Eight years ago, he retired from the sporting goods-import company he started. The daughter, <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Brainin </PERSON>, 47, is married with two children and lives in suburban <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
