<LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Thursday, said Sgt. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Riberdy </PERSON>, assistant military attache. `` There is a situation in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> which seems to be worsening and we have been thinking that we might not be able to get people out later,'' <PERSON> Riberdy </PERSON> said. He said only about 15 of the embassy's 45 staff members would remain. Japanese Embassy staff members telephoned nationals in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> urging them to leave by commercial flights or on Japanese airliners scheduled to arrive Thursday. A West German diplomat said his embassy was trying to arrange a special special flight to evacuate Germans on Friday. <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tatarata </PERSON>, vice consul of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, said Filipinos would be flown out Thursday. <PERSON> Eugenio </PERSON> <PERSON> Campo </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Italian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said it was urging Italians to leave but would not send any diplomats home. He estimated 30 percent of about 220 Italians in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had left or were planning to do so. A duty officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said there were no plans for personnel to leave. The Soviet complement of 77 registered diplomats is second only to the Americans, with 120.
