<HEAD>At Least 12 Percent of Children Have Mental Disorders: Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As many as 14 million American children suffer from some mental disorder, a problem that is costing society billions of dollars and depriving the nation of productive citizens, according to a study released Wednesday. `` There is a stigma associated with mental illness and there is a major problem in how children's problems are perceived,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, the chairman of an <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> committee that prepared the study. Mentally ill children have historically been `` underserved,'' he said, noting that `` this is a clear and persistent problem in our society.'' Although the committee said millions of youngsters are not receiving the mental therapy they need, <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON> said the study was `` an optimistic report'' because the last two decades have witnessed breakthroughs in understanding, preventing and correcting many childhood mental diseases. The committee recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> be given annual budget increases to develop research and to train professionals to deal with the specific mental illnesses of those under 18. `` We must examine our priorities as a nation ... to ensure that these real and persistent problems no longer place in jeopardy our most valuable resource _ future generations of productive citizens,'' <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON> said. The report said that a conservative estimate says 12 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children are mentally disturbed, but that the true number could be as high as 22 percent, or about 14 million. <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON> added, `` The likelihood is that the rate is increasing.'' Of the mentally ill, members of the committee said, only 20 percent to 33 percent receive care. Some studies, the experts said, say the majority of mentally ill children are never even diagnosed by parents, teachers and doctors. `` For the physically handicapped, the evidence is that 80 percent of those are served,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Fredric </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, director of the mental health division of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. `` Yet for serious emotional disturbance, the evidence is that less than 30 and maybe less than 20 percent are served, even when they are noticed.'' <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said studies have shown that even medical professionals, such as pediatricians, generally recognize only about about one-fourth of their patients who are suffering from mental disorders. He said often the children who receive attention are those with disruptive behavior. Dr. <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>, vice chairman of the committee and a professor of psychiatry at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said studies have shown a definite increase in childhood suicides and in eating disorders. The report identified a variety of problems besetting <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children These include developmental impairments that slow education and learning; emotional disturbances that include anxiety, depression or both, and behavioral problems that include disruptive and antisocial acts. Some of those problems manifest themselves as chronic drug use, sexual problems and eating disorders. Poverty and associated `` harsh child-raising methods'' contribute heavily to the number of troubled youth, the experts said. The report noted that youngsters with mental and behavioral problems `` may exceed 20 percent in some populations, such as inner-city children, who are exposed to severe psychological adversity.'' The total cost to the nation has not been measured, but <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON> said it is `` enormous.'' `` Billions of dollars are spent each year in direct service delivery,'' said <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON>. `` Added to this is the tremendous emotional burden carried by their families. `` Childhood depression, left untreated, may lead to suicide,'' he said. Some disorders, such as autism, may be a lifelong disability; other mental problems may lead to drug abuse and criminal behavior. `` Despite the distress and misery and great costs to society, relatively few resources have been directed at efforts to advance our knowledge,'' said <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON>. The committee said that the nation needs to invest in fundamental research to learn how to treat such children and to train specialists who can conduct research and treatment. `` There are fewer than 100 child psychiatrists who devote 30 percent of their time to research,'' <PERSON> Leckman </PERSON> said. `` The figures are equally dismal in psychology, pediatrics, social work and special education.'' The committee recommended a nationwide plan directed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> to nurture careers in childhood mental health and to sponsor research into methods of preventing, detecting and treating mental illness in children. The report called for a national investment that would grow to $ 198 million annually by the fifth year. The Institute of Medicine is part of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, a private organization chartered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as an adviser to the federal government in scientific and technical matters.
</TEXT>
