<FIRST>r i AM-China-LetterFromBeijing     06-07 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Letter From Beijing,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoarding, Dodging Soldiers Beijing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITORS NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> has reported for the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> since 1987. She lives next to the foreign compound that was fired at by troops early Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 I woke to gunfire Wednesday morning. I almost rolled over and went back to sleep. The sound of guns has become routine since hundreds of thousands of soldiers rolled into downtown <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> last weekend and drove student protesters from <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. Instead, I dashed to a window that overlooks <LOCATION> Changan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s main east-west street, where dozens of tanks and trucks of troops were parked two blocks west of my apartment. Peering over the sill, I could see no violence: only a few dozen Chinese bicycling under a grim, gray sky, skirting torn up road dividers. But the import of the shots became clear later. Chinese authorities claimed someone had fired on the troops marching along <ORGANIZATION> Changan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> from a foreigner's apartment in the compound next to mine. Dozens of soldiers took up positions outside the compound, pointing their rifles at the buildings. Some fired at the buildings, reportedly knocking out windows. Dozens more closed the compound gates while plainclothes officials searched inside. Eerily, a loudspeaker on an army vehicle began playing gentle music. `` Do they want to fight or do they want to dance?'' asked a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> employee watching from a stairwell in the compound. The simple act of closing the compound gates touched off panic in the foreign community. Those locked inside gathered to plead with the impassive soldiers to be let out. `` I have a plane ticket and they wo n't let me out to catch the plane,'' said a European diplomat. A Soviet reporter pleaded in vain for permission to evacuate five children. A long line of cars from various embassies formed outside. After two hours, plainclothes officials collared a Chinese man who they said fired at the troops, and brought him out to the soldiers. Abruptly, they formed lines and trotted off. The gates opened, and hundreds of residents rushed to cars and vans, some bound for the airport and some for hotels further from the troop positions. All but a small group of residents also left the compound where The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> has its office and several staff apartments. `` Yes, we are brave,'' boasted a Bulgarian diplomat who stayed behind. A Bulgarian woman living two floors down from him opened her door only after much persuasion and perspired with anxiety. `` Be careful, it's not safe out there anywhere,'' she urged. More shops were open Wednesday than earlier in the crackdown, but business was slow. Far fewer vendors appeared with fruits and vegetables. I loaded as much as I could into my knapsack and bicycle basket. Eggplant and stringbeans were available Tuesday, but only cabbages and tomatoes were in the shops on Wednesday. Prices were heavily inflated, cutting into my dwindling cash supply. Banks are closed. The government warned that water and electricty might be cut if order is not restored, and I went home and filled jars and buckets with water. Gas stations closed early in the turmoil. The driver of one of the few taxis still operating said he was charging a minumum of $ 50 for the airport trip, usually a $ 9 fare. He talked one desperate passenger into paying $ 1,000, he said. The International Hotel sent guests a cheery letter Wednesday inviting them to a cocktail party with the management and hoping their stay would be `` memorable.'' But a second letter warned, `` Stay off the balconies and keep your heavy curtains closed.'' Away from the foreign neighborhood, the mood of panic eased. Most Chinese were too nervous to travel to work, but they relaxed within their walled stone homes in the narrow alleyways. Old men played Chinese chess on a canal bank, oblivious to rifle-toting soldiers who roamed a nearby alley in groups of two and three. One man called out to me: `` Have you been shot at yet?'' Two colleagues were. AP reporter <PERSON> Terrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said non-uniformed security forces marching in formation down <LOCATION> Changan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> shot at him twice as he stood outside the International Hotel taking photographs. He fled to the hotel entrance, only to find the door boarded from the inside. AP reporter <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Biers </PERSON> was on <ORGANIZATION> Changan </ORGANIZATION> further east when an army truck approached from the north with soldiers firing out the rear. He took shelter behind a tree.
</TEXT>
