 The City Council has voted to sever ties with the local <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lodge </ORGANIZATION>, a major contributor to its youth programs, following the group's recent rejection of two black applicants. The council voted 6-0 Tuesday to support Mayor <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodge </PERSON>'s call to block donations from the 1,800-member lodge to city-sponsored youth programs The lodge donated $ 24,000 last year for disabled children. `` Let the <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> know that if the financial contributions are tainted with racism, the city does n't accept it,'' said <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON>, president of the local chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People. Elks leaders said the lodge does not condone racism, blaming the rejections of the black applicants last month on a small minority of members. It only takes three votes from the entire membership to turn down an applicant. <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Wodarczak </PERSON>, the local group's exalted ruler, noted that the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> lodge has joined other central coast lodges in urging the national Elks organization to change voting rules to admit more minority members.
