<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As luck would have it, the student who won a car at a post-prom party was the one who could n't take it home. <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON> is an exchange student from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gallen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. He won the 1981 Dodge Aries at an all-night, post-prom party sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s chapter of Students Against Driving Drunk. The party last month featured music by a disc jockey, volleyball, baketball and swimming. A car dealership in <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> donated the car as an incentive for students to attend the party, an alternative to drinking and driving after the prom. `` It was very early in the morning and I was very tired, but I of course was very happy. I never won a car before,'' said <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON>, 18. He said he would have to sell the car because he does n't have a driver's license, his stay in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is almost over and it would be too expensive to ship home and convert to use with European gasoline. Also, <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON>, who speaks his native Swiss-German dialect as well as fluent English, German, French and some Italian, said he wo n't really need a car when he goes back to finish high school in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gallen </LOCATION>, a city of 76,000 in northeast <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> `` You could get around with public transportation and a little bit of walking,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Neither sleet nor rain, snow nor heat nor dead of night will stop the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mail. But dive-bombing sparrows? Now that's a different story. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has discontinued deliveries to the <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> family home because the carrier considers birds nesting above it a hazard. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> said the nest is in the rafters of the porch, about four feet above the mail box. And the carrier reportedly told his superiors the bird `` dive bombs'' him when he attempts to deliver the mail. `` I really ca n't understand the reasoning,'' <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> said. `` The nest was built by a sparrow and most people do n't consider sparrows to be dangerous birds.'' <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> said he and other family members have called postal officials, but were told if carriers feel there is a hazardous situation they must deal with, they do not have to deliver the mail to a home. Postmaster <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaleski </PERSON> said he was informed of the problem Tuesday and will take steps to rectify the situation. `` I will contact the family,'' <PERSON> Zaleski </PERSON> said, `` and see if we ca n't work out an alternate delivery plan. I have to consider the safety of the carrier and if he thinks there is a hazard I have to respect his thoughts.''
