<HEAD>Pope Urges World Leaders To Promote Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OEM, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Wednesday called on world leaders to seize this `` moment of extraordinary awakening'' and push ahead with efforts to promote freedom and human rights. Later, he warned Roman Catholics in affluent <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> against the dangers of `` slavery to self under the guise of freedom'' and the indiscriminate pursuit of material goods. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, on the seventh day of a Scandinavian tour, addressed diplomats in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION> and then flew to Oem, a tourist center on the <LOCATION> Jutland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. There, he celebrated Mass for 10,000 people on the ruins of a medieval monastary. Speaking of what he said were worldwide winds of change, the pope told diplomats: `` Mine is an invitation to you, to all men and women with responsibility for the public life of nations, to do everything possible to encourage this moral awakening,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said. He called on his audience `` to further the peaceful processes which seek to implement freedom, respect for human dignity and human rights throughout the world.'' The <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said despite this century's wars and political tensions, as well as the afflictions of international drug trafficking and AIDS, there was reason for hope. `` The world is living through a moment of extraordinary awakening. The old problems remain, and new ones arise,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said. `` But there is also a growing awareness of an opportunity being offered to give birth to a new and better era.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> did n't mention specific countries, but he has previously expressed his approval of political reforms in his native <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and elsewhere. A Maronite Christian woman holding up a <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> flag and a group of Polish folk dancers were among those at Oem. About 20 Asian children pressed around the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> for blessings as he arrived. Immigrants, mostly from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and from <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> countries in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, have flocked to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s appearances throughout <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, an overwhelmingly Lutheran region. Danish Catholics number only 28,000. The pope also met priests, nuns and representatives of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> community To them he spoke of the sexual and family mores in this liberal society. He said church teaching called for `` lifelong fidelity in marriage, responsible parenthood ... reverence for every human person from the moment of conception until natural death, the equal and complementary dignity of women and men.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, who has also visited <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> on his Scandinavian tour, travels to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> on Thursday. He returns to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Saturday.
