<HEAD>Navy Will End Cruise-Missile Engine Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 1978 agreement requiring the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to buy cruise-missile engines from a defense contractor in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> is illegal and will be canceled, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has told a senator in a letter made public Wednesday. According to the letter, dated April 11, from then-Navy Undersecretary <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> to Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., the open-ended, multimillion-dollar agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walled </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, was negotiated by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON>, a consultant and a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> employee, and the former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> engineer he bribed were given 26-month prison terms June 2 for illegally scheming to help two companies get Pentagon contracts. <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON> were each fined $ 25,000 and ordered to serve two years of supervised probation after their release from prison. <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> pleaded guilty to charges that he bribed <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> to provide secret <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> bid information that would help <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hazeltine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, obtain lucrative contracts to sell electronic equipment to the Pentagon. The <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> letter to <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> was made public by the Project on Military Procurement, a Washington-based whistle-blower group. <PERSON> Danielle </PERSON> <PERSON> Brian-Bland </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the group, declined to say how the letter was obtained. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> sought comment from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on the agreement. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s press office said it was unable to provide information immediately. Both the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s office confirmed the existence of the <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> letter. The agreement guarantees <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> a certain level of engine sales to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Without the agreement, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> would be required to compete for contracts with <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the other supplier of the engines. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is fighting the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> negotiated the agreement in order to provide the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> with a second source for cruise missiles, said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustitus </PERSON>, staff director of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on oversight of government operations, which <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> heads. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> licensed some of its technology to <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> and, in return, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agreed to buy at least 240 engines a year from <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, plus 25 percent of any additional purchases up to 1,200 engines annually. The agreement `` contains no ending date and purports to apply not just to the contract with which its negotiation was associated but to ` all government contracts for F107 engines, its derivatives and associated logistic items having cruise-missile applications,''' wrote <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON>, who is now secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, under the agreement, must contract through <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> in buying engines from <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> has been paid about $ 36,000 for each of the 708 engines built by <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> wrote. Such provisions violate a 1984 amendment to defense purchasing legislation designed to ensure competition in Pentagon procurement because it binds the government to reward future contracts, <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> was an author of the amendment. In a May 12 letter, made public by <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contracting officer, <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, told <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> the agreement was n't authorized by purchasing laws in effect when the deal was negotiated The F107 engine is used in sea-based Tomahawk cruise missiles. `` The government ought to keep its word,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` The government made a contract, and under the Constitution, you can not abrogate a contract.'' The 1984 law applies only to new agreements, not to existing ones, and so the agreement with <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is within the law, <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said. `` I do n't concede in any way the 1984 law was violated by the contract even if it came after the 1984 law,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' vice president for public relations, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jolivette </PERSON>, declined to discuss the issue on the advice of counsel, saying the matter had not yet been resolved.
