<HEAD>Floods Recede; Death Toll Reaches 315</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flood waters slowly receded Wednesday in central and southern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> after five days of storms and mudslides that killed at least 315 people, officials said. Rescue workers carrying food and medicine Wednesday reached stranded inland hill areas that were worst hit by the rains, which began Saturday night, according to D.J. Wijesundera, of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> More than 200,000 people were left homeless, including 60,000 who were forced to flee <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>'s northern suburbs, <PERSON> Wijesundera </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Kelaniya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which winds north of the capital to the sea, surged over its banks Tuesday, but dropped again by about an inch Wednesday, according to <PERSON> Upali </PERSON> <PERSON> Delpechitra </PERSON>, of the Irrigation Department. `` The waters are expected to recede very slowly,'' he said. Walls of sand bags were put up along the river banks to protect villages near <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, he said. Most of the deaths occurred in the hills and valleys of the <LOCATION> Kegalle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, about 45 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Entire villages of thatched huts were buried after a torrential downpour on Saturday triggered landslides of mud and rocks already loosed by a month-long monsoon. Meanwhile, in <LOCATION> Teldeniya </LOCATION>, 60 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, police opened fire on students protesting the presence of Indian soldiers on the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> island. At least one person was killed and six others were injured, when students tried to storm a police station, police said. There are 40,000 Indian soldiers in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> under a 1987 Peace accord to end a 6-year-old Tamil separatist movement. President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> last week asked <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to withdraw its troops by the end of July but <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> has refused. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved in the ethnic conflict of its southern neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause. Tamils are 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. Tamils say they are discriminated against by the majority <PERSON> Sinhalese </PERSON>, who make up 75 percent of the population.
