</ORGANIZATION> joined him in appealing to Uzbeks and <PERSON> Meshki </PERSON> <PERSON> Turks </PERSON>, both of whom are traditionally Moslem, to halt the bloodshed. It was the second such appeal issued this week. The Turkish minority, which adopted Islam centuries ago, has been pressing its demands to be allowed to return to its ancestral homeland in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> since the national parliament began meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> late last month. Authorities charged with keeping order in the <LOCATION> Fergana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> openly admitted the situation was still volatile and ethnic hatreds keen. Despite the heavy military and police presence, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported that as recently as Tuesday night gunshots were heard in several neighborhoods in <LOCATION> Fergana </LOCATION>. The violence was the latest ethnic dispute to erupt in the southern <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where disputes in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> region and in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> have killed scores of people and left thousands homeless. A national outcry followed the use of chemicals, shovels and clubs by soldiers who broke up a pro-independence rally in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> on April 9. Nineteen civilians were killed in the assault, and one was later shot by soldiers for violating curfew. In his remarks to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> seemed to demand a firm but measured response in dealing with the <LOCATION> Fergana </LOCATION> violence. `` The developments in <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> show once again that we should be patient, reserved and alert and should bear responsibility for our actions in everything, especially in what concerns inter-ethnic relations,'' the Soviet leader said.
