<HEAD>Summary of Developments in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Wednesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ARMY IN BEIJING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Indiscriminate firing by soldiers in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> continued. Armed patrols marched near <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> and tanks and troops raced along main avenues firing at random. Soldiers in one convoy chanted: `` We love the people, we love the capital,'' then opened fire, scattering crowds. Several deaths of citizens were reported.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GOVERNMENT ANNOUNCEMENTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 State television broadcast a statement from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> threatening expulsion and severe punishment for any members found to have `` plotted, organized and led the rebellion.'' Another announcement said soldiers were authorized to `` forcibly dispose of, on the spot'' anyone who resisted arrest.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FOREIGNERS EVACUATE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> ordered the evacuation from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic dependents and non-essential personnel and is urging all other Americans `` to leave at once.'' Previously, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> had urged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens only to leave <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Foreign embassies were arranging flights for diplomatic and civilian evacuees. However, a Soviet Embassy officer said there were no plans for their personnel to leave.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MILITARY ACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of troops in trucks accompanied by tanks and armored personnel carriers departed in two large convoys, heading east. Their destination was not clear. No major battle between supposedly rival military units has taken place, but a witness said the 27th and 38th armies fought each other early Wednesday east of downtown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DIPLOMATIC COMPOUND FIRED UPON</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers sprayed bullets at a diplomatic compound then surrounded it in what they said was a search for a sniper. The compound was sealed off for two hours and security officials took a Chinese man away. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lilley </PERSON> protested to <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities about rifle fire that broke windows at apartments occupied by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employees, but said there were no injuries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER CITIES AND PROVINCES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Turmoil spread to more than a dozen provincial cities, where crowds blocked major roads and railways with barricades in anticipation of military assaults. Six people manning a barricade were run over by a train near the <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> railway station Tuesday night. <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> radio said angry crowds set the train ablaze.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>US-CHINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to stop arms sales and military contacts was a `` detriment to bilateral relations.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> condemned the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for giving refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> to dissident <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> and said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was interfering in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s internal affairs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WORLD REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Governments and citizens worldwide continue to protest the Chinese action with rallies, marches, and suspensions of exchange programs. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> became the first Soviet bloc nation to denounce the military crackdown in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> announced it will end a 40-year ban on telephone and mail links with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to help spread reports of the carnage.
