<HEAD>House Members Call for Greater Federal Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel on aging said Wednesday the federal government should do more to help states combat the growing problem of abuse and neglect of the elderly. How much abuse there is can not be documented, but only a fraction of the cases are reported to state authorities, the panel was told. `` Members want to see the national government play a more active role,'' Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, told <PERSON> Michio </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>, acting deputy commissioner of the Administration on Aging in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, at a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee hearing. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, chairman of the human services subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging, acknowledged that the federal effort has been hamstrung by lack of public awareness of the problem and cuts in available funds. funding cutbacks. But, he said, `` We're prepared to give you more resources.'' Rep. <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Slaughter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, questioned how <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>'s agency could address the problem without a clear picture of its national scope, and added: `` I'm not sure a federal passive role is going to help.'' <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> rejected the description of his agency as `` passive.'' He said the office plays `` an active role in a supporting role'' by providing assistance to states. `` The Administration on Aging has long recognized that prevention of elder abuse is primarily a state responsibility and a state prerogative,'' he told the panel. But <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> and other members noted that the federal government has made many efforts to take the lead in fighting child abuse, including monitoring state activities. `` It seems to me that what would be of national interest in the younger years of life would be of national concern in the older years of life,'' he said. <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> said the federal agency has not evaluated individual state efforts to prevent abuse and neglect of older Americans, but is `` trying to be responsive'' to states' needs in developing programs, supplying educational materials and enhancing public awareness. Though states are not required to spend any of the money they get from the agency on protective services, 40 states do allocate some of their federal funds to these services, he said. `` States are as interested in this as we are,'' he said. <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> said his agency relies on the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on Elder Abuse to gather information on the scope of the problem and the efforts of the states. The center, operated by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Units </ORGANIZATION> on Aging and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION>, receives federal funds. <PERSON> Toshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Tatara </PERSON>, director of the center, testified that because the reporting systems in many states are incomplete, it is impossible to estimate accurately the extent of the problem. He said state surveys turned up 140,000 reports of abuse of the elderly last year, but he said that represents only a fraction of the incidents. One study found that only one of 14 cases gets reported, which would mean that last year there would have been nearly 2 million `` reportable'' cases, he said. `` Elder abuse is far less likely to be reported than child abuse, about which the public has gained greater awareness of the problem than it has about elder abuse,'' he said. <PERSON> Tatara </PERSON> called for better coordination of federal programs and regulations. As an example, he cited a federal <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid policy that he said contributes to patient `` neglect.'' Under that policy, the cost of a medical device that prevents bed sores is not covered, though the cost of treating bed sores is, he said.
