<HEAD>Foreign Evacuees Tell Terrifying Stories of Escape</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf `Gasoline is...' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
quotes from Frankfurt; picks up 11th, `One American...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreigners fleeing <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> were returning to their homes Wednesday with terrifying stories of the killings they saw and the chaos they left behind. They flew to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and other cities after several countries ordered their citizens to leave the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> capital, where soldiers have killed or wounded thousands of people in crushing a pro-democracy movement. `` I saw a soldier's body, burned, hanging from the bridge. That made me get the hell out of there,'' Australian tourist <PERSON> Jimie </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. He said people told him the soldier had killed children and women. `` We were shot at by the tanks at the Peking Hotel doorway. They were shooting at anything that moved,'' said <PERSON> Yves </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON>, a French tour guide, after arriving in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> with a group of 40 tourists. `` I came out to the veranda of the Minzu Hotel to see what was happening and gunfire from a tank hit the veranda about 50 centimeters -LRB- 20 inches -RRB- above my head,'' Japanese businessman <PERSON> Ryoichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kikukawa </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, an English teacher from <LOCATION> Ithaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, got up before dawn Wednesday to line up for a ticket on the same <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight. As he was about to enter a taxi in front of his hotel, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said, he threw himself to the ground because of gunfire from soldiers, which shattered windows on upper floors. `` I think it was their way of telling us to get back inside,'' he said. White expressed concern for 20 American friends, including a pregnant woman, he believed were still in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierre-Louis </PERSON> said: `` There's chaos, even panic, at the airport. Everybody is trying to leave'' <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pierre-Louis </PERSON>, a 34-year-old a native of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, arrived with his wife <PERSON> Danielle </PERSON> and their two young children. He said they kept up with events by watching American cable television at their hotel. `` They cut off our phones for nearly two days but for some reason they left the television on,'' he said. `` The more we saw the more afraid we got.'' <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON>, a graduate student at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who was doing research in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, said in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>: `` Gasoline is a problem.'' She said her taxi driver said he had only enough for one more trip `` and all the gasoline stations are closed.'' One American woman who arrived in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Wednesday had been in a dormitory where soldiers entered firing guns, killing a number of students, according to her friends. She was too upset to talk to a reporter. `` The airline offices were just two blocks from our hotel, but with all the tanks out there and gunfire it was too long a walk to risk,'' said <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON>. An American professor at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> was stopped along with eight other Americans in a van on the road to the airport by <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> soldiers who took their baggage, money, tickets and vehicle. The group had to walk an hour further to the airport, the teacher told <PERSON> Junichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagano </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> supervisor at <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> airport, near <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Many others on <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight 925 also arrived in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> with no baggage or money, <LOCATION> Nagano </LOCATION> said. Ms. <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON> told of a group of seven <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students who tried to stick together in their efforts to escape, helped by a Japanese student who found them airline tickets. But he could get them only three tickets, and `` we had to leave the other four behind,'' <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON> said. `` The last we knew they were out on Changan Avenue trying to get to the airline offices, but that was where the heaviest fighting was going on. I do n't know what happened to them,'' she said. She said the lack of reliable information was the main problem. `` It was very difficult to get phone calls through. People were getting hysterical,'' said <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON>, who moved around trying to find a safe spot in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> clutching a shortwave radio to get <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> reports on what was happening in various parts of the city. `` There were hordes of people at the airport, it was hot and humid, kids everywhere, people near panic, thinking ` today I have to get out at all costs,''' she said, adding that she heard loud booms that sounded like artillery fire within range of the airport. Some embassies, under gunfire, seemed overwhelmed with the task of evacuating their citizens, leaving some feeling stranded. `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> embassy made it very clear that transportation arrangements were up to us,'' said <PERSON> White </PERSON>, who said he was worried as other embassies pulled out their students, leaving him at his university as the last foreigner, with no clear directions from the embassy whether to stay or leave. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy sent a convoy to bring <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students to safety Monday, but some students, unsure whether they were safer on campuses, where army units were rumored to be preparing a strike, or downtown where gunfire was already rife, stayed behind. Chinese cheered the American convoy of a half-dozen vehicles led by a limousine flying an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag, and flashed victory signs as it wound through the city trying to find a safe route, <PERSON> Benedict </PERSON> said. `` Chinese people are clearly looking to the American government and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people for support, and that seems to put American citizens at risk because the -LRB- Chinese -RRB- government will try to suppress that kind of thinking,'' she said.
