<HEAD>GAO Says Military Using Consultants for Wide Range of Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional investigators said Wednesday that the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> is relying on outside consultants rather than its own personnel to determine the cost of the $ 6.8 billion system of rail-garrison MX missiles. Officials from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, an investigating arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel that the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> use consultants for a wide range of services. The total number, however, is likely higher than the agency found because the definition of consultant varies and many contractors do not report whether consultants worked on certain programs, investigators said. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on investigations, responding to last summer's `` Operation Ill Wind'' investigation of military purchasing fraud, had asked the agency to look into the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s use of consultants. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> studied one weapon system from each of the three services _ the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 3.2 billion Fiber Optic Guided Missile program; the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s V-22 Osprey, a $ 26 billion tilt-rotor aircraft program, and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s system to deploy the land-based, nuclear MX missile on railroad cars. The Ballistic Systems Division, which manages the MX program, awarded 15 contracts worth about $ 99 million for support services during fiscal 1987 and 1988, said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, director of manpower issues in the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> national security and international affairs division. The support contractors provided cost estimates, reviews of contractor logistic support plans and helped determine system and component specifications. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report prompted Rep. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the subcommittee, to question who estimates the cost of the MX rail-garrison _ the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> or the consultants hired by the service `` The best we can tell it's the consultants that they have hired do the estimating. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> reviews and approves,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` Who are the experts _ the consultants or the people we have in the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>?'' <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has told the agency that `` the contractor in this case has the institutional memory and the expertise.'' The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Democrat also expressed dismay over the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s inability to keep track of the consultants, the absence of a specific definition of the term consultant and the possibility that these problems could result in incidents of conflict-of-interest. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burman </PERSON>, deputy administrator and acting administrator in the Office of Federal Procurement Policy, said his agency has come up with a policy letter on conflict-of-interest that will require a 60-day comment period. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON> was angered by the absence of a tracking system for consultants. `` What in God's name is so difficult? Why is this a hot potato that when we ask the question we can not get an answer? Is the bureaucracy that great?'' <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON> said, his voice rising. `` You categorize, you prioritize, you have certain numbers of people working for the government. You have a defense industry you're in touch with everyday. Do n't they have an obligation to give to you the proper information with regard to that question. I want to know. I have a right to know. The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people have a right to know. Why ca n't I get that from you?'' the congressman said. <PERSON> Burman </PERSON> said that with the number of broad categories it is difficult for consultants looking at those categories to determine whether they are part of the process. `` It's very difficult for us to get any kind of consistency,'' he said. Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON>, acting director of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> for the past two years, told <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON> that there is `` no incentive to report this information because what happens if they do n't report it.
