<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed legislation on Wednesday speeding $ 3.3 billion to veterans programs and a host of money-short federal agencies, setting up potentially difficult talks with a House that passed a different version of the bill. Senators approved the bill on a voice vote on the fourth day of debate. Final passage came after lawmakers refused to delay for one year much of the new <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> catastrophic health care program for the elderly. The bill now goes to a conference committee with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which passed its version last month, to iron out differences before the bill goes to the president. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, R-Ariz., had led a fight to postpone parts of the program, including a surtax on senior citizens that has drawn complaints because of its cost His effort was defeated 51-49 on a procedural vote in which he was opposed by leaders of both parties. Lawmakers, however, did adopt by voice a non-binding provision offered by the leaders calling on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to consider making changes in the catastrophic care program in future legislation. There is widespread agreement that the surtax will likely collect more money than expected, but disputes remain over whittling down the levy. `` Certainly most Americans would rather not have to pay anything and receive the benefits,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan. `` That's the American way But we're broke.'' Earlier, across the Capitol, four <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members of both parties joined members of veterans associations at a news conference to accuse the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> of delaying the legislation while senators attach pet projects to it. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved the veterans money, $ 1.2 billion, on May 24. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Silvio </PERSON> <PERSON> Conte </PERSON>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> was holding the veterans funds `` hostage to the pet projects of senators who have included the veterans money in a Christmas tree of non-emergency appropriations.'' Chairman G.V. <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, D-Miss., of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> complained that because of the delay, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> was already `` gearing down'' some of its operations `` We've never hollered wolf about this situation at all,'' he said. The spending bill, which President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> first proposed as a $ 2.2 billion measure in March, contains money for health care, compensation increases, and other programs for veterans. For want of the money, the veterans agency has begun limiting out-patient care in less-serious cases, delayed opening new facilities and halted many maintenance proects and equipment purchases. The department annually treats around 3.5 million of the nation's 27 million veterans. <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>'s amendment, offered Tuesday, would delay for a year the surtax people over age 65 must pay to help finance the catastrophic care program. It would also postpone other important parts of the program, including caps it places on senior citizens' doctors' bills and a prescription drug benefit. Democrats had countered with an alternative calling for changes to be considered in future legislation. The overall measure also contains $ 892 million for student loans, $ 100 million to help refugees move to this country, and finances for fighting forest fires, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping, unemployment benefits, foster care, and other programs. The legislation has picked up a batch of amendments in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, including several of interest to particular lawmakers. One addition would protect a school district in <LOCATION> Sumter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, from sacrificing about $ 700,000 in federal aid this year it would otherwise have to yield because of a loss of students covered by an assistance program. The clause was sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, an Appropriations Committee member. The bill also contains $ 75 million to repair a radio telescope in the home state of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; orders the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> to spend $ 50 million to buy cold-weather clothing made in 10 states; and sets aside $ 400,000 to study last year's fires in Yellowstone National The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> also added its own favorite provisions to the bill. These include: language easing the way for <PERSON> Alton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, to lease land on which it could build a public marina; allowing a $ 2.5 million increase in spending for cotton and tobacco grading; and providing up to $ 360,000 for aviation research at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>. The House bill also contains $ 822 million not in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure for anti-drug programs.
