<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two congressmen vying to succeed Gov. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> started hitting the campaign trail and each other Wednesday, only hours after their primary victories. Democrat <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, a winner by 27,000 votes, was at commuter train station by 7:30 a.m. and talking to more than 1,000 senior citizens by lunch time. Nearly eight years ago he lost to <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> by the narrowest margin in state history _ 1,797 votes out of 2.3 million cast. Republican <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Courter </PERSON> used the day to appear with <PERSON> Kean </PERSON>, who's still very popular among voters and is considered an important political ally, even though he differs with <PERSON> Courter </PERSON> on key issues <PERSON> Kean </PERSON>, barred by law from seeking a third consecutive term, endorsed no primary candidate but filmed commercials for the frontrunners that aired in a media blitz during the final weeks of the primary. Also decided in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> on Tuesday was a bitter primary for the Democratic mayoral nomination in <LOCATION> Plainfield </LOCATION>, where City Councilman <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> upset Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> by a 198-vote margin, 2,172 to 1,974. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, elected mayor in 1985, and <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, a 7-year councilman, head two factions of the city's Democratic party for years. Their primary fight this year was the most public show of animosity between the two popular politicians. At one point, both submitted to urine tests to fend off allegations that they consorted with drug dealers. <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>, a conservative who comes from a wealthy family and the Republican-rich northwestern part of the state, is expert on foreign affairs and gained national attention as a member of the Iran-Contra committee. <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, the son of a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> shipyard worker, has a formidable political base in southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and a national reputation as an environmentalist. <PERSON> Courter </PERSON> said <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> has amassed a `` big spending'' voting record in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and established himself as the head of machine politics in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Courter </PERSON> also backed away from his `` no new taxes'' primary campaign platform, and said if he ever had to raise taxes it would be `` only as a last resort'' but he would `` bend over backwards'' to avoid a tax increase. <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> picked up a favorite theme of <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> primary opponents and condemned <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>'s free-market plan to lower insurance rates by deregulating the industry. While saying political labels serve no purpose, <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> termed <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>'s call for deregulation so politically conservative it was `` off the charts of reasonability.'' Both candidates promised to spell out where they differ from one another, and said voters will have some clear choices.
