<HEAD>Senate Rejects Move to Delay Catastrophic Act Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> narrowly rejected a proposal Wednesday to delay the start of major provisions of <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>'s new catastrophic health care coverage, a proposal opponents argued would have effectively killed the new benefits. Reacting to criticism from senior citizens opposed to paying an income tax surcharge to help pay for the program, backers of the delay proposal argued that it was unfair to put roughly two-thirds of the cost of the program on roughly one-third of retired Americans with enough income to make them subject to income taxes. Those who voted against delaying the coverage maintained that huge federal budget deficits make it impossible to provide new benefits without providing a way to pay for them and that middle-and upper-income retired Americans should foot a major share of the cost. The surtax could be as much as $ 800 a year for Medicare-eligible retirees in upper income ranges. In the key vote, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 51-49 against an attempt by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., to kill an amendment by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> that called on the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to review the program while benefits continue on schedule <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> introduced his amendment as a substitute to <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>'s proposal to delay provisions while a way to reduce the surtax is found. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> then quickly adopted by voice votes the <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> substitute amendment and attached it to a pending supplemental appropriations measure to pump $ 3.3 billion additional money into a variety of federal programs for the current fiscal year. `` Nowhere in my amendment will you find the word repeal, but you will find the word delay,'' <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> maintained. He termed the <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> amendment a `` smokescreen'' that would not require <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> action and vowed to continue his fight to in order delay in implementation of the surtax. Sen. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn., argued that approving <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>'s delay of some benefits would amount to repeal because it would send a clear signal to the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to let the program `` We're going to get wisdom real quick and there is no way you're going to get this back out of that committee,'' said <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, a member of the panel that crafted the catastrophic health act The measure cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last summer on an 86-11 vote and, with similarly overwhelming <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approval, was signed into law with great fanfare by President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> who had proposed a more modest and less expensive version. <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> was one of the 11 senators opposing the catastrophic health measure last year. Opponents of the <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> attempt argued that an estimated 59 percent of the 32 million Medicare beneficaries do not have enough income to qualify for income tax and would pay only $ 4 a month for the additional coverage. They cited <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates that 70 percent of those eligible for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> would pay $ 100 or less a year in additional surtaxes and that only 5.6 percent in upper income levels would pay the maximum $ 800 tax. The catastrophic coverage took effect Jan. 1 with unlimited hospitalization coverage after a once-a-year $ 560 deductible. However, a $ 1,370 cap on out-of-pocket doctor bills does not kick in until next year and a new prescription drug benefit begins a three-year phase-in period in 1991. It was those benefits beginning next January that <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> wanted to delay, along with the surtax _ or `` supplemental premium'' _ to finance them. The surtax started this year to build up a trust fund to pay the new benefits without dipping into the federal treasury.
