 One of three men who kidnapped and buried a bus full of schoolchildren in 1976 was denied parole Wednesday. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoenfeld </PERSON>, 35, serving a life sentence at the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Men </LOCATION>'s Colony here, is still a danger to society, a Board of Prison Terms panel ruled in refusing the inmate's 10th plea for a parole date. The panel's vote was 2-1: Deputy Commissioner <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> argued that a date should be set, but far enough in the future to exceed the prisoner's life span. The board turned aside a lengthy apology from <PERSON> Schoenfeld </PERSON>, who said: `` I ask that you at least set a date so I can see a light at the end of the tunnel.'' He was convicted for his role in the kidnapping and abduction of 26 schoolchildren and their driver from the rural town of <LOCATION> Chowchilla </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> for $ 5 million ransom. <PERSON> Schoenfeld </PERSON>, his brother, <PERSON> James </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> commandeered the bus at gunpoint on July 15, 1976, and took it 100 miles to <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. There they shut the victims in a poorly ventilated moving van buried in a quarry. It took the group 16 hours to dig to safety through the wood - and earth-covered hole All three inmates are serving life terms.
