<HEAD>Construction Industry Agrees to Traffic Management Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction unions and businesses have agreed to a plan that would keep heavy trucks from making deliveries during peak commuting hours to help reduce air pollution, Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> announced Tuesday. <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s skies are among the nation's most polluted because of surrounding mountains that trap the filth along with stagnant weather and industries that operate in the area. The city agreed to exempt from its proposed traffic management program trucks and equipment necessary for pouring concrete, laying hot asphalt and erecting structural steel, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. In return, the construction industry `` agreed to shift its work hours _ without premium pay _ to 6 a.m. to 3 p.m. instead of the current 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. to reduce truck and automobile traffic,'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. The one-hour shift would remove about 125,000 construction workers from city streets during morning and afternoon rush-hour traffic, the mayor said. The proposal, developed by the city jointly with a regional air quality control agency, would require truck operators to pay a surcharge for a license allowing them to use city streets during rush hour. It also would create a rapid deployment task force intended to quickly respond and clean up major accidents. The altered work schedule would involve members of 83 union locals, including boiler makers, brick layers, carpenters, operating engineers, teamsters, general contractors, pipe trade workers and painters. The plan is expected to go before the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> early next month.
