 A national <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> official resigned Wednesday in the uproar over a memo he wrote comparing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s voting record with that of a homosexual congressman. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was described as `` disgusted by this entire incident'' and considering it closed. However, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the resignation of `` one staffer'' was n't good enough and suggested his <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> counterpart, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s former campaign manager <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, should be fired by the president. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON>, a press assistant in <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s 1988 presidential campaign, wrote the memo and had it distributed as communications director of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>.
