<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> on Wednesday promised cuts in defense spending, growth of the Soviet economy and said there would be government relief for almost 40 million people now living below the poverty line. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> also disclosed that the war in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> cost the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> the equivalent of $ 8 billion a year. Speaking to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies after he was reappointed premier, <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said the government planned to cut defense spending by between 33 percent and 50 percent by 1995. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> spends 77.3 billion rubles, the equivalent of $ 118 billion a year, on defense, almost four times more than previously acknowledged. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>, who has been premier since September 1985, gave the first public breakdown of that spending.
