<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv07   06-07 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 07,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Wednesday, June 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>What Is the Fed Fighting?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Why use a cudgel when a scalpel is called for? In one form or another that question forever arises in discussions of <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> or monetary policy, which involves decisions about the supply and cost of money in the economy. Most likely it will continue to arise for years to come, the simple truth being that monetary officials are familiar with the cudgel, a blunt instrument, but have n't yet acquired skill with the more refined scalpel. As a consequence, critics say, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s inevitable first reaction to signs of inflation is to slow the economy, mainly by restricting the money supply and thereby raising interest rates. It works. Just as a human being would falter under repeated blows to the head, the economy eventually slows. Factories close, unemployment rises and demand lessens. No mystery there; people just do n't have the money to buy. But the question remains: Why should the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> have to slow the whole economy rather than simply restraining the inflationary culprits? Because the instruments and skills do n't seem to be available to it. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, an international investment adviser and frequent critic of <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy, claims that for years monetary policy failed to perceive the true causes of domestic inflation and needlessly bludgeoned the American economy. He becomes particularly incensed at repeated <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> efforts to dampen the American economy because of a factor that should have been dealt with abroad. The inflationary factor was Eurodollars, created by European banks. In his view, these dollars, created whenever dollar-denominated loans were made by foreign banks, created a classic inflation scenario, that of too many dollars chasing too few goods. Prices rose, but not because of domestic demand but because foreign banks created dollars without any supervision or restraints by American authorities. Still, he says, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> response to Eurodollar inflation was to cudgel the American economy into repeated recessions. A somewhat similar worry arises today. Inflation for the 12 months ended in April was 5.1 percent, up from 3.9 percent in the year before, as measured by the Consumer Price Index. The suggestion is that of general inflation. However, over the same time the consumer price index inflation rate for all items, less food and energy, barely rose. For the 12 months ended in April 1988 it was 4.3 percent. For the 12 months through April 1989 it was 4.6 percent. Exclude food and energy prices and the inflation rate is almost stable. Add them and you have a dangerous trend. Now, however, there are some indications that food and energy prices may have stabilized, albeit at high levels. Last year's drought largely was responsible for driving up food prices by 6.5 percent. While there is no assurance the drought will not continue or resume, those knowledgeable about weather conditions are optimistic. Last year energy prices rose 8.7 percent, largely on the basis of reduced production by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> Exporting Countries. This year there are some indications supplies will be larger than before. <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> watchers therefore are expressing optimism that <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy wo n't grow harsher, and even that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will ease up on the economy, allowing interest rates to fall. In short, the belief is that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will try to use the scalpel instead of the familiar cudgel.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed June 7</NOTE>
