<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:UndergroundAtlanta Adv12   06-07 1099</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Underground Atlanta, Adv 12,1125</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Mon PMs, June 12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Lot's On The Line As Underground Atlanta Opens _ Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Often derided as `` a nice place to live, but you would n't want to visit,'' <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> tries one more time next month to amuse conventioneers and capture its soul as Underground <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> opens for business _ again. Seven years after the lights went out, ostensibly for good, the entertainment and shopping playground beneath downtown is set to open Thursday after a three-year overhaul under the auspices of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the wizards of American urban reclamation. In its prime, Underground <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> was <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s answer to the French Quarter, created in old storefronts that were the city's heart before a network of bridges over railroad tracks literally raised downtown one level Underground had swinging Dixieland, loud rock' n' roll, cool jazz, fine eateries, chic watering holes _ even a shop where segregationist restaurateur-turned-governor <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON> signed autographs and sold souvenirs. Underground opened in 1969, peaked in 1972, was struggling by 1975, and was gone by 1982. It was eulogized as the victim of crime _ or a perception thereof _ derelicts, subway construction, ripoff merchants and changing times. There were dozens of theories about what went wrong, but seemingly no answers. Without it, downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> has acquired the reputation of a ghost town after dark, which has been an albatross around the neck of the city's thriving convention industry. While conventioneers sit in gleaming downtown hotels, real Atlantans are miles away in the biracial city's largely white suburbs. In 1985, the city signed the deal for a $ 142 million rerevitalization. It turned to <PERSON> Rouse </PERSON>, the people responsible for <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Faneuil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Place </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>'s Harborplace, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seaport </LOCATION>, among other projects. `` We're trying to create a town center for metropolitan <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, back to the birthplace of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of the Underground <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> development company. `` We want it to be a place ... where visitors will come to find out about what <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> has to offer, but where also the hometown crowd can feel some sense of identity.'' Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> sees the new Underground as `` one of the most significant accomplishments'' of two terms in office. `` This represents a new heart for <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. It represents a gathering place for the entire metro area.'' The new Underground is on and around the original site, on downtown's south side, just blocks from the high-rise hotel district. It's three times the size of the old Underground; visitors will find 22 restaurants and nightclubs and nearly 100 retailers. While the emphasis on retailing marks a change for Underground, the entertainment focus is something new for <PERSON> Rouse </PERSON>. `` We've never done this strong an entertainment aspect to any of our urban places,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, vice president and general manager of <LOCATION> Rouse-Atlanta </LOCATION>, the Rouse affiliate created to run the project. `` Some of that is due to the name,'' he said. `` Underground <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> has probably the highest name recognition of any project we've ever touched ... and what Underground <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> was known for was entertainment.'' Rouse officials anticipate 10 million to 11 million visitors a year, half of them out-of-towners. They say there are enough office workers and convention-goers downtown to meet three-fourths of Underground's needs. Even so, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said, `` The real test of whether the project succeeds ... is whether the project appeals to residents. The obvious concern _ what a lot of people talk about around here _ is security.'' That's because the old Underground came to be regarded as dangerous. <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephensen </PERSON>, whose <PERSON> Dante </PERSON>'s Down The Hatch jazz club and restaurant anchored the old Underground, said, `` At its worst, Underground had a lower crime rate than Lenox Square -LRB- a popular mall -RRB-. But downtown areas ca n't protect themselves from bad publicity.'' Clearly, this time around Underground must be perceived as safe. `` We've taken a common-sense approach,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. A squad of some 30 private guards will patrol, accompanied by <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> police, who are building a 34-officer substation there. Planners have made sure there are no blind alleys, and lighting designers have made it bright enough to read at midnight. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> admits to being irked that he is repeatedly asked what Underground will do to keep out `` undesirables.'' `` First, tell me who the ` undesirables' are. This is a town center. It's open to everyone. If a person comes to Underground and happens to look different, that's fine. If a person starts to infringe on somebody else's rights, that's not fine.'' A no-nonsense security policy seems to have wide public appeal. Where city officials triggered a storm of criticism with a plan to run vagrants out before last year's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, hardly anything has been heard from anyone concerned about loiterers' civil rights in Underground. `` I do n't see it as a problem,'' <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. `` The biggest problem is in perception, and that perception problem goes away as people come here and have a good time and find out they are n't hassled. `` I would be surprised,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said, `` if Underground is not the safest place in the whole <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> area.'' It had better be. The city has sunk more than $ 80 million in revenue bonds, as well as other public funding, into Underground. If it flops, the city could be forced to cough up some $ 3 million a year for 30 years. `` Underground is important symbolically, and it is a test of whether a town center can work here, whether we have enough cohesiveness,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. `` Because if we continue to drift apart, as we've been doing, there could be all sorts of consequences _ economic, political, social and otherwise.'' And although <PERSON> Rouse </PERSON> has relatively little capital invested, the company's track record is on the line. `` It seems that each year, the expectations get higher, as they see what's happened in other cities,'' <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. `` Rouse has taken slums and turned them into landmarks,'' said <PERSON> Stephenson </PERSON>, who is reopening <PERSON> Dante </PERSON>'s. `` And Underground <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> was never as bad, at its worst, as any of those other areas were.'' Project officials maintain there's virtually no way Underground will fail. `` I'm convinced Underground is going to be a great success,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said, pointing out that while two developers put together the first Underground on a shoestring, this time the city is landlord, partner and major investor. `` The city leaders recognize how important it is, and they're not going to let it fail,'' he said. `` They just ca n't.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs Mon June 12</NOTE>
