<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv08   06-07 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 08,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, June 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Opportunity To Prepay Your Mortgage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As interest rates drop, smart homeowners with variable rate mortgages are preparing for a great leap forward by voluntarily raising their monthly payments. Such homeowners, and there are lots of them, exploit the cyclical nature of interest rates by accelerating their payments when rates are down and slowing them when rates rise, thus obtaining the greatest return for their dollar. Not everyone has the cash flow to do so, of course, but even small amounts can make a big difference when repeated for many months. Assuming a five-year cycle of high and low rates, some of these homeowners add to their payments for the 30 months or so when rates are lowest and then add nothing to their payments during the high end of the cycle. In such ways they can pare years from the maturity date of their loans. The theory is similar to what is practiced regularly in the stock market where wise investors buy when stock prices are low and avoid further commitments when prices are high, thus getting the most shares for the dollar. In real estate, homeowners in effect obtain more equity for the dollar by adding to their payments when their variable mortgage rates fall. In effect, such prepayments: _ `` Buy'' more equity for the buck. _ Accelerate the equity-loan ratio, or the amount of the monthly payment that goes to equity versus loan repayment Most of the payment in the first few months of a mortgage loan is to repay interest. As each month passes, more money is applied to equity and less to interest until, near maturity, the payments are almost all equity. By making additional payments, that process is hastened. Not only does the additional payment, in itself, lower the loan amount and add to the equity, but it `` jumps'' the homeowner into the more favorable equity-loan relationship. _ Shrink the mortgage maturity date _ perhaps, for example, from 20 years to 18 _ saving thousands of dollars of interest payments All three of these benefits are simply different ways of saying the same thing, that when you speed up repayments, especially when rates are at the low point in the cycle, you can save substantial sums. Unless drastic changes occur in the way the American economy operates, such opportunities will present themselves at least two or three times in a 20-year period. Economies are cyclical, forever expanding or contracting. During the old days of fixed-rate mortgages, homeowners did n't have the opportunity to take advantage of these cycles No matter what happened to rates in general, borrowers were locked into their initial contract rates. Variable rates were developed primarily because lenders wanted them for their own protection. Why, they reasoned, should they be locked into low rates for long terms when their own costs of obtaining money might rise? Lenders thus obtained the protection they sought, but in so doing they also left an opening for savvy homeowners. There is nothing in most mortgage contracts written today to prevent borrowers from taking advantage of the low end of the interest-rate cycle. Even for bankers, it seems, security comes at a price.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for PMs Thursday, June 8.</NOTE>
