<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, June 9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Southern Baptist Candidates Partly Agree, But Not Mainly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Both say that they want to cool it, to stop the battling. Both take a fundamentalist view of the Bible. Both affirm friendship. But they're poised for a fight over the nature of Southern Baptists. Both claim to represent the genuine Baptist way, the authentic heritage. But the two candidates for the denomination's presidency disagree strongly about principles essential to that heritage. It's a conflict that has gone on for a decade in the nation's biggest Protestant denomination, numbering l4 .8 Its presidency holds sway over makeup of its operating personnel. Filling that powerful top post is the key decision for the denomination's convention June 13-15 in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> determining whether fundamentalists will keep the office for an 11th straight year. Their incumbent candidate, the Rev. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Vines </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, seeks a second term, calling for peace in the ranks. `` I have made a conscious effort to create an atmosphere where healing and reconciliation could occur,'' he says. His challenger, the Rev. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON> of suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, backed by moderates, also calls himself a peacemaker, a `` responsible reconciler, a bridge to call our people back together.'' While both speak of `` peace,'' however, both also declare their adherence to differing positions on principles considered basic for Baptists, involving the latitude of condoned doctrinal freedom. On that, Vines sets certain limits on what is acceptable, primarily about the Bible but impinging on many other issues, while <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON> insists on greater room for acceptable differences. `` We have certain parameters which are overwhelmingly accepted in Southern Baptist life,'' Vines says, adding that he has confined his appointments to those whose beliefs are within those approved `` parameters.'' <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON> says this has clamped on `` a kind of tight control'' demanding allegiance to it. `` Our freedom is being threatened,'' he says. `` It has to stop ... or we are going to destroy this denomination.'' Vines, 51, a native Georgian, has been pastor of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, for the last seven years. <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON>, 44, a Texan, led the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, for 12 years, before becoming pastor of suburban <LOCATION> Dunwoody </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> last fall. Weighing against <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON>'s bid is a longtime convention custom, unvarying in modern history, of always giving the incumbent a second term. Vines also is riding a fundamentalist tide. Its appointive authority, surpassing that of any post in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christianity </ORGANIZATION>, determines trustees that control the denomination's 26 agencies and institutions with budgets totalling about $ 400 million annually. `` In my second year,'' <PERSON> Vines </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, `` I would emphasize building soul-winning churches, and I would like to lead our convention to a renewed emphasis on church growth. `` We have settled the debate over the nature of Scripture. Now it is time to move into a new era of growth in our local churches.'' <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON> says that `` humanly speaking, it is not likely that I will be elected, although I'm going to try.'' If he does win, he says he would seek a limitation on presidential powers to `` de-politicize'' that office. `` The pattern of the last 10 years has been basically a philosophy of winner-take all,'' he says. `` My philosophy would be that the winner shares all.'' Curiously, both Vines and <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON> espouse `` biblical inerrancy,''' meaning Scripture is literally without error historically, religiously or scientifically. However, Vines' policy has restricted appointments to persons inside those `` parameters.'' Linked to the paramenters have been various social positions such as against divorced personnel, abortion or ordaining women. <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON> says his `` appointments would be from a different perspective. I would include all Southern Baptists'' on both sides of the prolonged conflict. He says that he himself is an `` inerrantist'' about the Bible, but also is a `` centrist'' who accepts differing approaches under the Baptist principle of the right of believers to interpret Scripture as each understands it. Vines, seeking to deflect sharp conflict from the convention, has asked the executive committee to postpone action on a highly controversial proposal to establish a separate <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, religious-liberty arm. It would be an alternative to the current agency in which nine Baptist bodies cooperate, the <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Public Affairs. Fundamentalists have assailed it as not adhering to their social agenda. Vines says he wants the matter deferred so the convention can focus on evangelism and be `` as positive and united as possible.'' <PERSON> Vestal </PERSON>, who has campaigned in church meetings in several states, says he wants the convention to return to its `` time-honored principles'' such as local church autonomy and `` priesthood of believers'' emphasizing their equal rights. `` We have forsaken basic principles,'' he says. `` It is a power or control issue, and Southern Baptists have got to resist it. We have got to stand up and say enough is enough.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 9</NOTE>
