<HEAD>Harry Connick Jr. _ A Young Pianist Praying For the Past</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the young pianist whose music has been rattling chandeliers at the city's swankier jazz joints, planned to do just one thing before the biggest gig of his life, a sold-out show at <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` Pray,'' said the 21-year-old <PERSON> Connick </PERSON>. On the day of the concert, he'd sleep the day away, go to the little Catholic church around the corner and ask for some divine guidance. The day before the May 6 <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> performance, he's up before dawn to appear on a morning TV news show. He'll be playing in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that night. He's fighting a case of strep throat and, since he sings during a good portion of his performances, he's worried that his voice wo n't hold for the big show the following night `` Hopefully, I'll have my chops back,'' <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> says, rubbing his throat with his huge hands. `` This is awful. It's like I can sing but I have no control.'' His <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> studio apartment is littered with tiny throat lozenge wrappers, most of them crumpled in a pile on the mantle of his grand piano, which takes up a good part of the space. It's a gray day, and the studio is lighted only by the muted sun streaming in the window. The only glow comes from <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> who beams when he talks about his favorite topics: music and singing. Lately he's been practicing all night and, he says, `` praying is the only thing that can help me now.'' It's a tactic that's served him well. Relying on religion, in part, brought him from a rich bog of musicial influences in his native <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to the splendor of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Tully </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. He arrived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at age 18, got a room at the local <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION> and within a month had a job playing the piano in a church. Then another church in the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> needed a choir director. After that, gigs at `` little dives here and there'' led to others; the joints got classier, the pianos better tuned. Three years later, he has two albums out with <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> _ the first called `` <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'' and the second `` 20,'' as in his age at the time. Earlier this year, he had a successful and often sold-out run at the famed Algonquin Hotel. His repertoire relies heavily on nostalgia: <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON>'s `` If I Only Had a Brain''; <PERSON> Hoagy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON>'s `` Lazy River''; and <PERSON> Bart </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>'s `` In Other Words'' -LRB- also called `` Fly Me to the Moon'' -RRB-. <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> finds the whole notion of today's popular music distressing. `` They do n't understand,'' said <PERSON> Connick </PERSON>, his trademark slick ash-blond hair bobbing back and forth, referring to no one in particular and everyone in general who produces and performs trendy tunes. `` There was just an innocence which is lost in American society today. Can you imagine how nice it would have been, back in the'40s? The innocence they had back then _ there is such a joyousness about the music back then.'' Still, his passion for the past leaves many puzzled. `` People always say, ` Harry why do you do all those old songs?' I would just run out of songs to play,'' <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> said of his first days as a performer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> when he'd be pressed to play for hours on end. `` I would hear a song like ` Somewhere Over the Rainbow,' by <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> and I would say, ` That sure is a pretty song. I'm going to buy all his music.' Then I started reading his music and realized he wrote ` Come Rain or Come Shine,' ` That Old Black Magic,' ` It's Only a Paper Moon' and a bunch of other songs that are really great `` Not only lyrically are they wonderful to sing, but the melodies are so perfect,'' <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> said. `` No one writes like that now.'' He denies he's on a revival trip, and says his polished image _ big, pouty lips, slicked back short hair and loose-fitting suits _ is n't calculated. `` I did n't say, ` What can I do to market myself? I got it! I'll slick my hair back, wear baggy suits and sing songs from the 40s. Everything just happened coincidentally.'' Not completely. Growing up near <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' bohemian French Quarter with parents who loved to indulge their boy's musicial aspirations, helped make the package of <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> what it is today. He made his first public performance when he was 5 for his father's inauguration as the city's district attorney. `` I got up there and I remember hearing that applause and I said, ` I got ta have more of that! Where can I get more of that?''' In his quest for a big, happy audience, he began to study a host of musicial influences _ rhythm and blues, honky-tonk, bebop and stride. Stride is a devilish piano style that requires one hand to race across the keyboard at a furious speed while the other one pounds away at a different tempo. He began to incorporate sounds from other artists including <PERSON> Erroll </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>, <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON>, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellington </PERSON>, Thelonius Monk and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Prima </PERSON>. Under the tutelage of jazz pianist <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> -LRB- father of <LOCATION> Wynton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Branford </LOCATION> -RRB-, <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> began to master bebop. The <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> family played a large role in <PERSON> Connick </PERSON>'s young career. <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> admits one of the reasons he moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was to be near his friend <PERSON> Wynton </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON>, the Grammy-winning jazz and classical trumpeter. <PERSON> Delfeayo </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wynton </PERSON>'s brother, produced <PERSON> Connick </PERSON>'s first album, which was recorded in one afternoon in January 1987. But on this day, ballads were on <PERSON> Connick </PERSON>'s mind. He said he'd been listening to a piece by <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> from the album `` In the Wee Small Hours'' over and over again He jumps up and plays it to explain a nuance of the pain he hears in <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>'s voice and how he hopes to one day be able to sing a ballad as well. `` He's saying, ` I get along without you very well, of course I do.''' <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> said. `` He's being sarcastic. `` Now listen,'' he adds, reciting the lyrics along with the music: `` Except when soft rains call and the drip of the leaves, then I recall the thrill of being sheltered in your arms, of course I do.'' <PERSON> Connick </PERSON> stares off and gets a melancholy look in his eyes. `` These days they just do n't understand,'' he said.
