<HEAD>Jonathan Silverman Stars As Opportunistic Rookie Salesman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> was first offered his role in the <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> movie `` Traveling Man,'' he loathed the character. `` I enjoyed the script but I could n't see myself in it,'' he said. `` It called for someone in his late 20s, cocky and a Southerner. I read it again. I really hated <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>. `` But the more I hated him the more I loved him. Then when I heard <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lithgow </PERSON> was also going to play the older salesman I was thrilled.'' <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> is a pushy, opportunistic young hustler ready to steal his mentor's sales route out from under him in the <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> film, premiering Sunday. <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> is best known for playing `` nice Jewish boys,'' most particularly <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> in playwright <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s autobiographical trilogy, `` <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> Memoirs,'' `` <ORGANIZATION> Biloxi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blues </ORGANIZATION>'' and `` Broadway Bound. <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> played the role on Broadway, and in the movie version of `` Brighton Beach Memoirs.'' `` Traveling Man,'' described as a combination of `` Death of a Salesman'' and `` Tin Men,'' was written five years ago by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. The crackerjack movie, with fine performances all around, had kicked around so long, because it was n't considered commercial enough, until it was picked up by Home Box Office. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Cluett </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lithgow </PERSON> -RRB- is a middle-aged salesman of industrial foam in the deep South whose spectacular sales record hits a slump. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON> is the district sales manager with an evangelical fury and a heart of stone. <PERSON> Glover </PERSON> induces <PERSON> Cluett </PERSON> to take along rookie salesman <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> to show him the ropes. What <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> has in mind is to hang <PERSON> Cluett </PERSON> from the ropes and take over his lucrative route. <PERSON> Irvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kershner </PERSON> -LRB- `` The Empire Strikes Back,'' `` The Flim-Flam Man'' -RRB- directed. The movie was shot in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. It also stars <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> as a caring woman <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> meets during <PERSON> Mardi </PERSON> <PERSON> Gras </PERSON>. `` I've never played a character as shady or with such evil intentions as <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> said during a break in shooting his next movie, `` Sketches,'' also starring <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Bateman </PERSON>. `` He's a very complex character, but he has to come across as naive and innocent until he sticks it to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lithgow </PERSON>. `` He's thoroughly messed up <PERSON> Ben </PERSON>'s life, but when <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> gets into trouble <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> comes back and rescues him. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lithgow </PERSON>'s my idol. It was a thrill to work with him, but it was difficult to yell at him and hit him.'' <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> grew up in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and was 17 when he landed the role in `` <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION> Beach Memoirs'' in 1983, replacing <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Broderick </PERSON>. `` Working in ` <ORGANIZATION> Brighton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memoirs </ORGANIZATION>' was my first job and my first time away from home,'' he said. `` I'd never intended to become an actor. It was just something I'd done in high school. My passion was playing baseball, and I went back and forth between baseball and drama. An agent saw me in a school play and called me. I thought it was a friend playing a joke. He sent me on an audition and that's how I was cast in the play. His other film credits include `` Stealing Home,'' `` Caddyshack II,'' `` Girls Just Want to Have Fun,'' and `` Weekend at <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON>'s.'' He was on the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> series `` Gim me a Break'' in 1984-86. The producers had a role written for him after seeing him on stage. In `` Weekend at <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON>'s,'' which will be released in July, <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> play two insurance agents who stumble across some information on a crime. They tell their boss, who turns out to be the crook. `` The boss invites us to his beach house so he can have the Mafia kill us,'' <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> said. `` But they kill him instead, so it's two guys with a body. There's a party going on in the house and no one else is aware he's dead. It's a very black comedy.'' What's next for <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>? `` I'm being offered a lot of things,'' he said. `` I usually have to fight for things. This is a lovely time. But I have n't decided yet what to accept.''
