<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Paramount Hopes For Another `Trek' Into Profits </HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The allure of `` Star Trek'' has long delighted its followers and confounded its detractors. Star <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON> has an explanation. `` Is it possible that we're creating a mythology, that we touch a mythological vein somewhere? The more I read and the more I think about it, I wonder if the key to ` Star Trek' is not all the wonderful stuff we talk about: the character interplay, the sci-fi, action and adventure and all those good things that seem to be on the surface,'' he said. `` Somewhere underneath, the chemistry and the concept touch upon a mythological need in modern culture. That's my real thought. I do n't quite know what I mean. It would take a far more intelligent and perceptive person to divine what I mean.'' <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> takes a far less intellectual view of the phenomenon. The company still makes nice rentals on the 1960s TV series, and `` Star Trek: The Next Generation'' has prospered in syndication. A $ 50 million gamble on the 1979 `` Star Trek: The Motion Picture'' paid off handsomely. `` Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home'' was the highest moneymaker of the series, earning $ 57 million in rentals. Now comes `` Star Trek V: The Final Frontier,'' directed by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON>. Why would he want to take on the onerous job of guiding an immensely complicated production? `` Directing a film is the end of the rainbow,'' he said in an interview. `` You've seen those T-shirts: ` What I really want to do is direct.' What I really want to do is direct. I've directed several stage plays, some television. I thought that directing a huge, large-budget motion picture might be something that would be the culmination of all my efforts. `` I was indeed the culmination of my career _ I do n't know if this will be the end of my career. It is certainly the top moment of my life, and it was everything I hoped it would be.'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimoy </PERSON>, who directed `` The Voyage Home'' as well as `` Three Men and a Baby'' and `` The Good Mother,'' gives his co-star good marks as a director. `` I think he's terrific,'' <PERSON> Nimoy </PERSON> said. `` He has a quality which is wonderful. It's an almost childlike desire to entertain, to tell a story, to capture your attention, to surprise you and touch you, make you laugh. He wants to do that: to be a fun storyteller. That kind of exuberance will serve him well.'' <PERSON> Nimoy </PERSON> also discussed the difference in their directorial styles. `` The joke is that in a <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON> film he does a lot more running and jumping,'' he said. `` He's much more physical as a person than I am. I've always been a lot more sedentary, always made more cerebral choices in my acting. He makes more physical choices. He would rather do a chase than a conversation.'' `` The Final Frontier'' was <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON>'s baby from the beginning. He submitted a 14-page original story about a messianic leader who kidnaps the Enterprise and its crew and takes them to a faraway land where he believes God resides. Producer <PERSON> Harve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> approved his story idea, and the pair worked on the plot with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Loughery </PERSON>, who wrote the script. Production was stalled by two industry strikes and <PERSON> Nimoy </PERSON>'s commitment to direct `` The Good Wife. `` The Final Frontier'' had only 18 weeks in post-production, <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON> said, which was about one-third of what was needed. The speed may have contributed to bad previews which were reported in the press. The movie was retooled for its wide release on June 9. With all of his directorial duties, was <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON> the actor neglected? `` Interesting,'' he mused. `` If I had been handed this script and somebody else was directing, I probably have gone in and said, ` Look, I do n't think the character is quite focussed.' `` I might have shortchanged myself as the egotistical actor. Let me rephrase that. I do n't mean egotistical in the bad sense; I mean in the actor whose sole point of view is the character. `` My job when hired for Capt. <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> was to keep my focus on Capt. <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, to protect Capt. <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, to make him as exciting and make him move as well as possible,'' he said. `` I did n't want to do that with this film. I wanted to open myself up and make sure the other characters were not only protected but a great deal was made of them.'' <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON>, 58, is a Canadian, born and reared in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>. He started acting early. `` I began at the age of six, acting in camp plays,'' he related. `` I continued in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> amateur theatricals as a teen-ager. I put myself through college with radio work. I went to the professional theater when I graduated from the university -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> McGill </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, stayed in the professional theater through thick and thin. I've never done anything else but act, write and direct.'' Trained in the classics at the <LOCATION> Stratford </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> -RRB- <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> <PERSON> Festival </PERSON>, he made his Broadway debut in the festival's `` Tamburlaine the Great.'' <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON> became one of the busiest actors in live TV dramas, won an <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION> contract and made his film debut in `` The <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Karamazov </ORGANIZATION>.'' For a time he bounced between the theater -LRB- `` The World of <PERSON> Suzie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>,'' `` A Shot in the Dark'' -RRB-, films -LRB- `` Judgment at <LOCATION> Nuremberg </LOCATION>,'' `` The Outrage'' -RRB- and television -LRB- `` For the People'' -RRB-. In 1965, <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Roddenberry </PERSON> produced a pilot of a new space series starring <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> as Capt. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> gave it thumbs down, declaring it too cerebral. <PERSON> Roddenberry </PERSON> shot a second pilot for `` Star Trek,'' casting <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON> as Capt. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> in what became something of a lifetime job.
</TEXT>
