<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s governor and tourism officials, fearing that Americans picture their state as a soiled paradise since the biggest oil spill in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history, began a damage-control tour to promote the vast reaches unaffected by the disaster. `` If you went to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and if you wanted to see the oil, you would have to go to a pretty substantial expense and a lot of trouble to do so,'' Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said Tuesday. Tourism is a $ 750 million-a-year industry for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, behind only oil and seafood among the state's biggest industries.
