<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional efforts to force the nation's thrifts to meet stringent capital requirements would push almost one-third of the industry into insolvency and keep home mortgage rates above 10 percent, the chief economist for a trade association said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, director of the economics department for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, told <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> thrift executives Tuesday that as many as 973 thrifts, with $ 768 billion in assets, would fail to meet requirements that they maintain 3 percent tangible capital.
