<HEAD>More Big Companies Evacuate China; Banks Tighten Lending Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks are tightening lending guidelines for Chinese-foreign business ventures because of the civil strife that threatens to engulf <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and American companies are accelerating their retreat from the country. Reversing its position of a day earlier, <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday it was evacuating expatriates and was among the first companies to charter a plane for the pullout. The <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> workers included 43 from a <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> factory that assembles MD-80 twinjets, seven workers based in the southwest city of <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> and one representative in the northeast city of <LOCATION> Shenyang </LOCATION>. `` We've changed our situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. We decided last night to begin pulling our people out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> back to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said from company headquarters in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` The situation apparently has changed overnight.'' <ORGANIZATION> Babcock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Wilcox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> also was moving out its staff of about 30 workers housed near <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Summer Palace and <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was attempting to withdraw an unspecified number of people from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. Several other companies also ordered employees to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and scrapped business trips there because of the growing fear of civil war. The intensified effort to get employees out reflected the deteriorating situation in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> since the weekend, when soldiers killed hundreds of unarmed pro-democracy demonstrators and other civilians. Protests have flared in other cities and it has become unclear if anyone is running the country. In another sign that the chaos may have a widening and profound economic impact, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks began reviewing credit to companies that do business with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and shortened time limits on new loans for trade and investment projects. `` We're doing something all banks are doing, just making sure any new commitments and any renewed commitments are kept very short-term, three months or less,'' said an official of one major <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bank, who asked not to be identified by name. An official of another big <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bank, who also requested anonymity, said: `` It's obvious that any sensible country-risk process would be operative under present conditions and commitments would be reviewed.'' <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> are among some of the prominent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banking companies with offices in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Many established representative offices there after relations were normalized a decade ago. The banks' main role is to expedite financing for joint ventures between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Chinese companies, but their direct loans to the Chinese are considered inconsequential and are n't reported in their accounting statements. A study by <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> estimated that total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank loan exposure in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was less than $ 1 billion. Nonetheless, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s government historically has been considered an excellent credit risk and many other foreign banks have loaned money to the country. The <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> research organization for commercial banks, estimates <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign debt totaled $ 42.4 billion at the end of 1988, of which 46 percent was in commercial bank loans. But the size of the debt compared with the country's overall economic output is small. `` A simple way of looking at it is that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> does n't have that much external commercial debt,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Layman </PERSON>, the institute's director for <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>
