<SECOND>PM-Children's TV,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Backs TV Station Targeted by Complaint About Children's Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> television station was not required to tell viewers that a toy maker was providing a children's program in exchange for free advertising time, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ruled The commission, in a ruling Tuesday that uphold's the common industry practice of `` barter'' sales, denied a complaint that <ORGANIZATION> KCOP-TV </ORGANIZATION> should have identified <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and TV syndicator Group W Productions as the sponsors of the animated cartoon show, `` He-Man and the Masters of the Universe.'' The Los-Angeles based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> had characterized the children's fantasy show as a non-stop depiction of `` He-Man'' logo and `` He-Man'' toy products, which are made by <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION>. The association said the barter arrangement, whereby <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> and Group W provided `` He-Man'' in exchange for two minutes of commercials distributed throughout <ORGANIZATION> KCOP </ORGANIZATION>'s children's program schedule, constituted a `` token payment,'' given the cost of producing the shows. The association said the producers spent $ 14 million to make 65 episodes of the program. The association, in a 1984 complaint, said Section 317 of the 1934 Communications Act requires that sponsors be identified whenever shows are provided free or with only nominal payment. But <ORGANIZATION> KCOP </ORGANIZATION> valued the commercial time at $ 300,000 a year. At the same time, it said that even if the payment were deemed `` token,'' Section 317 does not require sponsor identification when the sponsors are mentioned incidentally or not at all in the broadcast. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 denied the complaint, which had been joined by Action for Children's Television. <ORGANIZATION> NABB </ORGANIZATION> appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which in September 1987 remanded the case to the commission. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> denied the complaint again Tuesday. `` I guess it would be amazing if they had voted any other way,'' <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Charren </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, said of the 3-0 FCC ruling. She said the problem of advertising messages slipped into TV programs was `` one of the sorriest problems in all of broadcasting'' and that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> was saying they are `` going to let everything relax on the subject of advertising and editorial content.'' <ORGANIZATION> NABB </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Orme </PERSON> said his group would continue the fight. `` Whatever they have done, the court will have to approve,'' <PERSON> Orme </PERSON> said by telephone from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` I think eventually we will win this.'' <PERSON> Charren </PERSON>'s group, which helped write a bill pending in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that would re-impose limits on the amount of commercials on kids' shows, had said various broadcasters were violating FCC regulations by airing `` He-Man'' and seven other programs with substantial product tie-ins But the commission, in its 1985 ruling, said such the shows were not program-length commericials. The commission said the broadcasters `` had made a good faith determination that ` He-Man' and the other challenged programs possessed significant entertainment value for child audiences.'' The appeals court said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had interpreted Section 317 incorrectly and it instructed the agency to devise a standard to determine if Section 317 covers barter arrangements. In its ruling Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> admitted it erred when it said Section 317 applied only to broadcasts that were purely commercial in content. As for determining a standard, it said <ORGANIZATION> KCOP </ORGANIZATION> clearly had paid more than a nominal fee for `` He-Man,'' and Section 317, therefore, did not apply. The commission said it was not its business to `` engage in a detailed review of the adequacy of a broadcaster's payment in every case in which a program discount is alleged.'' It such such an approach would `` not necessarily further the statutory objectives, is unlikely to yield conclusive results and could require disclosures that cause substantial competitive harm to program suppliers.''
</TEXT>
