<HEAD>Dollar Edges Up, Share Prices Erase Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar edged up against the Japanese yen Wednesday morning, while share prices erased early gains and declined on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 5.07 points Tuesday, lost another 15.04 points, or 0.04 percent, to finish the morning session at 33,436.97. The dollar was trading at late morning at 142.88 yen, after opening lower at 142.45 yen, down 0.18 yen from Tuesday's close of 142.63 yen. The currency moved in the range of 142.40 to 143.00 yen. There were two main incentives in the foreign exchange market Wednesday: an incentive to buy due to the turmoil in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and one to sell sparked by a prime rate cut by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks, said <PERSON> Mitsuhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinugawa </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. He said the buying pressure due to the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was stronger. Investors tend to purchase dollars in times of uncertainty or crisis. `` Although Japanese investors do n't have a feeling of emergency, they are buying because of reactions overseas,'' he said. Many market players believe the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has been easing its monetary policy since major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks lowered their prime lending rate by 0.5 percentage point to 11 percent Monday. The trader said the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> intervened in the market by selling the dollar to support the yen. He said the amount of the bank's selling was unknown. The central bank does not comment on its monetary activities. On the stock market, the index fell marginally mainly due to selling for profit-taking after earlier gains, while the majority of market players remained on the sidelines. Other traders said turmoil in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> contributed to the wait-and-see mood in the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market. Japanese goverment has urged the swift evacuation of Japanese residents in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Many Japanese businesses in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have closed temporarily and brought employees back to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
