<HEAD>Hong Kong Stocks Up Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rose for a second day Wednesday on reports that the power struggle in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> may be ending. Trading was active, and brokers said they were surprised by the brisk activity. The Hang Seng Index of blue chips, which plummeted Monday in its worst loss since the worldwide market collapse in 1987, closed at 2,224.66 points, up 74.95 points. All blue chips registered gains. Volume totaled $ 296.5 million, up from $ 256.6 million Tuesday. On Monday, the index closed at 2,093.61 points, down 581.77 points from Friday. The drop was the worst since the 1987 international market collapse, when the index fell 1,120.99 points in one day. The <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the territory's largest bank, said it purchased shares for a third straight day to bolster the market. Brokers linked the market's activities to reports that Chinese troops responsible for attacks on pro-democracy demonstrators last Sunday were leaving <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>.
