<HEAD>Central Banker Says Cooperation Exists In Exchange Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> Governor <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Larosiere </PERSON> said Wednesday that the top seven industrialized nations continue to cooperate to keep exchange rates stable despite recent volatility in world markets. `` There has been some volatility over the past month,'' he told a bankers' forum. `` But what is important is that the international cooperation put in play since 1985 is still operating. `` The seven major countries are on the same wave-length and do understand the problems in the same fashion,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Larosiere </PERSON> said at the end of the three-day <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> attended by members of 99 comercial banks from 22 countries. He said the major task of the cooperation was to keep inflation down and sustain current economic growth. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Larosiere </PERSON> made the remarks to reporters after a closed meeting with private bankers and central bank governors or senior officials of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Sir <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Morse </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plc </ORGANIZATION>, moderated the central bankers' discussion and appeared later before reporters. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pohl </PERSON> participated in the closed-door panel but did not attend the press briefing. <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> said <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> had told the bankers it was difficult to correctly evaluate the recent rise in the dollar's value. But he said <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> indicated the dollar's rise appeared to be more of a market phenomenon than the result of fundamental economic factors. <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> said the central bank officials did not believe the dollar `` was likely to go raging on.'' The Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Leigh-Pemberton </PERSON> sai, `` The degree of currency stability is still reasonably satisfactory'' if seen from the view of whether it inhibits cross-border investment. He added that the markets had seemed to incorrectly imply that the international coordination policy on exchange rates `` had given up.'' <PERSON> Takeshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohta </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy governor for international relations, said policy coordination among the major nations does not always mean taking measures `` at the same time in the same direction.'' But he said, `` We should be able to move swifly when necessary.'' He and de Larosiere expressed concern over too much emphasis being placed on monetary policy to attempt to cut back economic imbalances.
