<HEAD>OPEC Works to Restart Talks on Production, Pricing Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with three grafs to UPDATE with several bargaining sessions
being held. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `We are ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> oil ministers today held a flurry of bargaining sessions to try to break a deadlock in negotiations for a new production and pricing agreement. `` We are working toward an agreement for sure,'' said Iraqi Oil Minister <PERSON> Issam </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Chalabi </PERSON>. The ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries held private meetings in their hotel rooms in late morning and early afternoon. They took a break after lunch and planned further discussions in late afteroon. `` We are consulting with each other and hope to reach an agreement,'' said <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>'s minister, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> <PERSON> bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Thani </PERSON>. He predicted a deal could be struck within the next two days. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> raised the possibility that all 13 ministers would gather at cartel headquarters later in the day to resume their formal strategy session. The ministers opened their mid-year conference on Monday, then broke up to bargain privately. The talks have stalled over a Kuwaiti demand for a much larger share of any increase in cartel production in the last half of the year. Other members, including influential <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, want the increase shared proportionately among all the members. `` A lot of work needs to be done,'' Iranian Oil Minister <PERSON> Gholamreza </PERSON> <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` We need about one or two days for consultations,'' <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> said. A delegate from one nation, who demanded anonymity, said, `` It's a deadlock. The ministers seemed in agreement on lifting their production cap to 19.5 million barrels a day, or at most 20 million barrels a day, in the last six months of the year. The ceiling in the January-June period is 18.5 million barrels a day. The ministers also appeared to have settled on retaining their benchmark price of $ 18 a barrel. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> had recommended getting rid of the target price. The cartel late last year agreed on its supply ceiling of 18.5 million barrels a day for the January-June period, well under output levels at that time. Cutbacks earlier in the year helped drive prices beyond the cartel's $ 18 benchmark. Prices have eased a bit recently as <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> has turned up its production. But the price of a basket of crudes monitored by the cartel was still more than 40 percent above the level of late November. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the contract for July delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, has been trading at more than $ 20 a 42-gallon barrel. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, reported that the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations lifted their crude production by 500,000 barrels a day in May to 21 million barrels, the highest so far this year. `` This was primarily the result of higher production in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, partly offset by a small decline in Iranian and Ecuadorian production,'' it said. The slippage in <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s output, it said, was due to a landslide that damaged the country's main oil pipeline. The agency's Monthly Oil Market Report predicted demand for the cartel's oil would rise in the second half of the year to about 20.85 million barrels a day. The agency previously estimated demand for the period at 20.4 million barrels a day.
</TEXT>
