<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 new grafs to UPDATE with early stock activity,
editing to conform. Picks up 7th graf, There had...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> shares shot higher in early trading today in response to a $ 6.5 billion takeover offer by <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cellular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The $ 120-a-share unsolicitated offer, disclosed after stock trading closed late Tuesday, would solidify <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>'s position as the nation's largest cellular telephone company. In national over-the-counter trading early today, <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> was up $ 24.25 a share to $ 127.25. <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> rose $ 2.50 to $ 45.75 a share. <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>, which is LIN's largest shareholder with a 9.8 percent stake, has franchises serving customers in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>. New York-based LIN operates seven network-affiliated television stations and has interests in cellular systems serving <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> It also owns a specialty publishing house that produces hard-cover tourist guides for hotel rooms. <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement it would `` study the offer carefully and act in the best interests of its shareholders.'' There had been speculation for months that <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> would launch an offer for LIN. LIN announced two weeks ago that its board had approved in principle spinning off all of the stock in a new subsidiary that would own its TV stations. It said it would operate its cellular operations along with a specialty publishing business as a separate company. LIN said the move was made for operating and strategic reasons due to the differences in the nature of the television and cellular-phone industries. The <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> proposal was seen by industry analysts as a recognition of the premium that the stock market has placed on the fast-growing cellular business. `` Given the regional geographic and operational nature of the cellular business, the logic of combining our two companies is compelling,'' <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> said in a letter to Lin Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pels </PERSON>. In the letter, <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> called the $ 6.5 billion bid `` the highest price per ` pop' in the history of our -LRB- cellular -RRB- industry.'' Pop, a yardstick in the industry, refers to market area populations multiplied by percentage ownership in the cellular systems serving those areas. <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>'s cellular telephone systems serve 50 million pops, while <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> serves more than 18 million pops. `` The next stage in the development of American cellular communications must be the rationalization of the many disconnected fragments of our industry,'' the <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> letter said. `` The McCaw-LIN combination would hasten that process. ... We would thus advance the effort to provide a truly national cellular network for American consumers.'' LIN's TV stations are <ORGANIZATION> KXAS </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort-Worth-Dallas </LOCATION>; WISH in <LOCATION> Inidianpolis </LOCATION>; WOTV in the <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, area; WAVY in <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roads </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> KXAN </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; WAND in central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>; and WANE in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. Last year LIN earned $ 82 million on revenue of $ 226 million.
