<HEAD>Turmoil in China Continues to Affect Grain Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures opened lower this morning on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> again was on the minds of traders, as the unrest there raises concern there will be reduced demand by that nation for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat, according to <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Feltes </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Forecasts for dryer weather in winter crop areas is expected to allow farmers to move ahead with the harvest, putting added pressure on wheat prices. The announcement yesterday of the sale of 300-thousand metric tons of corn to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> may offer limited support to corn prices. In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 2 -RCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.86 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1 -RCB- cents lower with July at $ 2.59 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1 -LCB- cent lower with July at $ 1.61 a bushel and soybeans were a -LCB- cent to 2 cents lower with July at $ 7.12 a bushel. Livestock and meat prices were higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .30 cent higher with June at 68.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .43 cent higher with August at 79.10 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .17 cent higher with June at 48.32 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .40 cent lower to .15 cent higher with July at 30.60 cents a pound. Livestock and pork futures settled lower Tuesday.
