<HEAD>Union Election July 26 and July 27</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> have agreed to a union election at the plant July 26-27 It will be the first vote on union representation since production began at the plant southeast of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> in 1983. The plant, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s only one in this country, manufactures light pickup trucks and Sentra cars. The agreement Tuesday came after three days of testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in which the parties argued over which employees would be eligible to vote. Union officials have made the plant a priority. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> filed a petition with the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> May 18 to hold the election. Union organizers said about 2,400 of <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s 3,200 workers are eligible to join the union. Under the agreement, the collective voting unit will include all hourly production and maintenance employees _ or technicians _ including the 176 lead technicians and maintenance apprentices. Excluded are all other personnel, including office, clerical, professional, managerial, contract labor, guards and supervisors.
