<HEAD>Eastern in Talks with American on South American Routes</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to UPDATE with comment from American spokesman;
picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, Wall Street ...; ADDS byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Strikebound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is in negotiations to sell its <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> routes to rival <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said today. `` We have talked to American,'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> He said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> also has had talks on the routes with other airlines since announcing its plan to rebuild as a smaller carrier and sell around $ 1.8 billion in assets separately. <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> declined to identify the other carriers interested in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> network or to disclose <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s asking price. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, a spokesman for American at its headquarters in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, would n't confirm that the talks had taken place although he acknowledged American's general interest in Eastern assets. `` We're looking at things that might be for sale,'' he said. Wall Street analysts have estimated the value of the South American routes at around $ 150 million. Any sales of Eastern assets must be approved by the federal bankruptcy court. Eastern sought bankruptcy protection from creditors on March 9, five days after pilots and flight attendants joined striking ground workers represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union in a walkout that virtually grounded the airline. The court recently approved the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s prized Northeast shuttle to developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for $ 365 million. For American, the nation's largest airline, a purchase of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> routes would bolster its strategy to expand overseas operations. American, which recently added new flights to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, also has expressed interest in <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> routes.
