<HEAD>OPEC Appears to Reach Tentative Output Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with apparent agreement on production, edits throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> oil ministers today reached a tentative agreement to raise their production a modest amount to keep prices strong in the coming months. The ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries held a flurry of meetings to try to wrap up an agreement. Venezuelan Oil Minister <PERSON> Celestino </PERSON> <PERSON> Armas </PERSON>, asked if a deal had been struck, replid, `` Yes, of course.'' <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> said the new production ceiling would be 19.5 million barrels a day. The current cap stands at 18.5 million barrels for the first six months of the year. But the cartel, according to analysts, has been producing above that level in recent months. As a result, analysts say an increase of about a million barrels in the supply cap should keep crude prices _ and consumers' gasoline prices _ steady. Further details of the accord were not immediately available. It was unclear whether the agreement would span six months or be for a shorter period of time. It also was not immediately known how the ministers had dealt with <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s demand for a higher production share. The ministers opened their mid-year conference on Monday, then broke up to bargain privately. The talks stalled Tuesday largely due to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s demand for a much larger share of any increase in cartel production in the last half of the year. Other members, including influential <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, want the increase shared proportionately among all the members. The ministers also appeared to have settled on retaining their benchmark price of $ 18 a barrel. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> had recommended getting rid of the target price. The cartel late last year agreed on its supply ceiling of 18.5 million barrels a day for the January-June period, well under output levels at that time. Cutbacks earlier in the year helped drive prices beyond the cartel's $ 18 benchmark. Prices have eased a bit recently as <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> has turned up its production. But the price of a basket of crudes monitored by the cartel was still more than 40 percent above the level of late November. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the contract for July delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, has been trading at more than $ 20 a 42-gallon barrel. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, reported that the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations lifted their crude production by 500,000 barrels a day in May to 21 million barrels, the highest so far this year. The agency's Monthly Oil Market Report predicted demand for the cartel's oil would rise in the second half of the year to about 20.85 million barrels a day. The agency previously estimated demand for the period at 20.4 million barrels a day.
</TEXT>
