<HEAD>Voters Decide To Close Nuclear Power Plant; Child-Care Measure Nixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: NEW thruout to UPDATE with shutdown beginning; PICKS UP 13th
graf, `But supporters ...' Also moved on general news wired</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rancho Seco nuclear plant began shutting down today after voters for the first time in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history decided to close a working reactor. With all precincts reporting, there were 111,867 votes, or 53.4 percent, against a measure that would have kept the plant operating, and 97,460, or 46.6 percent, in favor. About 40 percent of registered voters turned out. Tuesday's vote was not binding on the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the 15-year-old plant, but a majority of its elected board members had promised to abide by the will of the people. `` The plant is in the process of being shut down today,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>, a Rancho Seco spokesman. <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> said the mood is `` pretty somber'' at <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>, where the jobs of many of the 1,500 to 2,000 employees and contractors are in jeopardy. How many of those workers will be laid off is uncertain, <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION> General Manager <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said he would put the plant into `` hot shutdown,'' in which the reactor is operable but producing no electricity. <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION> will then confer with the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on putting the reactor in cold shutdown and beginning the decommissioning, he said. He said he had already informed the <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION> directors of his plan to shut down the plant and would not seek their approval. He lamented the vote and said decommissioning and dismantling could cost more than $ 210 million. Public Citizen, a group formed in 1971 by <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, said in a statement that the vote `` marks the beginning of the end for nuclear power in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s love affair with the atom is over,'' it said. Meanwhile in Fremont, a city of 165,000 on the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, a child-care tax measure that was touted as the first of its kind in the nation was trounced at the polls. Measure B, which would have taxed residents and businesses to pay for citywide child care, was supported by many working parents, feminists and business leaders but opposed by activists who targeted senior citizens, older families and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> groups. With all precincts reporting, there were 3,671 votes in favor and 12,697 against. The measure needed a two-thirds majority to pass. Voters in the utility district that includes most of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Placer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> gave <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> a reprieve in June 1988 but put it on probation until Tuesday's vote. Critics claimed the plant 25 miles from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s capital is unsafe and has a poor operating record. They also expressed anger at rising utility bills and pointed to a $ 400 million repair bill after a 1985 overcooling accident that caused a two-year outage. But supporters said the 913-megawatt plant's bad days were over thanks to an overhaul and hiring of new managers. The expense of decommissioning Rancho Seco, together with the higher cost of buying electricity from outside sources, is expected to boost utility bills, but estimates vary widely as to how much. <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> predicted an initial increase of 7.5 percent in 1990. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dellinger </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the the campaign to keep the plant open, called the vote `` a big mistake.'' `` It was based on the historical performance of <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> and frustration with <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION>, without considering the ramifications of shutting the plant that supplies half the power of the community,'' she said. The vote Tuesday marked the first time in the nation that voters chose to shut down an operating nuclear power plant, according to <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Nuclear opponents have won elections preventing new nuclear plants from being built in some states. The nuclear industry, fearful that a closure vote could strengthen nuclear opponents, raised $ 580,000 for the campaign to keep <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> open. Opponents, including the Campaign <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> environmental group formed by <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> and his estranged wife, actress <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON>, raised $ 111,000, according to the latest campaign reports.
</TEXT>
