<FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Economy     06-07 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economist Says 1988 Inflation Was 8-9 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet inflation was 8 percent to 9 percent last year, about double previous government estimates, a top economist said Wednesday. <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>, an economic adviser to President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said a 4 percent to 5 percent increase in official prices combined with another 4 percent rise caused by excess money consumers ca n't spend due to shortages. Deputy Finance Minister <PERSON> Vyacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Senchagov </PERSON> termed <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>'s estimate too high He said the official estimate for 1988 price increases was 2.7 percent to 2.8 percent, not 4 percent to 5 percent. The two Soviet economists spoke at a conference `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the 1990s'' sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s Economicheskaya Gazeta and the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. They said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is hampered by lack of proper statistics to determine the actual rate of inflation. Soviet officials denied for years that inflation existed, but under the influence of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms have acknowledged inflation and begun to talk about how to combat it. Last October, deputy statistics director <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Belov </PERSON> said wages rose 6.7 percent in the first nine months of 1988, but real income rose only 3.5 percent. But he refused to term the difference a rate of inflation. <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON> said Soviet economic reformers were hampered when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took power in 1985 by a lack of understanding of the severity of problems. Economic managers made the situation worse by boosting spending on housing, education and health but implementing no cuts, he said. <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON> said that aggravated a budget deficit, officially set at 35 billion rubles, or $ 56 billion, this year. But economists said including money the government borrows from its savings, the deficit is more than 100 billion rubles, or $ 160 billion. <PERSON> Senchagov </PERSON> said the Soviet government plans to attack the deficit by slashing construction expenditures and relying on a drive for efficiency for added production. Plans for 80 billion rubles, or $ 140 billion, in capital investments will be halved, and 390 new construction projects will be eliminated, he said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> already has announced a 14 percent defense budget cut. But <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, who also spoke at the conference, said he saw `` every prospect that the deficit will increase.'' He called for the government to stop a flood of ill-considered economic decrees. `` They've come out quickly, they've been poorly coordinated, in some cases fighting with each other,'' he said. `` That's basically because the reform has gone half-way.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrialist <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>, who began his business career with a deal with Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> to supply grain in 1921, told Western businessmen that flexibility would pay off in dealings with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` Above all, you've got to have patience,'' the 91-year-old <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> said. `` I think it's worth it because they have a huge population ... and they need everything.''
</TEXT>
