 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> continued its expansion Wednesday, announcing it would spend up to $ 550 million to build one maintenance facility and expand another to service the airline's growing fleet. American Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crandall </PERSON> said the carrier will build a $ 400 million maintenance and service facility at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alliance </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, ending a hard-fought battle between <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> that had involved the governors of both states. <PERSON> Crandall </PERSON> also announced a $ 150 million expansion of the airline's current maintenance facility in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Alliance </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> is 12 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, where American is based and operates its largest American is the nation's biggest airline. The Alliance maintenance center will be built on 207 acres and include a series of hangars, shops and support buildings. Initial construction will start next January and cost about $ 222 million. The first phase should be completed by the end of 1991, the airline said. Initial employment will be about 2,500 people, but could exceed 4,500 by completion. <PERSON> Crandall </PERSON> said American will spend $ 150 million to add a hangar at <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, which will increase employment there by 1,600 people. The <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> facility, already undergoing a $ 250 million expansion, currently employs some 6,100 people. The larger maintenance operation has become necessary to service <LOCATION> American </LOCATION>'s expanding fleet, which will grow from about 480 jets currently to about 752 by the mid-1990s. The carrier recently announced several multi-billion-dollar contracts for new jets for both its main operation and its commuter airline subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION>'s parent, recently announced record first-quarter earnings of $ 101 million. <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> plans a $ 95 million expansion of its headquarters building in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> and is working on plans to build a $ 1 billion terminal at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>.
