<HEAD>Mexico, Creditors To Continue Debt Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and its commercial bank creditors agreed Wednesday to reconvene debt-reduction talks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Friday. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s undersecretary of finance, <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurria </PERSON>, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, co-chairman of a bank-negotiating committee, said in a statement that a two-hour meeting in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> `` set the stage for rapid progress in the negotiations with the commercial banks.'' The meeting coincided with a three-day <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> attended here by members of 99 comercial banks from 22 countries. After the debt meeting with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> executive, told reporters, `` We have gotten a better understanding of what type of funding and guarantees the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> are willing to provide. `` We've heard from the official institutions, now we will have to work out the details.'' <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has criticized the commercial banks' attitude toward debt rescheduling. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> owes $ 74 billion to about 500 commercial banks. Its overall foreign debt totals $ 107.4 billion and is the second-highest in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, behind that of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. The joint statement said the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> had explained `` the nature and extent of their financial support for debt and debt service reduction transactions to be negotiated by <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the commercial banks.'' <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is viewed as a test case for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's Third World debt strategy, which calls on commercial banks to forgive a substantial part of their loans to heavily indebted countries in return for guarantees the rest will be repaid But it did not specify how much financial support the lending agencies had offered. <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> managing director <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> told reporters at a separate news briefing that the <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> meeting was `` very positive'' and provided an opportunity for the international lending agencies to inform <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> officials and the commercial banks their view in detail.
