<SECOND>AM-Paris Air Show, 1st Ld-Writethru,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Jet Makes Internationl Debut at Paris Air Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to CORRECT plane designation to SR-71,
sted SR-1, in 2nd and 8th grafs; picks up 9th pvs: First delivered...;
Also moved on general news wires</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With its engines spitting fire and its pencil-thin nose outlined against gray skies, the sleek <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spy plane set down here Wednesday for its debut at the world's most famous air show. The SR-71 reconnaissance jet has never been displayed outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but it will be a featured attraction at the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Air Show, where it will stand beside flying machines from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other nations. More than 365,000 people are expected to attend. The air show, which is to be opened Thursday by President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, will include a celebration of the 20th anniversary of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s walk on the moon. The show, held every two years, is to the air industry what the <LOCATION> Cannes </LOCATION> film festival is to movies: a glitzy gathering where products are promoted, aviation stars strut before reporters, deals are announced and others are made. More than 1,000 exhibitors from 34 countries will be at the show this year, and 140,000 industry professionals are expected. They cut deals under the roar of aircraft flying nonstop demonstrations overhead. Even before the show officially opened, the rainy skies over <ORGANIZATION> Pari </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourget </PERSON> airfield were filled with jets performing feats that awed even jaded professionals in the midst of last-minute preparations for the displays. After setting down in the SR-71, known as the Blackbird because of its two vertical stabilizers and sleek profile, the pilot and systems officer climbed out of the aircraft dressed like astronauts. Before a crowd of photographers, they unfurled the blue, white and red French flag. First delivered to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> in 1966, the plane was developed by <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as a long-range, advanced strategic reconnaissance aircraft. It is one of the fastest and highest-flying in the skies today. It cruises at altitudes above 80,000 feet and at speeds of about 3,100 feet per second _ more than three times faster than sound. The aircraft carries systems capable of surveying 100,000 square miles in one hour, placing it in direct competition with newer, more sophisticated satellites. The Soviets also gave a glimmer Wednesday of what their planes can do. Their Soukhoi-27 _ being shown alongside two MiG-29 jet fighters and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> space shuttle Buran _ swooped, spun, and flipped high overhead. At one moment, the high-speed plane seemed to stall dead still, pulled its nose straight up, and flipped over on its back. <PERSON> Apollon </PERSON> <PERSON> Systvov </PERSON>, the Soviet Aeronautics Industry Minister, later told a news conference the relaxation of international tensions and more openness in his country made it possible for greater participation by the Soviets at this year's show. `` We want to give you an idea of the level of Soviet technology and the expertise of our pilots,'' he said. `` But we do not deny the commercial aspects and know there is a market for our aircraft.'' The Soviet officials said he expected his country's space shuttle to be the star of the show. He said Buran, which made its first unmanned flight last November, has commercial possibilities as a satellite launcher. However, he said his government will continue launching its satellites with rockets. Buran's next flight is to be in 1991, he said.
