<FIRST>u f AM-OPEC Bjt   06-07 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, Bjt,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Finalizes Production Agreement; Maintains $18 Benchmark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers struck a deal Wednesday night to restrain production in order to keep bolstering oil prices, but crude futures tumbled in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading on indications that some nations would continue cheating. The accord, signed by all 13 members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries in the sixth day of sometimes-tense bargaining, lifts <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s official production ceiling to 19.5 million barrels a day in the July-December period from the 18.5 million barrels in effect for January-June. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the July contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate _ the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude _ closed down 79 cents at $ 19.67 a barrel. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> is limiting production in an attempt to support a price of $ 18 a 42-gallon barrel in the last half of the year. Analysts say <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> has been pumping an estimated 21 million barrels a day in recent weeks, so the producing nations would have to curb output to meet the new supply level. `` Everybody is supposed to rein in production levels,'' said <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Rilwanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON>. If they do, analysts say, crude prices and gasoline prices at the pump should hold steady. At their final strategy session, the ministers agreed that a special committee would meet in September to review the oil market. `` If it is found that the demand warrants an increase in the ceiling, then this can be raised to 20 million barrels per day or any other level agreed upon,'' read a statement released by the ministers. Any adjustments would take effect Oct. 1. Under the accord, the 1 million barrel increase in the production ceiling will be distributed proportionately among all members. Talks had stalled Tuesday over <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s demand for a greater share of any increase in the ceiling, and some <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> delegates indicated that nation did not accept its new quota. <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON>, asked about <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s position, told a news conference, `` <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> signed the resolution.'' But Kuwaiti Oil Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON> later told reporters he had made a reservation to the agreement. He said he would give details on Thursday. A Kuwaiti delegate, who demanded anonymity, said his government does n't feel bound by the quota assigned it under the new accord. Another Kuwaiti delegate, who also sought anonymity, said <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> wrote those reservations in the margin of the agreement signed by the ministers. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> has been pumping well over its <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> quota. If it continues doing so, it would add to the world supply and possibly help weaken prices. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> also has persistently produced more than its ceiling. There was no indication whether it intended to adhere to its new target, although a <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> delegate said the U.A.E. verbally expressed its reservations in the closed meeting. Prices have risen from near-term lows reached in late 1988, partly due to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> cutbacks earlier in the year and to accidents that temporarily disrupted supplies in key oil-producing regions of the world. The average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> exceeded the $ 18 a barrel reference earlier in the year and prices are up more than 40 percent since last November. In its insistence on a greater share of the increase, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> was pitted against influential <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the world's largest crude exporters. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> walked out of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting hand-in-hand with <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> in an apparent attempt to signal their differences were patched up. <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> said several times during the bargaining that he wanted to see prices rising. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, however, is concerned that higher prices will erode the cartel's share of the oil market to non-OPEC countries, analysts say. Higher prices encourage more production and more exploration by producers. The ministers' statement said they intend to talk to independent producing nations `` with a view to soliciting their cooperation in support of market stability.'' Some of those countries agreed earlier in the year to curtail their output some to help bolster prices. Under the agreement, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s new quota will be 4.8 million barrels a day, up from 4.5 million barrels. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> will have quotas of 2.8 million barrels a day, up from 2.6 million barrels in the January-June period. Other quotas for the July-December period are: <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, 733,000 barrels per day; <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, 242,000 barrels; <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, 175,000, and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, 1.3 million barrels. Others included <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, 1.1 million barrels; <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, 1.1 million barrels; <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, 1.4 million barrels; <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, 329,000 barrels; <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, 1 million barrels, and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, 1.7 million barrels.
</TEXT>
