e in you ... We do n't believe your numbers','' said <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON>. The market initially displayed some strength when it was announced that the new <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production ceiling was lower than the 20 million to 21 million barrels a day some analysts had anticipated. But doubts about <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to abide by its accord created an opportunity for traders to sell and collect profits. Selling was dominated by large commercial energy brokers, <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON> said.
