<FIRST>r f AM-WasteSettlement     06-07 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waste Settlement,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Company To Pay $2.75 Million in Toxic Waste Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An energy company has agreed to pay a reported $ 2.75 million to eight families who discovered in 1987 that their homes sat atop a toxic waste dump, officials said Wednesday. The settlement was announced at a meeting attended by the families, local officials, mediators who helped construct the deal and representatives of <ORGANIZATION> Colonial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which once dumped on the site. Colonial Gas acknowledged its coal-gasification byproducts were dumped decades ago where the families' homes were later built. Railroad debris, leather, hospital bandages, bottles, light bulbs, drums, metal paint cans, ash, paint, dye and rubber shoe scraps were among the waste dumped at the site when it was known as Costa's Dump from the 1920s to'40s. The families reported seeing blue soil and camphor-like odors in 1987 to the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION>. Under the settlement, Colonial Gas will buy the homes, pay damages and finance the continuing cleanup costs at the site near the <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in this city about 35 miles north of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The agreement will provide each family with approximately $ 250,000, the parties said. Colonial Gas reportedly also has agreed to pay $ 750,000 to the <ORGANIZATION> DEQE </ORGANIZATION> for the testing and fencing and cleaning the site. Colonial Gas attorney <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Child </PERSON> the cleanup would not begin for at least a year. He said the houses either will be razed, transported to another location or left on the site during cleanup. As a provision of the agreement, the families will not be allowed to seek further damages for future health problems. In a report, the DEQE found the site `` does not currently pose an immediate threat to the health or welfare of abutters to the property.'' But it said the area was unsafe to live on and `` remedial actions were necessary'' to ensure the protection of the families and future users of the site. The families, whose members complained about health problems including headaches and asthma, were reolcated together to a condominium complex in another town. The mediation took six months.
