<HEAD>NLRB Orders Sewing Machine Maker To Reinstate Workers After Eight
Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: DELETES extraneous garble after 3rd graf, picks up 4th graf,
Labor lawyers...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sewing machine company that closed its <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> plant in 1981 has been ordered to rehire the entire workforce and make up eight years of lost earnings for up to 190 employees, officials said Wednesday. Jubilant workers hailed the decision by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> as vindication of their claim that the company, <ORGANIZATION> Reece </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Waltham </LOCATION>, moved operations to <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and overseas to escape a costly union contract. `` Maybe this will show people that unions hang on and defend people, we're not just dues collectors,'' said <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ofria </PERSON>, president of the 2,000-member Local 1596 of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, which represented the Reece employees. It's not clear what how much total back pay might be owed. The <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> must hold a separate hearing to determine that. Labor lawyers said the decision did not chart new legal ground but appeared to mark a shift from the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION>'s decisions under former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, when the board steadily strengthened management rights at the expense of unions. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abate </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reece </PERSON>'s president and chief executive officer, said the company would appeal the order, which could cost it millions of dollars, in court. The exact amount of back pay remains to be determined through a separate <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> hearing. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON>, an attorney in the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> office, said the hearing wo n't be held until after the company's appeal <PERSON> Reece </PERSON>, a 108-year-old firm that had sales of $ 59.5 million last year, announced in April 1981 it would close the plant, which made industrial machinery for sewing buttonholes and pockets. Approximately 190 workers were laid off, and the operations were transferred to plants in <LOCATION> Gorham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Leiden </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. A three-member <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> panel issued its decision in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on May 31, but it was not received by the parties until this week. By a 2-1 vote, the panel overturned a 1982 decision by an administrative law judge who had found that the company had a contractual right to shut the plant. The <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> interpreted the contract more narrowly, ruling that neither a management-rights clause nor a paragraph covering severance pay eliminated the company's obligation to bargain with the union over the plant's future. `` By refusing to bargain collectively and in good faith with the union ... the company has engaged in unfair labor practices,'' <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> and board member <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> Cracraft </PERSON> wrote. The <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> ordered <PERSON> Reece </PERSON> to make up any difference between what the workers have earned over the past eight years and what they would have earned at the plant. Workers at the Reece plant earned an average of more than $ 9 an hour, and many who were paid at piece rates made more than $ 14 an hour. The company also was required to offer the <LOCATION> Waltham </LOCATION> employees immediate reinstatement to their former jobs, and if those jobs no longer exist, to equivalent positions at the company's other plants. The board said the company would have to pay the workers' moving costs and, if necessary, make jobs for them by dismissing employees hired after the plant closing. The <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> did not explain why it took nearly seven years to decide the case. However, lawyers said the board has been struggling with a significant backlog, and delays of three years or longer are common. The dissenting board member, <PERSON> Wilford </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON>, argued the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> had waived its right to bargain over the plant's future by agreeing to put the management-rights and severance pay clauses in the contract. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> labor lawyer, called the decision `` a good precedent from a union perspective.'' `` It sounds like this kind of a decision _ in which the board is not willing to buy into a waiver-by-contract argument _ is shifting away from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years, when they found waivers in everything,'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said.
