<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday it would buy Ohio-based <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which the retailing giant had said it wanted to unload. The price was undisclosed. `` We do n't anticipate it being a significant loss or gain for us,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Muir </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> at the retailer's <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> headquarters. The casualty insurance subsidiary, headquartered in <LOCATION> Westerville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, lost $ 7 million on premiums of $ 168 million last year, about 80 percent of it in auto insurance, <PERSON> Muir </PERSON> said. It had about 350,000 policies in force. Metropolitan Property and Casualty, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, earned $ 40 million on premium income of $ 543 million last year. It had 1.1 million policies, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostrowski </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> will keep its life insurance subsidiary, <PERSON> Muir </PERSON> said. Unlike rival <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Penney </PERSON> had been unable to produce a satisfactory package of financial services to sell through its stores, <PERSON> Muir </PERSON> said. `` The direction of our company is to become a department store. We found that people did not choose to make financial decisions at the same time they were shopping for apparel,'' he said. Ms. <PERSON> Ostrowski </PERSON> said Metropolitan would probably keep <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>'s over-the-counter insurance sales force in place for up to 18 months after the expected closing of the sale later this summer, then fold those operations into <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION>'s existing sales force of agents, direct-marketing specialists and <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> 21 real estate agents Less certain was the future of 770 employees at <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in suburban <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> Metropolitan would keep a service center there, but staffing levels had not been decided, Ms. <PERSON> Ostrowski </PERSON> said. Metropolitan, which writes most of its business in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, wants to expand to the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Ostrowski </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> wrote nearly half its premiums in 1987 in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, with other significant amounts in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> A.M. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an industry rating service. Best gave <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>'s insurance operations a B-plus rating last year, which one expert said is generally the lowest rating accepted by insurance brokers. Metropolitan improved from B-plus to A-minus.
