<FIRST>r f BC-IMF-ThirdWorldDebt     06-07 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-IMF-Third World Debt,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Debt Dropped $12.4 Billion in 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Debts of the Third World to commercial banks dropped by $ 12.4 billion last year, partly because banks used the money to buy local assets, according to new figures from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. The fund did not give totals in its monthly <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> Memorandum, distributed this week, or the debts of individual countries. It classes 130 countries in the Third World as `` developing.'' According to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, its sister organization, Third World debt now comes to $ 1.3 trillion. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON>, the fund's managing director, said banks hold about 60 percent of it Most of the rest is owed to governments and intergovernment bodies such as the fund itself. Both organizations, owned by the same 151 governments, have pledged to help reduce the debt further, as urged by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. They are pressing private banks to go along by forgiving some of the debt in return for assurances that interest will be paid promptly on what is left. There was a drop of $ 17.3 billion in the amount owed by the 15 countries singled out as specially troubled by Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> when he was secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> calculates that they owe about $ 520 billion. They include <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, where price rises linked to debt have brought bloody rioting recently. According to the fund, the reduction in the debt owed to the banks is not due to repayments but to other operations. The banks disposed of $ 8.7 billion worth by using what the fund calls official conversions. These include conversion of the debt from dollars or other hard currency into the money of the debtor country, and then buying shares of stock in local industry. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> has taken the lead in these `` debt-equity swaps.'' In <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and other countries the swaps have been criticized as contributing both to inflation and to the sale of too many important assets to foreigners. The banks also sold off at a discount debts with a face value of $ 8 billion. Some Third World debt brings as little as 10 cents on the dollar in the market. After a sale, the debtor country still owes the full face value to the new purchaser, but nothing to the bank. In addition to the 15, more than 100 other Third World countries are classified by the fund as `` developing.'' In 1987, the debts of all of them to the banks increased by $ 18.7 billion. Debtor countries complain mostly about the burden of interest payments. <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> reported last week that debtors fell another $ 11 billion behind on their payments in 1988. These are largely interest payments, since few debtors have paid back much principal since 1982.
</TEXT>
