<HEAD>MAI Basic Says Prime Computer Has Beefed Up Its `War Chest'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Four </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it had filed a lawsuit opposing the postponement of <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting, where it plans to wage a proxy battle for control of the company. The suit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, seeks to compel the Natick-based computer maker to hold the meeting June 14, as previously scheduled. Prime announced Tuesday that it would delay the meeting until July 26 to give its stockholders time to consider MAI's recent reduction in its hostile tender offer, from $ 20 a share in cash to approximately $ 19 a share in a mixture of cash and securities. MAI is a <LOCATION> Tustin </LOCATION>, Calif.-based computer company controlled by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBow </PERSON>. It has been pursuing Prime, a maker of minicomputers and computer-aided design equipment, since November. On June 1, <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> cut its bid to $ 19.50 in cash for about 75 percent of the shares on a fully diluted basis, plus securities with a face value of $ 21 per share for the remaining 25 percent of Prime's stock. Since the securities are likely to trade at less than face value, many analysts have valued the new offer at $ 18 to $ 19 a share. MAI also said Wednesday that Prime has put an additional $ 5 million into a war chest to oppose MAI's hostile takeover bid and defend `` tin'' and `` golden'' parachute arrangements. Prime previously announced charges totaling $ 15.4 million for legal, investment banking and other costs associated with fighting MAI's tender offer. In a filing Monday with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, Prime said its board authorized a $ 5 million letter of credit to cover legal costs for defending its employee protection and executive retention agreements. Those agreements, known generically as tin and golden parachutes, provide payments ranging from a few hundred to many thousands of dollars to soften the landing for ordinary workers and top executives who bail out of the company after a takeover. MAI has claimed the arrangements could cost the company up to $ 170 million and has pledged to fight them in court. MAI charged Wednesday that Prime has `` apparently deliberately chosen not to publicize this new $ 5 million commitment.'' Prime spokesman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gavaghan </PERSON> declined to comment directly on MAI's statement. Prime stock closed unchanged at $ 16.50 a share in composite trading Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>.
